<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrat-Bush,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice Chair Of House Democratic Caucus Warns Against Overconfidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Democrats start packing their bags for
Atlanta and the coronation of Michael Dukakis, Ohio Democratic
congresswoman Mary Rose Oakar is hoping they leave one item behind:
overconfidence about beating George Bush.
   ``Everyone thinks he's sort of wimpy. I don't see him that
way,'' Oakar said in an interview. ``He's a war hero. Wait until
you see them pull all that stuff out.''
   ``I have some great anxieties that we think this is our year and
we're not going to have the zeal and lust to win that we should
have,'' said Oakar, the vice chair of the House Democratic Caucus,
which Dukakis will appear before on Wednesday.
   Oakar is worried the vice president is already making moves to
shore up relations with two groups never totally comfortable with
President Reagan: women and the elderly.
   The six-term Cleveland congresswoman, also a leader of the
party's platform committee, said the image of Bush as a preppy
milquetoast doesn't square with the popular and savvy GOP
politician she has come to know on Capitol Hill.
   At the annual House gym parties where Bush shows up to have his
picture taken with Democrats and Republicans alike, ``he's one of
the boys,'' said Oakar.
   ``Frankly, on a one-to-one basis, he is not the so-called
elitist type that he appears to be. ... He is much more appealing
in a smaller crowd than he is on Dan Rather's show,'' she said.
   ``I think George Bush is much more formidable than a lot of
people give him credit for,'' the liberal congresswoman said.
   Ohio, with its 23 electoral votes, is rated by both sides as a
key battleground. Ohio Sen. John Glenn has figured prominently in
speculation about possible running mates for Dukakis.
   ``Bush has been laying the groundwork for reconciling all of the
problems Reagan always had, such as the women's problem and the
elderly issue _ two areas that ought to be natural Democratic
constituencies,'' Oakar said.
</TEXT>
