<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Disclosure List,700</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are capsule summaries of the financial
disclosure statements for members of Congress who received
extensions to file their reports after the May 15 deadline.
   Income includes the official salary, honoraria earnings from
writing and speeches and other income such as dividends and
interest.
   Earnings by spouses and dependents are not included, nor are
holdings and liabilities of spouses and dependents covered.
   House members are permitted to keep honoraria earnings from
speeches and writings up to 30 percent of their salary. Senators
can keep up to 40 percent. The congressional salary received by the
members in this list was $87,483.
   Many members receive honoraria above the limit and donate the
excess to charity.
   In their financial disclosure forms, members are allowed to list
income, assets and liabilities by ranges instead of specific
figures. Some provide specific figures.
   In listing assets, representatives do not have to include their
personal residences and vehicles. Gifts, though listed, are not
counted in income figure given here.
