<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CongressionalJockeying     07-11 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congressional Jockeying,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers In Battle For Powerful Appropriations Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A battle is brewing behind the scenes on
Capitol Hill as three New England lawmakers fight for a single
vacancy on the powerful House Appropriations Committee.
   The struggle has taken on more importance than the usual
jockeying for coveted committee assignments because it pits two
Massachusetts Democrats who had been mentioned as possible
successors to Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis in 1990 _ Reps.
Joseph P. Kennedy II and Chester G. Atkins.
   Kennedy, Atkins and Rep. Bruce A. Morrison, D-Conn., began
lobbying fellow Democrats for their support in April just days
after Rep. Edward P. Boland, D-Mass., announced he would not seek a
19th term, according to another Massachusetts Democrat, Rep. Brian
Donnelly.
   Donnelly, a member of the House Steering and Policy Committee,
which recommends members for new committee assignments, confirmed
information obtained from various congressional sources.
   Donnelly and other lawmakers said the House Democratic
leadership has all but promised to keep Boland's appropriations
seat within New England, but only if the region's Democratic
members can rally behind one candidate. If they cannot, they risk
losing the seat.
   Seats on the Appropriations Committee are among the most coveted
in Congress because of its control over spending. Committee members
are well positioned to include federal money for favored home state
projects.
   Many consider Atkins the favorite. His home state of
Massachusetts boasts a majority of the region's Democratic House
members, and he could reasonably expect an added amount of loyalty
stemming from his position as chairman of the state party. The
second-term congressman is stressing his experience as chairman of
the Massachusetts Senate Ways and Means Committee.
   Kennedy is only a freshman, and it would be unusual for a member
so low on the seniority ladder to secure an appropriations seat.
But Kennedy is considered by some observers to be a ``wild card''
because of his family's legacy.
   ``There's no question when you're a Kennedy you bring special
advantages to the process. That's a fact of life,'' said Morrison,
who works with Kennedy on the House Banking Committee. ``He has
more clout than the average freshman.''
   Kennedy declined to comment.
   Morrison has been lobbying members aggressively, perhaps in the
hopes that he could put together a coalition of Connecticut
Democrats and other non-Massachusetts members while Kennedy and
Atkins split the Massachusetts vote, one lawmaker suggested.
   The battle has already had ramifications on the Massachusetts
gubernatorial race that is expected to develop for 1990 if Dukakis
does not lose his quest for the presidency and decide to seek a
fourth term at the Statehouse.
   Atkins' recent statement that he would not run for governor in
1990 was seen by many Democrats as an attempt to convince House
Speaker Jim Wright and New England lawmakers that he intends to
stay in the House, and therefore is deserving of the appropriations
seat.
   ``That's correct,'' Atkins said. ``They wanted to be assured
that whoever gets that seat that they have a long-term commitment
to the House. That's the kind of committee where when you get on it
and you work you become'' more effective over time. ``My colleagues
wanted to know that I was going to be in a position where I could
do that.''
   Atkins, in a recent interview, stressed that the competition has
been friendly and that all three members have discussed the
position among themselves.
   ``The campaign is being run in a very low-key way so that we can
avoid any kind of divisions that would make it difficult to keep
the seat in the region,'' he said. ``We've been able to maintain
very excellent relations with each other and cooperation with each
other. It's very polite, genteel and low key.''
   Donnelly said the contest is ``very much still up in the air.''
   ``Most members are not going to make commitments until after the
elections because these are very difficult personal decisions to
make. These are not political decisions, they're personal
decisions,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880711-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 0100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Disclosure Bjt   07-11 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Disclosure, Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outside Income Puts Glenn in Senate's `Millionaires' Club'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Glenn and Rep. George Miller rent
rooms, but that's about as far as that particular comparison can go.
   Glenn, the former astronaut from Ohio who is under consideration
for the Democratic vice presidential nomination, says his interests
in two hotel management companies brought him income of $287,349
last year.
   At the other end of the lodging business, Miller, a California
Democrat, collected between $5,000 and $15,000 in 1987 from three
House colleagues who rented rooms in his townhouse near the Capitol.
   These are some of the details contained in 1987 financial
disclosure statements filed recently by Glenn, Miller and a handful
of other lawmakers who received permission to submit their reports
after the May 15 deadline.
   Glenn's report, which like others gave most information only in
broad dollar ranges, showed that he remained one of the wealthiest
members of the Senate, which is frequently called ``the
millionaires' club.''
   Listing a myriad of investments, he reported assets of from
$7,753,163 to more than $15 million, with liabilities at no more
than $865,000. Glenn said his income last year was between
$1,280,906 and $2,704,480, including his congressional pay of
$87,483 and Marine Corps pension of $16,584.
   Miller reported earnings last year of from $122,397 to $132,397,
including his official salary, $29,914 in speaking and writing fees
and rent from roommates Marty Russo, D-Ill., Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., and Leon Panetta, D-Calif.
   Miller's only listed assets were his houses in Washington and
Martinez, Calif., worth a combined $200,000 to $500,000. His
liabilities, mortgages on the properties, were from $60,000 to
$115,000.
   His only reported gift was a membership in the Big ``C''
Athletic Club in Concord, Calif., worth $1,000.
   Patrick Leahy, the Vermont Democrat who chairs the Senate
Agriculture Committee, said he received $39,927 from speaking and
writing fees, with at least $24,959 coming from farm organizations
and agribusinesses.
   He also got free trips from the Chicago Board of Trade, the farm
commodities trading market, but the Windy City wasn't on the
itinerary. One Board of Trade trip took Leahy and his son to West
Palm Beach, Fla. Another transported the senator and his wife to
London.
   Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., reported $49,255 in speaking and
writing honoraria in 1987. His free trips, paid for by business
groups, took him to the mountain resort of White Sulphur Springs,
W.Va.; Sun Valley, Idaho; Ft. Myers, Fla.; Monterey, Calif.; and to
Salt Lake City for a charity skiing event.
   Among Quayle's reported gifts were $287 worth of golf
merchandise at the Kemper Open in suburban Maryland and $825 in
golfing gear from a constituent, professional golfer Fuzzy Zoeller
of New Albana, Ind.
   The depressed condition of U.S. oil and gas production was
evidenced by the disclosure statement filed by Sen. Malcolm Wallop,
R-Wyo. His petroleum leases on at least 912 acres of land brought
him just $74.42 in royalty payments.
   Wallop also reported income of at least $216,433, assets of at
least $1.46 million, liabilities of at least $500,000 and between
$995,000 and $1.9 million worth of sales in stocks and bonds.
   Even more active in the market was Rep. James Scheuer, D-N.Y.,
who bought from $5.6 million to $11.5 million in securities and
sold from $2.5 million to $4.8 million worth. He showed capital
gains ranging from $284,102 to $666,000 and dividend income of
$14,552 to $57,000.
   Rep. Robert Garcia's assets included a legal defense fund
containing between $5,000 and $15,000 to pay lawyers representing
him in the ongoing Wedtech defense contracting probe.
   The New York Democrat has been under investigation since
February 1987 but is ``hopeful and confident he'll be exonerated,''
said his spokesman, Bill Danvers. Garcia has not been indicted in
the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
