<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DominoChampionships     07-11 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Domino Championships,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mississippi Team, Missouri Man Capture Domino Titles</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0411 to correct winner's home state in
overline.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ANDALUSIA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Travis Newsome has been competing in the
World Championship Domino Tournament since 1978. His diligence
finally paid off.
   Newsome, of Kansas City, Mo., beat E.H. Edwards of Waldo, Ark.,
2-1 in an hourlong, best-of-three match Sunday to capture the
singles title. Newsome won $4,000, while Edwards got $1,500 for his
second-place finish.
   Newsome said he would use his prize money to defray some of the
expenses he has incurred traveling to the south Alabama town of
Andalusia, which has played host to the tournament since 1976.
   A Mississippi team won the doubles championship and $4,000.
James Morgan of Bassfield and Harold Marler of Clinton beat Ralph
Foster of Mesquite, Texas, and Daryl McClain of Summerall, Miss.,
2-1. Foster and McClain received $1,500.
   Nearly 500 people from as far away as California competed for
some $45,000 in prizes. The competitors, ranging in age from 7 to
107, gathered at Lurleen B. Wallace State Junior College's
gymnasium for the event, which is sponsored by the Andalusia Rotary
Club and the local chamber of commerce.
   Charles Tomberlin, co-chairman of the tournament, is credited
with creating the domino championship.
   ``They call me Dr. Domino because in 1976, when the Bicentennial
committee came around asking clubs to sponsor a Bicentennial
project, I jokingly suggested a domino tournament to my fellow
Rotarians,'' said Tomberlin, who remembered playing the game as a
child.
   Tomberlin said he sent letters to George Bush and Michael
Dukakis asking the two likely presidential nominees to play each
other in this year's tournament.
   ``I never got a response,'' he said, laughing. ``We probably
could have really packed them in if those two came.''
 
</TEXT>
