<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 0108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BomberProblems     07-11 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bomber Problems,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tests Show B-1 Bombers May Fall Short of Performing Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's B-1 bombers may not be able to
fulfill their mission of penetrating Soviet air defenses in the
1990s, according to congressional and administration officials
citing new test results.
   Recent tests have shown problems with the B-1's Electronic
Countermeasures, or ECM, system used to foil enemy radar, House
Armed Services Committee Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., said in a
memorandum sent to panel members and disclosed on Sunday.
   Plans to build the B-1 were shelved during the Carter
administration but revived under President Reagan as he persuaded
Congress that a penetrating bomber was needed to bridge the gap
between the aging fleet of B-52s and the B-2 or Stealth Bomber
expected to become operational in the 1990s.
   Reagan won approval for a version called the B-1B by pledging to
keep the first 100 planes under a $28 billion ceiling. The planes
became operational in 1986, although they are still undergoing
tests and adjustments.
   Aspin said in his two-page memorandum said that ``ECM has been
the chief question mark in the B-1B's future as a penetrating
bomber. It looks like we have our answer. The Air Force is now
admitting that, because of a design flaw, it will never work as
advertised.''
   The memo, excerpts of which were obtained by The Associated
Press, quoted a letter from Air Force officials to the committee
late last month saying that `there are limitations within the
current system architecture.''
   Aspin said in his memo that ``the Air Force acknowledged that
those limitations will prevent the B-1B ECM from ever achieving
full operational capability.''
   Despite the problems, Air Force officials said the plane should
be able to penetrate Soviet air space until the introduction of the
Stealth bomber, which is designed to appear as small as possible on
enemy radar screens.
   Air Force officials confirmed the information in Aspin's memo,
but a spokesman, Capt. Jay de Frank, said ``the current round of
flight tests verified that the most important ECM techniques work,
giving us a high degree of confidence that we can penetrate enemy
defense and accomplish our mission.''
   The Air Force is trying to achieve what it calls Mod-1
capabilities on the bomber's ECM system, meeting specifications
that were supposed to be achieved in 1986, according to Air Force
and congressional officials.
   The current hardware aboard the plane is not capable of meeting
higher Mod-2 capabilities, those thought necessary for the plane to
cope with expected improvements in Soviet air defenses by the
1990s, congressional sources said.
   ``The current system has a limitation which precludes achieving
Mod-2 capabilities without modifying the hardware,'' de Frank said.
``We are evaluating options to address these limitations.''
   The exact nature of the limitations is classified for security
reasons, but one congressional source said ECM devices aboard the
B-1 simply do not have the capacity to handle the job.
   ``It's a little like trying to pour a 12-ounce drink into a
7-ounce glass. It just can't be done,'' said one source, speaking
on condition of anonymity. ``They are a long way from being where
they were supposed to be in 1986.''
   The system is designed to receive signals from Soviet radar and
jam them, masking the B-1 and protecting it from Soviet air
defenses, sources said. The current system can cope with what the
Air Force calls ``significant'' threats, but cannot handle
``secondary'' threats.
   Those threats, although secondary, may be sufficient to prompt
the Air Force to alter or reroute the missions of some of the B-1s
to increase the probability that they could return safely, the
sources said.
   ``We had always thought we could correct the problems. But we
got test results within the last six weeks which showed a basic
problem with the architecture of the ECM,'' said one administration
source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Aspin has been critical of the B-1, and last year released a
report citing shortcomings in the ECM and other systems. In 1987,
Congress approved a $600 million program to test and correct the
defects by 1991.
   One widely publicized problem, leakage from the B-1's fuel
tanks, has already been fixed, and solutions are thought possible
for other headaches, including flight instability and poor
coordination between its terrain-following radar and guidance
controls, administration and congressional sources said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880711-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 0032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OilCity Bjt   07-11 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil City, Bjt,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crown of the North Sea Oil Trade Worn Uneasily by Aberdeen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roses, not derricks, bedeck the
streets of this capital of North Sea oil, and the tough Scots who
live here are proud of that.
   Oil changed many lives, made some people rich, and pushed out
the ailing fishing industry, but it has not spoiled the city
sandwiched betweeen the rivers Don and Dee or changed Aberdonians,
they say.
   Aberdeen lives with oil, not for it, and felt largely unscathed
by the two decades of vast changes it brought _ at least until last
week's oil rig tragedy claimed 166 lives, including many
Abderdonians.
   ``Aberdeen doesn't see itself as an oil town,'' says the Rev.
James Stewart of the Kirk (church) of St. Nicholas, the seat of the
city's ancient Church of Scotland congregation. ``It's a town on
which oil has made a deep impact, but it has sufficiently deep
roots in the past and in the hinterland to see itself as something
more.''
   The city of 214,000 residents stresses this in a brochure for
tourists: ``Since the discovery of North Sea oil, Aberdeen has
justifiably earned the title of Europe's offshore oil capital.
   ``The city, however, has not been spoiled by this new industry
... Only occasionally can an oil rig be seen far out on the horizon
_ under tow to a new location or at anchor waiting a new contract.''
   Stewart's stone church looms over a city built of granite, from
rowhouses to two early 16th century universities. Splashes of color
come only from miles of roses lining the streets for Aberdeen's
11th attempt to win the ``Britain in Bloom'' competition.
   Aberdeen is a tough, no-frills city.
   ``It's a town where the character of the people in some ways is
a reflection of the stone of which the city is built,'' says
Stewart, a Scotsman who arrived in the city a few years after the
oil boom began in the early 70s.
   ``Granite is a very hard stone, and there's a kind of
independent toughness about the Aberdonians. It's not a city which
wears its heart on its sleeve.''
   In the days after Wednesday's oil rig disaster, that seemed true.
   Memorial services were held and some flags flew at half-staff;
but shoppers thronged the main street as crying seagulls drifted
overhead.
   The city mourned, but privately.
   ``We're a close-knit people,'' said Kathleen Skene, head
bartender at the Aberdeen Petroleum Club, once the elite haven of
North Sea pioneers, oilwise Americans and, since the world oil
slump, a haunt of fish merchants and businessmen.
   ``Most people know someone or know of someone who's been lost.
It certainly affected a lot of lives,'' she said.
   ``Once Aberdeen folk were considered lucky to have oil on their
doorstep,'' said the Sunday Post newspaper, which calls itself
Scotland's largest Sunday paper. ``Now like many mining communities
before them, they have found the Earth doesn't give up its riches
without a price.''
   The first North Sea oil was struck in 1969 and brought to shore
in 1975. At the time, Aberdeen was in decline.
   But from 1970 to 1984, jobs rose by 54 percent, house prices
rose nearly 20 percent a year and annual passengers through
Aberdeen airport rose 1,370 percent to more than a million, the
city says.
   With oil came a lot of outsiders _ what the Aberdonians call
``in-aboot-comers,'' in their dialect _ especially from the United
States.
   ``I think when oil first started we definitely resented the
Americans because they had the good jobs, they made the money, and
a lot of Aberdonians didn't benefit,'' said Ms. Skene. ``Not
everyone made money.''
   Others welcomed oil from the start.
   ``It meant a complete turnaround from fishing to the oil
scene,'' said manager Frank Naughton of North Star Fishing Co., a
major fishing fleet now used mostly as oil support boats. ``With
the decline in fishing, personally I'd say it was a good thing oil
came in.''
   Since the world oil slump, many Americans have gone and the jobs
are not as well paid. But the city still thrives, and until last
week, had settled quietly into oil work.
   Still, the Rev. Stewart believes Aberdeen's granite spirit will
help it face up to the disaster.
   ``It's sobering, but I think it's part of the character of the
people here to pick up the threads and make the best of it.''
</TEXT>
