<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-11 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Suggests Partial Privatization Of Social Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private study says Social Security should be
placed at least partially in private hands so the federal
government won't be tempted to dip into a surplus expected to reach
$500 billion in 27 years.
   The Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. says such a move would give the
United States a chance to dramatically increase its savings rate.
   The study suggests that workers be allowed to divert 2
percentage points of their payroll tax into individual investment
accounts, similar to Individual Retirement Accounts, starting in
1990, when the tax climbs from 7.51 to 7.65 percentage points.
   In exchange for the private accounts, the workers would
eventually get reduced Social Security benefits.
   The approach would ``ensure that most of the Social Security
reserve is productively invested,'' said the study in the July
issue of Morgan's World Financial Markets report. The report is
published by Morgan Guaranty Trust Co., a subsidiary of J.P. Morgan
& Co. Inc.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fund Organizer Says He's Ready To Give Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian man who set up a fund to aid
American hostages in Lebanon has raised only $20 in six months and
is dissolving the account.
   Gary Selby said he has spent more than $1,200 on telephone calls
to hostages' families and drumming up publicity for the Freedom
Trust at a Washington bank. Selby said he will likely dissolve the
fund before the end of the month.
   ``I feel like I have to apologize to the families, because I got
their hopes up,'' Selby said in a weekend telephone interview. ``I
have to give it up or I'll go bankrupt.''
   Bank officials could not be contacted during the weekend to say
how much money was in the fund.
   Selby, of Shawbridge, Quebec, said documents he receives as
trustee show the account currently holds $20, mostly in $1 checks
mailed from Pennsylvania after a radio station there interviewed
him.
</TEXT>
