<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     07-11 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proxmire Says Democrats Better Off Losing Presidential Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. William Proxmire says his party
might be better off losing the presidential election because of the
severe recession he expects will hit the debt-ridden United States
in the next two years.
   Proxmire, D-Wis., who is retiring after 31 years in the Senate,
said he believes a recession or depression is almost certain by
1990, and so it may be better for Democrats if the Republican
nominee wins the election.
   Otherwise, Democrats might be kissing ``the presidency goodbye
for 40 years,'' he said.
   ``Many of us earnestly believe our country is headed for
economic hell-in-a-handbasket,'' Proxmire was quoted as saying in
The Milwaukee Journal on Sunday.
   ``This senator would give very strong odds that sometime in 1989
or 1990, recession and probably depression will hit,'' Proxmire
said. ``The next president and his party at that time will be in a
political dilemma from which there will be no escape.''
   ``Let us face it. You will not get one in 100 to admit it, but
the best thing that could happen to the Democrats might be to lose
the next presidential election.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush, Dole, Thompson Plead Unity Before State GOP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Gov. Jim Thompson told Nebraska
Republicans they must improve voter registration and turnout to
help Vice President George Bush become president.
   ``We have the lowest voter turnout of any democracy in the
world,'' the four-term governor told more than 300 delegates
assembled for the GOP state convention Saturday.
   ``I know it sounds humdrum, but registration and turnout are the
key. It's his (Bush) job to convince the voters, it's your job to
make sure they vote,'' Thompson said.
   In remarks to reporters following a speech which emphasized the
peace and prosperity of the Reagan-Bush administration, Thompson
said voters will choose the next president on the basis of the
economy.
   ``The candidate who wins will be the one who best speaks to the
economic values of the American middle class,'' Thompson said.
