<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Pakistanis     07-11 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Pakistanis,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Signed on Repatriation of Pakistanis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior government official says an
agreement has been signed in Pakistan on the repatriation of about
250,000 Pakistanis who were stranded in Bangladesh when it gained
independence.
   Foreign Secretary Nazrul Islam told a news conference the
agreement was signed Saturday in Islamabad, the Pakistani capital,
between the government of Pakistan and Rabita, a humanitarian group
based in Mecca, Saudi Arabia.
   Islam said officials in Dhaka were ``happy'' over the agreement.
   According to the agreement, Rabita will raise nearly $500
million for the repatriation and rehabilitation of 250,000
Pakistanis stranded in Bangladesh since December 1971, when
Bangladesh, then East Pakistan, became an independent country after
a liberation struggle and a war between India and Pakistan.
   By 1973, 174,000 refugees had returned to Pakistan, but the
repatriation ended abruptly when funds ran out, stranding about
250,000 people who remain in refugee camps in Bangladesh.
</TEXT>
