<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather ,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disappointing Rain in Drought-Battered Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms packing winds up to 58 mph covered
sections of the Northeast, the Midwest and the Southwest today
after disappointingly small rains fell in the drought-battered
Midwest.
   A flash flood watch was in effect for much of west Texas, where
rain was very heavy in some places. Nearly an inch of rain fell in
just one hour near Pandale in southwest Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms also fell in southern Arizona, eastern
Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern Nebraska and parts of
Missouri. At Cleveland's Lakefront Airport, winds gusted to 58 mph.
   The storms Sunday in parts of the Midwest left less than a
quarter of an inch of rain in most of Illinois, Indiana and lower
Michigan. Chicago received only a trace of rain.
   A few farmers got a break. An inch of rain fell at Sheridan,
Ind., and more than an inch fell at Alpena, Mich.
   Showers and thunderstorms dissipated late Sunday over Florida,
the Gulf Coast states, the Carolinas, the Tennessee Valley and the
Rockies.
   In Michigan, a gust from a severe thunderstorm Sunday collapsed
Dome World, an indoor softball and golf driving range complex in
Grand Rapids. In Belding, where the Gus Macker Basketball
Tournament was being played, one person was injured by lightning
and another was hurt by falling tree limbs. All the backboards,
each weighing 1,200 pounds, were knocked down.
   Two people were struck by lightning in Bay County, Mich., while
trying to cover a boat, authorities said.
   In High Point, N.C., a severe thunderstorm knocked over a
two-story cinder-block wall of a building under construction, and
blew a roof off a K mart being built down the road. The roof landed
on cars in an adjacent parking lot.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
East Coast to the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the Gulf Coast states
and the southern Plains, with showers and thunderstorms most
numerous over northern New England and the upper Ohio Valley;
widely scattered showers and thunderstorms over the Rockies; and
showers in the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were forecast for the 70s in the upper Great
Lakes region, the upper Mississippi Valley and the northern Plains;
the 60s and 70s in the Pacific Northwest and along the California
coast; more than 100 degrees in the desert Southwest and
California's central valleys; unseasonably high temperatures in the
mid- to upper 90s in the middle and north Atlantic Coast states;
and 80s and and 90s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 46
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 94 degrees at Nellis
Air Force Base in Nevada.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 75 fair; Boston 78 fair; Buffalo 76 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 77 cloudy; Cincinnati 71 foggy; Cleveland 70
foggy; Detroit 69 foggy; Miami 82 fair; New York 75 foggy;
Philadelphia 78 hazy; Pittsburgh 74 showers; Portland, Maine 66
foggy; Washington 79 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 55 fair; Chicago 68 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
76 partly cloudy; Denver 63 fair; Des Moines 68 fair; Indianapolis
71 hazy; Kansas City 70 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 64 partly
cloudy; Nashville 80 cloudy; New Orleans 79 partly cloudy; St.
Louis 79 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 67 fair; Anchorage 60 cloudy; Las Vegas 93
windy; Los Angeles 64 cloudy; Phoenix 85 cloudy; Salt Lake City 78
partly cloudy; San Diego 65 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle
56 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 75 cloudy; Toronto 72 hazy.
</TEXT>
