<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChildHunter     07-11 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Hunter,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Self-Described Child Hunter Jailed On Abduction, Sexual Abuse
Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 6th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARKERSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who says he runs an agency that
helps find abducted children and pledged to use ``guerrilla
tactics'' to return youngsters to their parents has been charged
with attempted abduction and sexual abuse of young boys.
   David Robert Riggs, 37, is being held in the Wood County jail in
lieu of $25,000 bond. He was arrested July 2 by Wood County
sheriff's deputies after a woman in nearby Boaz said he tried to
abduct her 13-year-old grandson.
   Riggs was charged with two felony counts of attempted abduction
and a misdemeanor count of third-degree sexual abuse.
   Riggs represents himself as director of Search Seven New York,
which purportedly does ``aggressive investigations designed to
recover criminally abducted children.''
   In all, six boys in Mason and Wood counties accused Riggs of
propositioning them for photographs July 1 and July 2. He allegedly
offered the boys $5 to pose for photographs on the spot, and more
if they would get in his car and pose in a remote area wearing
bikini underwear he would provide.
   Three boys agreed to pose on the spot but none got into Riggs'
car. The attempted abduction charges stem from his request that
they enter the car; the third-degree sex abuse charge was brought
because one of the boys said Riggs pulled down the boy's swim
trunks and touched his genitals.
   Last week, police searched Riggs' dusty 1973 Oldsmobile Omega,
but police found no exposed film. The one roll in a camera was
loaded incorrectly and contained no photographs.
   Wood County Sheriff Steve Greiner said he hopes to keep Riggs in
custody while investigators continue to study his past.
   So far, authorities here said they have no evidence Riggs has
ever been charged with sexual abuse anywhere else. But Greiner said
they also have found no record that Riggs ever helped locate lost
children in the four years that he has dogged police departments, a
national missing-children center and the parents of abducted
children for information.
   Police said Riggs, a New Yorker who recently moved to the
central Michigan town of Crystal, alternatively represents himself
as a private investigator, the head of a non-profit agency and a
university sociologist.
   His queries prompted the FBI in Pennsylvania and state police in
Illinois to investigate him, officials said. Police in Tennessee
said they closed the door on Riggs when he gave different stories
of who he was.
   The National Center for Missing and Exploited Children _ which
does not work with private investigators _ turned Riggs away when
he was unable to verify who he was or why he wanted detailed
records on every missing child in the United States.
   In June 1987, the center warned parents of missing children
that, despite his claims otherwise, Riggs was not working with the
agency.
   ``No information has been released to him, nor will it be,''
according to the center's deputy director John Rabun.
   ``We said, `OK, David, fine. What are you?''' Rabun said.
``First, he said he was a not-for-profit agency, then he said he
was a private investigator. Later he said he was working for
Columbia University.''
   Rabun said a background check turned up no New York records of a
private investigator's license for Riggs or a tax number for Search
Seven.
   In 1984, Riggs described himself to an Allentown, Pa., newspaper
reporter as a schoolteacher turned salesman who started searching
for missing children because he was outraged by the abductions.
   ``I plan to use `guerrilla tactics' police don't usually use,''
Riggs was quoted as saying. ``This is a battle. This isn't
something you can sit back in your armchair and contemplate your
next attack.''
</TEXT>
