<1ST_LINE>r p PM-UtahGovernor     07-11 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utah Governor,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gov. Bangerter Struggling To Salvage Re-Election Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits to fix category code to p</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beset by a weak economy but boosted by
Utah's Republican leanings, Gov. Norm Bangerter hopes to salvage
his sagging re-election campaign with an aggressive attack on his
Democratic challenger.
   But some Republican die-hards say it may be too late.
   Bangerter, who trails Democrat Ted Wilson in polls, says he will
spend the dog days of summer in rural Utah and other traditional
GOP strongholds trying to persuade Republicans that Utah has moved
forward under his hand despite a stagnant economy and a record tax
increase.
   ``My biggest challenge and concern is that people are going to
base this decision on emotion rather than facts, and that would be
the biggest mistake,'' Bangerter said in an interview.
   Other Republicans say Bangerter still can win, but they caution
that even in this predominantly Republican state a victory over
Wilson will not come easily.
   ``I believe it's winnable, but the governor has got to get his
case to the people, his record and what he's done. It's a good
case, but we may have passed the point in time where we could
salvage the election,'' said former Republican State Chairman
Charles Akerlow, who presided over the GOP's sweep of major offices
in 1984.
   Bangerter's popularity plummeted after he cajoled the
Legislature last year into passing a $166 million tax increase, the
largest in Utah history.
   His problems have been deepened by the state's weak economy, the
failure of five Utah thrift and loan institutions and dry weather
that made a mockery of his decision several years ago to spend $60
million to install pumps to remove floodwaters from the Great Salt
Lake _ the lake level has since gone down largely on its own.
   Recent initiatives have done little to restore public
confidence. Even his announcement last month of a plan to rebate
$80 million in surplus income taxes and lower rates by 5 percent
failed to revive his candidacy.
   A Deseret News-KSL-TV poll taken in early July and released last
Tuesday found he had the support of 28 percent of the 603 residents
surveyed, compared with 51 percent for Wilson, the former mayor of
Salt Lake City.
   Bangerter lost 2 percentage points of support while Wilson
climbed by the same amount since a similar poll in June. But Dave
Buhler, Bangerter's campaign manager, dismissed the changes as
statistically irrelevant since the poll's margin of error was 4
percentage points.
   A further complication for Bangerter is the independent campaign
of former Republican Merrill Cook. Cook entered the race at the
behest of the Tax Limitation Coalition of Utah, which is sponsoring
three tax-reduction initiatives that have qualified for the
November ballot.
   The latest Deseret News-KSL-TV poll found Cook had the support
of 13 percent of those surveyed, evenly divided among those who
otherwise would vote for Bangerter and Wilson. But Wilson can
afford the loss; Bangerter cannot.
   Bangerter contends that the state's Republican majority will
vote for him once it realizes that, despite the tax increase, he
has made sound decisions. For instance, he said he will emphasize
that during his term the state budget has dropped 8 percent and
unemployment has fallen to 5 percent, the lowest rate of the 1980s.
   ``If the voters want strong, conservative fiscal government,
responsible government, my record provides that,'' Bangerter said.
``I don't think Wilson provides that. He provides a record of
taxing and spending. I have a record of taxing, but not spending.''
   Wilson said his task is to keep Bangerter on the defensive.
   ``I predict my lead will narrow,'' Wilson said. ``I need to get
my story out, and I'm not going to let them take the agenda away
from me. Let's face it, the state is 2-1 Republican.''
   Bangerter appears to have a slight lead in fund-raising. Buhler
said the governor has spent about $350,000 and has $50,000 to
$70,000 in the bank.
   Rob Jolley, Wilson's campaign manager, said the former mayor has
raised about $365,000 and spent $350,000. The largest single
expenditure was $170,000 for a television advertising campaign that
was designed to solidify Wilson's support. Jolley said the ads
apparently did more than expected.
   ``We didn't feel it would bring us a lot of new support. We were
surprised that we gained,'' he said.
</TEXT>
