<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Maxwell'sPlum     07-11 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Maxwell's Plum,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Side Restaurant Closes Its Doors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell's Plum, a Manhattan restaurant that came
to symbolize the city's swinging singles bar scene, has closed its
doors after more than two decades.
   ``As much as I like Maxwell's, it's an awful lot of work to keep
it open, and really, for me, the fun is lost,'' said owner Warner
LeRoy.
   The restaurant's 155 employees were told Sunday afternoon of the
closing, which was effective after dinner service.
   Maxwell's failing fortunes in the highly competitive Manhattan
restaurant market were no secret, and in recent years LeRoy had
hired four chefs with drastically different styles in an effort to
turn the restaurant around.
   Maxwell's Plum, located on the Upper East Side, opened in April
1966, and with its outlandish Art Nouveau decor and sprawling bar,
was an immediate hit.
</TEXT>
