<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 0821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-Protests     07-11 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Protests,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Claims Victory; Leaves Bridges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Mexico-Elections, Bjt
^By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition supporters shut down
three bridges spanning the U.S. border to protest delayed election
results, then lifted the blockades today when the government
announced that their party won local races.
   The protestors, adherents of the right-of-center National Action
Party, held the bridges for more than 26 hours in a peaceful
demonstration that began Saturday night.
   Their candidates won all three Juarez area races for the federal
legislature's lower house in last Wednesday's balloting.
   In Mexico City on Sunday, opposition activists held vigils
outside centers where ballots were being counted, saying they were
guarding against vote fraud.
   Also, supporters of presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas
of the National Democratic Front demonstrated outside the Interior
Ministry to demand that the government release vote tallies without
rigging the results.
   When the results were announced in this border city, local
National Action Party campaign coordinator Ramon Galindo said they
``signify the death of the (governing party) in Ciudad Juarez.''
   About 1,000 people cheered and then began leaving the Cordova
bridge, the main link between Juarez and El Paso, Texas. Another
200 protesters left the smaller Zaragoza bridge about eight miles
to the east. Protesters had also occupied a bridge 20 miles east of
the city.
   Traffic on Sunday was restricted to the two other bridges that
link Juarez with El Paso.
   As the bridge takeover began in Juarez, National Acton Party
party members blocked the Pan American highway outside the state
capital of Chihuahua, 200 miles south of the U.S. border.
   Similar traffic stoppages took place in the Chihuahua cities of
Delicias, Jimenez and Parral.
   Party leaders were vowing to continue their campaign of civil
resistance if they determined that the governing Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, was attempting to cheat them out of
electoral victory.
   Since its creation in 1929, PRI has never lost a gubernatorial
or presidential race. But it has long been accused of massive vote
fraud, especially in Chihuahua.
   The National Action Party is considered a contender in much of
Mexico's north.
   On the Cordova Bridge, the protesters had set up tents and tarps
to escape the sun and food and drink vendors plied their trade. The
air was almost festive there and at the Zaragoza bridge.
   After the government said it would release election results
Sunday night, local National Action Party leaders met and decided
to vacate the bridges as when the tallies were announced, said
party spokesman Francisco Barrio.
   In 1986, Barrio ran for Chihuahua governor and was defeated by
PRI candidate Hernando Baeza in what the National Action Party
termed massive vote fraud.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
