<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Farmers-Canola     07-11 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farmers-Canola,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good Canola Harvest Helps Take Farmers' Minds Off Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heat and drought are scorching corn
and soybeans, but a few farmers are counting the cash from a new
crop they just harvested. Canola.
   ``That probably will be the best crop I've got this year,'' said
Don Hiter, who sold about 1,000 bushels of the tiny, black oil-seed
from his 20-acre plot in DeWitt County. ``Everything else is in bad
shape.''
   Canola is a trademark for a variety of rape, a plant whose seeds
are crushed to produce oil for cooking and food production and meal
for livestock feed. Canada grows about 80 percent of the world
supply of rape and little has been raised in the United States.
   There were about 12,000 acres of the crop in Illinois, Indiana,
Ohio, Michigan and Kentucky this year, according to Tony Jones, a
representative of Canola, Inc., an Indianapolis-based seed
distributor.
   That could increase significantly in 1989 because the current
drought threatens to reduce the U.S. harvest of soybeans, another
oil-seed crop, said Jones.
   ``When we harvest Canola next year, we will be riding on the
effect of this drought and we'll still have high prices,'' said
Jones. ``We'll generate good cash flow and know we're getting the
best price of the year without having to tie up storage space.''
   Canola is planted in the fall and grows until cold weather
causes it to become dormant. It resumes its growth in the spring
and is harvested in late June or early July.
   ``It looks like sweet clover when it's in full bloom, covered
with yellow flowers,'' said Hiter. ``You can see it from miles
around. I had a lot of neighbors looking at it.''
   Canola survived the drought because it matured and was harvested
much earlier than the corn crop. The grain got an early start in
the spring, thus avoiding the harsh effects of the drought.
   The plant, which is related to mustard, is about four feet tall
and grows thick enough that ``it smothers all the weeds,'' said
Hiter, who farms 880 acres with his son near Weldon.
   Hiter said he was pleased with his yield of 50 bushels per acre.
   The 1988 Canola sold for $7.25 a bushel, but Hiter had to truck
the seed 100 miles to a grain elevator at Farina, one of only two
receiving points in Illinois.
   Roger Read, who operates a farm supply and grain marketing
business in Madison County, said he and some of his customers also
raised Canola this year. He said they had generally good results,
but hope there will be more places to sell the crop in the future.
   Another advantage of Canola, said Jones, is that the U.S. crop
is harvested earlier than spring-planted Canadian rapeseed, at a
time when processors need it.
   ``Canola gives you flexibility _ another option in your crop
rotation and a chance to spread out your workload,'' Read said.
``With the drought, canola was a bright spot this year _ something
to make you smile and get excited.''
</TEXT>
