<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL-Bakker     07-11 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL-Bakker,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Expects All Lawsuits Against Him to Be Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trustee for PTL says he will examine
deposed founder Jim Bakker's proposal to buy back the ministry, but
he doesn't think Bakker's plan is viable.
   ``The real big problem for (Bakker) is that I think we're going
to have some better offers than his ... That's what we're waiting
on, to see if they develop,'' said the court-appointed trustee,
M.C. Benton.
   Bakker's plan to buy back the Christian retreat and television
ministry calls for PTL's assets to be appraised at $130 million and
all lawsuits against him to be dropped.
   Bakker's conditions were listed in a three-page letter to Benton
released Friday by Ryan Hovis, Bakker's attorney.
   Benton said he is uneasy about Bakker's plan to use the Heritage
USA theme park as collateral for the $100 million loan he will use
to buy the ministry. Benton said Bakker's lawsuits against the
ministry were another hurdle.
   In January, Bakker sued PTL to recover $1.3 million for a house
his family had lived in. That house was sold for $685,000.
   PTL countersued for more than $52 million, saying Bakker and his
wife, Tammy Faye, owed the ministry for excess salaries and
mismanagement.
   The letter released by Hovis did not shed any new light on who
would finance Bakker's $100 million loan. Bakker said the investor
is foreign and is the head of a company worth $2.3 billion.
   The ministry has been in financial straits since Bakker left in
March 1987 after relevations that he had a sexual tryst with church
secretary Jessica Hahn.
   Benton said he continues to hold talks with businessmen
interested in buying the theme park, just south of Charlotte, N.C.
He hopes to make a recommendation on a buyer to the bankruptcy
court by August.
</TEXT>
