<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Airliner-Pueblo     07-11 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airliner-Pueblo,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pueblo Commander Says Persian Gulf Sailors Face More Difficult
Task</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. forces on patrol in the Persian Gulf face
a more difficult situation than the crew of the USS Pueblo, says
the commander of the spy ship whose crew was imprisoned for 11
months in North Korea.
   ``I don't think the Persian Gulf is anywhere near the situation
we had,'' retired Navy Cmdr. Lloyd Bucher said at the 20th reunion
of the Pueblo crew this weekend. ``Those guys have it more
difficult over there.''
   The gulf is an all-out war, Bucher said.
   ``They're trying to deal with these harassing attacks and live
within very constricted rules of engagement,'' he said. ``I don't
see how any person in the history of the U.S. Navy has had to deal
with the tensions these guys are dealing with. I think they're
handling it extremely well.''
   The Pueblo, armed with only two .50-caliber machine guns and
hand-held firearms, was monitoring communist ship movements and
messages in international waters near the North Korean coast when
it was attacked by torpedo boats Jan. 23, 1968.
   One crewman died and 10 others were wounded before the vessel
was seized. The 82 survivors were taken to a prison camp, where
they endured beatings and physical and psychological torture.
   More than 40 Pueblo crew members gathered to renew ties and
discuss the hardships they endured.
   Retired Chief Petty Officer Jim Kell had boarded the Pueblo for
a 30-day assignment shortly before the ship became the first U.S.
military vessel to be captured since 1812.
   ``I would never say I wish it had been somebody else because
I've been through it and it's something I'm never going to
forget,'' Kell said. ``I wish I hadn't been through it, but I
wouldn't wish it on anybody.''
   ``It made 82 people become very close ... but I know some are
still bitter about it,'' said Kell, of El Cajon, Calif.
   Crewman Stu Russell said conversation at the weekend
get-together was ``standard reunion-type stuff about families, jobs
... and what percentage disability you get from the Veterans
Administration.''
   ``Almost invariably, the stories you hear are about funny or
stupid things that happened (during their ordeal). The real
heavyweight stuff isn't talked about much,'' said Russell, of
Eureka, Calif.
   ``It's still been kind of intense, but really good therapy.''
   The crew members were released on Dec. 23, 1968, after the nited
States apologized for ``grave acts'' committed against North Korea
in its claimed territorial waters.
</TEXT>
