<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MineDisaster     07-11 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mine Disaster,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Dynamite Blast Caused Mine Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KASSEL, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dynamite blast triggered the
underground explosion that killed 51 miners in West Germany's worst
mining disaster in 25 years, the prosecutor in Kassel said today.
   Shortly after the June 1 disaster, officials said they believed
methane gas had exploded in the Stolzenbach mine in Borken, about
70 miles northeast of Frankfurt.
   But prosecutor Stephan Walcher said today that the fatal
explosion was sparked when workers set off dynamite to close a
depleted shaft.
   Walcher said the dynamite blast ignited coal dust in the air,
sending a powerful shock wave through the mine.
   He noted that the use of dynamite is considered normal in mining.
   He also said investigators ruled out that a cigarette lighter
ignited the blast, as West German media speculated after the
disaster.
   Walcher said that the results of the investigation were only
preliminary and it would probably take several more months to
determine if the correct procedures were used in the blasting.
   Three days after the explosion, six surviving miners were
discovered 500 feet underground after their sounds were picked up
by a television crew's microphone, which was lowered into the shaft.
   Carbon monoxide poisoning killed most of the 51 miners who
perished.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
