<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     07-11 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Reaches 136 In Flooding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overflowing rivers inundated a widening
area of Bangladesh and claimed 15 more lives, raising the death
toll in a week of flooding to at least 136, newspapers reported
today.
   More than 5 million people have been driven from their homes,
mainly in the northeast, as rain-swollen rivers overflowed their
banks and swept through villages and farmlands, the reports said.
   They said the latest deaths occurred Sunday in the northeastern
district of Hobiganj, the northwestern districts of Gaibandha,
Kurigram and Jamalpur, and the central districts of Netrokona and
Comilla.
   Most of the town of Barahmanbaria, 50 miles east of Dhaka, was
under three feet of water and crops over a large surrounding area
were damaged or destroyed, according to officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   They said army troops were performing large scale rescue
operations, but many areas remain inaccessible because bridges are
flooded and there is not enough dry land for helicopters to land.
   Road and railway traffic between Dhaka and northeastern
districts today remain blocked for the seventh day because many
bridges and rail crossings are submerged.
   The waters of the Brahmaputra and Jammu rivers, which rose above
flood levels, rushed into neighboring India, the reports said.
   In northeastern India, seven people died in flooding in Assam
state and more than 3,000 families were left stranded in Tripura
state, Indian news agencies reported today.
   Floods are an annual threat in this country of 105 million
people with heavy monsoon rains, which are essential for the
country's rice crop. Bangladesh, one of the poorest nations in the
world, does not have the funds to build dams that would hold back
the flood waters.
   Last year, in the worst flooding in 70 years, some 25 million
people were driven out of their homes and more than 1,200 died.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad flew over flood-affected areas
on Sunday. Later, at an emergency Cabinet meeting, he ordered
government officials to personally supervise the relief operations.
</TEXT>
