<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Drought-GreatLakes     07-11 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Great Lakes,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Debate Great Lakes Diversion Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The factories of the Midwest and the farms of
the South have a common stake in keeping Mississippi River
barge-traffic moving, even if it takes Great Lakes water to do the
job, Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., said today.
   ``If the farmers in the Mississippi delta go under, the
automobile workers in Detroit ... are going to go down also,''
Pryor said on the NBC-TV ``Today'' show.
   River shipping carries 60 percent of the nation's grain, 40
percent of its petroleum and 80 percent of its diesel fuel, Pryor
said.
   But Sen. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., said during the program that
diverting Great Lakes water would be wasting a resource needed in
the drought.
   ``That fresh water in the Great Lakes is 95 percent of the fresh
surface water we have for the whole country,'' Riegle said. ``If we
send it down the Mississippi River to lift the level to float those
barges, that fresh water goes down the river and goes into the gulf
and becomes salt water. So we lose what is a precious resource.''
   Thirteen senators on Friday asked President Reagan to allow an
emergency diversion of water from the Great Lakes to the
Mississippi. They proposed increasing the flow from the lakes to
the river from the 3,000 cubic feet per second to 10,000 cubic feet
per second for 100 days.
   Supporters of diversion said the drought has depressed the
Mississippi River to its lowest level since record-keeping began in
1872, stranding as many as 3,000 barges with losses to the barge
and towing industry expected to run as high as $60 million.
   Opponents said water levels in the Great Lakes have dropped 3
feet in the last two years and the water is needed for Midwest
agriculture.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., said in a
Kalamazoo, Mich., speech he would not support efforts to divert
water from the Great Lakes to the Mississippi River.
   ``The pressure to do it in times of emergency is great, but in
many ways it probably would be the worst time to lower the level of
the lakes because they're already down in a drought year,'' Foley
said Saturday.
   A 1986 law forbids new diversions of Great Lakes water for use
outside the lakes basin without approval of the governors of all
the states in the region.
   ``Diversion would be a short-sighted policy,'' said Ohio Gov.
Richard Celeste, chairman of the Council of Great Lakes Governors,
on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.''
   ``I am deeply concerned about environmental and economic
consequences for people in the Great Lakes states and Canadian
provinces.''
   Each inch the lakes are lowered costs some $200 million in cargo
carried, $10 million in generating power and $3 million to $5
million in recreation revenue, he said.
   But Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., said on the same program that the
proposed diversion would lower the lakes by an inch or less while
raising the Mississippi up to 1 foot.
   The diversion of lakes water to the Mississippi was increased
during a drought in the 1950s, ``and there were no serious
environmental effects,'' Sasser said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
