<HEAD>Mexican Nationals Rally For Fraud-Free Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 local supporters of one of Mexico's
opposition party presidential candidate called on that country's
government to release the results of last week's election.
   ``We want the government to respect the decision of the
people,'' Salvador Vasquez, president of Mexicans in Support of
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, said Sunday at a rally in front of the Mexican
Consulate.
   Protesters here and across Mexico claim the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party or PRI is fraudulently withholding returns from
Wednesday's election to manipulate them in favor of its candidate,
Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   Cardenas, who broke with the PRI last year, claimed victory
Saturday as the candidate of the leftist National Democratic Front.
   ``We will not tolerate fraud any longer regardless of where we
are,'' said Isabel Vasquez, representing a coalition of voting
rights groups in California which include many Mexican nationals.
   The Mexican government said today, after opposition activists
blocked highways and shut down international bridges to protest the
delay, that Salinas had a wide lead over his opponents but that
results still were not final.
   Manuel Clouthier of the right-wing National Action Party said
his party's figures showed he was ahead in the presidential
balloting.
