<HEAD>Palestinian Killed in West Bank Clash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs with background on Israeli economy; pickup
3rd graf pvs, ``In the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops fired on stone-throwing high
school students in the occupied West Bank today, killing a
16-year-old Palestinian, hospital officials said.
   Economics Minister Gad Yaacobi, meanwhile, said the 7-month-old
Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied
territories has cost Israel more than $600 million. The figure
included Israeli losses in tourism, export and production revenues,
he said.
   Israel's gross national product was $27 billion in 1987,
including $1.6 billion from tourism. In May, tourist officials said
they expected tourism income to drop by about $300 million this
year, mainly because of the uprising.
   In the West Bank village of Anabta today, troops fired on
students who hurled rocks and empty bottles at them after classes
let out, hospital officials in nearby Tulkarem said.
   Hassan Addas was shot three times in the chest, said the
hospital officials, speaking on condition of anonymity. The army
said it was investigating.
   The death brought to 219 the number of Palestinians killed in
the uprising, according to U.N. figures. Four Israelis have also
died.
   Several Israeli Arabs suspected of carrying out arson attacks on
forests and farmland in Israel have been jailed for six months
without trial, the daily Yediot Ahronot reported.
   The newspaper said Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin signed the
order jailing the men from the northern Galilee who allegedly
belonged to an anti-Israeli group called Sons of the Village.
   The defense ministry declined comment.
   Since the uprising began Dec. 8, more than 2,000 Palestinians
from the occupied lands have been jailed for up to six months
without trial under administrative detention, but such measures
rarely have been taken against Israeli Arabs.
   On Sunday, Israeli soldiers fatally shot an Arab youth and
seriously wounded another in West Bank clashes and the army
demolished the homes of five Gaza Strip residents accused of
hurling firebombs at troops.
   Troops shot and killed an Askar resident when Arab youths
erected roadblocks of burning tires and stones along the main
highway outside the camp and hurled rocks at troops, the army said.
   The army later clamped a curfew on Askar's 8,200 residents.
   Officials at Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus said 17-year-old
Zubdi Mansour Isragi died after a bullet pierced an artery in his
thigh.
   Ittihad officials said the 18-year-old youth was in grave
condition with a gunshot wound in the chest.
   The army did not confirm the report, but said three Arabs were
hurt by gunfire or rubber bullets during a clash in the
marketplace. It did not elaborate.
   Five Israeli soldiers, among them a woman, were indicted on
charges they beat bound Arab detainees and humiliated them by
forcing them to make animal sounds, an Israeli newspaper reported.
   An army official confirmed Sunday that indictments were handed
up in the case, but said he could not provide details.
   An Israeli army lieutenant and four soldiers were indicted
Friday on charges they abused prisoners at the Dahariya detention
center near Hebron, Yediot Ahronot said.
   On March 28, the officer ordered detainees to curse Palestine
Liberation Organization leaders, the newspaper quoted the
indictment as saying. Prisoners who refused were kicked and struck
in the head and chest.
   A military policeman punched a bound and blindfolded prisoner
who was later hospitalized with internal bleeding, the newspaper
said. The officer also smashed the heads of other prisoners against
a wall, the report said.
   Another soldier forced detainees to make animal sounds and beat
them with sticks when they refused, according to the paper.
   The newspaper said the complaints against the five were lodged
by other soldiers.
</TEXT>
