<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FerretAssociation 1stLd-Writethru a0446 07-11 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ferret Association, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferret Lovers Band Together To Protect Their Favorite Animals From
Criticism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, ``The lack of xxx, to delete reference to
ferrets as `pink-eyed'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To critics, ferrets are ill-tempered little
cousins of the weasel: sharp-fanged beasts that threaten to spread
rabies and look like stretched-out rats when their owners parade
them around on leashes.
   George Harmon, head of the International Ferret Association,
offers a contrasting view: ``Ferrets are love with four legs.''
   Jennifer Au would surely agree. The 19-year-old Manassas woman
went to jail for refusing to produce a ferret authorities believe
may have bitten a 5-year-old boy.
   Ms. Au faces a contempt of court hearing Thursday after
arranging to have her ferret whisked away to a location she claims
not to know. Meanwhile, the boy has had to undergo rabies shots
with potentially dangerous side effects.
   Ms. Au spent five days in jail on a contempt-of-court charge to
protect her ferret from being killed to perform a rabies test,
displaying a loyalty Harmon said is not uncommon among the
tightknit society of ferret lovers.
   ``I'm really surprised somebody hasn't gotten killed over a
ferret,'' said Harmon, a longtime fancier of the animal whose
international network has its headquarters in a small office above
the Better Business Bureau.
   ``If somebody comes into your house to impound your ferret,
wouldn't you fight to protect it?'' he said. ``Particularly if it
was innocent.''
   Harmon's group, which claims more than 100,000 members in 19
countries, registers about 1,500 ferrets per month, sort of what
the American Kennel Club does for dogs, but not all its tasks are
so mundane.
   Some ferret lovers rescue the animals from authorities in
California, where owning the animals is banned, while others hide
them in New England states where they are outlawed.
   The International Ferret Association is also preparing to wage a
battle to prevent ferrets from being used as laboratory animals at
the University of Oregon.
   The group is raising money to try to keep Ms. Au out of jail. So
far it has collected more than $300. Harmon acknowledges that her
fight to save her ferret ``is the worst case we've ever had.''
   Authorities must remove the heads of ferrets to test them for
rabies, a viral disease of the central nervous system. Ms. Au
maintains they have already decapitated the ferret that actually
bit the child, as well as a third ferret that was at the scene. The
authorities found no rabies.
   The lack of reliable rabies tests that can be performed on
living ferrets is cited by officials who try to keep the furry
animals outlawed.
   Doctors also have documented cases of ferrets attacking babies,
mutilating ears and noses. Some officials worry that ferrets will
establish colonies in the wild and disrupt the environment.
   Harmon said at least six states _ California, New Hampshire,
Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Georgia and Hawaii _ have passed laws
that force ferret owners underground. Federal statistics show
ferrets are far less likely to spread rabies than dogs and cats, he
said.
   Harmon said he has been bitten thousands of times in the 32
years he has owned ferrets, which have been used for centuries to
catch rats, mice and rabbits. He has never contracted rabies and
said few cases of the disease have been attributed to the animals,
which he said number up to 8 million in the United States.
   ``They've got a mouth _ anything with a mouth will bite,''
Harmon said. ``They have teeth like cats. Yeah, they'll draw blood,
but they'll hold on. They don't bite and let loose and bite again,
like dogs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
