<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TankerExplosion     07-11 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tanker Explosion,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tanker Truck Explodes, Levels Office Building; Two Hurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STERLING, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gasoline tanker truck exploded today
while unloading fuel, burning down an oil company office, sending
flames 500 feet into the sky and injuring two people, authorities
said.
   The explosion occurred about 7 a.m. as the truck driver was
unloading fuel into an underground tank at Plains Oil Co., a mile
west of this northeastern Colorado community, authorities said.
   The driver told ambulance attendants that he was climbing into
the truck cab to turn off the engine when the blast hit.
   Officials said a volunteer firefighter who lives near the Plains
Oil office, Jeff Hunker, dragged the driver away from the flames.
   The fire, visible up to five miles away, was so hot that
firefighters had to wait 45 minutes before they could begin
battling it. The crews trained hoses on gasoline storage tanks to
keep them from exploding.
   The fire spread to the Plains Oil office and burned it to the
ground. The truck cab and tank melted, officials said.
   Authorities evacuated a nearby park, officials said.
   The tanker truck driver was in critical condition and was to be
transferred to the burn unit at University Hospital in Denver, said
Rhonnie Kuebler of Sterling Regional MedCenter.
   A Plains Oil employee was listed in fair condition at the
Sterling hospital, Kuebler said.

</TEXT>
