<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Convention-Fun     07-11 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention-Fun,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta: Nice Place To Live, But Who Wants To Visit?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta is a great place to live, but even the
residents acknowledge you wouldn't want to visit here.
   Nevertheless, Atlanta offers a handful of attractions to people
visiting the nation's third-busiest convention city: Braves
baseball games, a shopping spree at Saks, a trip to the gigantic
Six Flags Over Georgia amusement park and maybe an evening spent at
nearby Stone Mountain Park watching a laser light show on the side
of the world's largest outcropping of granite.
   The 35,000 folks in town for the Democratic National Convention
next week won't be able to do two of those: the Braves are in
Philadelphia and New York all week, while the laser show takes
place at night when the convention sessions occur.
   On the other hand, there is an eclectic assortment of dining
available: The telephone listings run for 28 pages from A Kenneth
Melear Barbecue No. 1 and A Taste of New Orleans to Zorba's Corner
and Zorba's Gyro.
   In two hotels _ the Westin Peachtree Plaza and Hyatt Regency _
delegates can have drinks and dinner in a revolving restaurant,
watching the city spin below.
   Convention organizers, however, have warned restaurant owners
not to expect too much business from the Democrats, unless the
businessmen are willing to stay open much later than usual to
accommodate delegates after the long evening sessions.
   Other places to visit in Atlanta include:
   _ The High Museum of Art, a 130,000-square-foot museum with a
permanent collection that includes European and American paintings
and sculpture and West African sculpture and decorative arts.
   _ The Jimmy Carter Library, which includes a replica of the Oval
Office and Carter's presidential memorabilia.
   _ The Martin Luther King Jr. Center For Nonviolent Social
Change, adjacent to Ebenezer Baptist Church, the civil rights
leader's base, and a block away from his birthplace. King's tomb is
at the center, which also features a display of memorabilia.
   _ Zoo Atlanta, a newly renovated attraction. It recently
unveiled the Ford African Rain Forest featuring the city's famous
gorilla, Willie B.
   _ Cyclorama, next to the zoo, which features a 100-year-old
painting depicting the Civil War Battle of Atlanta. Spectators sit
in a revolving platform while listening to a narrative of the
battle.
   _ Fernbank Science Center, one of the nation's largest
planetariums with regularly scheduled programs.
   _ Fox Theatre, built in 1920 as an open courtyard in a Moorish
city. Now a national landmark, a renovation was recently completed
and tours are available, although the building is a working theater
and concert hall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880711-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RomanMarbles     07-11 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roman Marbles,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ancient Sculptures Arrive At Emory, First Trip Outside Italy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Photographs'' from antiquity of a Roman
empress, Hadrian's lover Antinous and various slaves and private
citizens go on exhibit Thursday on their first trip outside Italy.
   The 19 marble portrait sculptures from imperial Rome are from
the vast collection of the Roman National Museum, which agreed to
loan them for an exhibit by the Emory University Museum of Art and
Archaeology.
   Emory financed the packing, shipping and publication of a
catalog co-written by Maxwell Anderson, director of the Emory
museum, and Leila Nista, inspector of archaeology for the Roman
museum. Following an international symposium next January on
private portraiture in the Roman world, the busts return to Italy
for their first exhibit at the Roman National Museum.
   The current exhibit of Roman portraiture will remain at Emory
until Jan. 3. ``It's here for the longest period of time allowed by
Italian law to the day _ six months,'' said Anderson, who was a
visiting professor at the University of Rome last year.
   The wealth of information about the original location, function
and method of display for most of the busts ``furnish invaluable
evidence about the uses of portraiture in antiquity,'' Anderson
said.
   Romans from most economic classes could afford life-sized
sculptured heads of themselves and it was customary for slaves to
commission their portraits when they were freed, he said. After
subjects died, their sculptures usually were buried along with
their remains or were placed on display in a gallery in the home of
their descendants.
   Among the marble busts are an elegant woman and an older,
melancholy man, fashioned around the time of Nero in the first
century, A.D.
   ``These were slaves of the first imperial family of Rome,'' said
Anderson.
   They found in an underground tomb just outside the city walls in
1847, but have never been displayed until now, Anderson said.
   Also on exhibit is a bust of the Empress Faustina Minor found in
the late 1800s in the Roman Forum's House of the Vestal Virgins.
This mother of 13 children by Emperor Marcus Aurelius apparently
was honored with a portrait display for lending her support to a
renovation of the temple, Anderson said.
   The bust of Antinous was found in 1869 in the sanctuary of the
Earth mother goddess Magna Mater at Ostia, a seaport colony for
which Hadrian served as benefactor, according to the exhibit
catalog.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880711-0079 </DOCNO>
