<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Kenya-Shakespeare     07-11 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Kenya-Shakespeare,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Wants Shakespeare Taught In Kenyan Schools Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi wants Kenya to
scrap a policy that forbids the nation's high schools to teach
William Shakespeare's plays, the Kenya Times reported Monday.
   The plays were dropped from school courses in 1981 in what an
official report said was a move to get rid of ``the colonial
hangover in independent Kenya,'' which gained independence from
Britain in 1963.
   Moi on Sunday urged the Education Ministry to change its policy,
saying he regarded the British writer as ``an international
figure.''
   ``The Ministry of Education dropped Shakespeare thinking it is
colonial. But I do not see why it should not be part of our
syllabus in secondary schools,'' Moi was quoted as saying in a
speech.
</TEXT>
