<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Helicopter Escape at New Mexico Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter landed in a state prison
recreation yard today, picked up two inmates and made a daring
getaway under fire from guards, corrections officials said.
   The prison was immediately locked down and a head count was
under way to determine who had escaped, said Don Caviness, a
spokesman for the New Mexico Corrections Department.
   Department of Public Safety spokesman Dan Taylor said the brown
and beige helicopter apparently flew into the area at a low
altitude about 9:40 a.m.
   The chopper picked up two inmates and took off, flying away at
low altitude as corrections officers blazed away. Taylor said New
Mexico National Guard and U.S. Customs Service helicopters have
taken to the air searching for the craft.
   The Penitentiary of New Mexico, 12 miles southwest of here,
activated its emergency notification system to the press and nearby
residents, informing them of the escape.
