<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-11 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite temperatures in the 90s, a 1910
Stanley Steamer showed its mettle by puffing up Dead Horse Hill in
record time in a recreation of a race that was an early proving
ground for motorized horsepower.
   Sue Keith of McClean, Va., guided her 78-year-old steamer up the
mile-long incline in 45 seconds Sunday to eclipse the 54-second
mark established by L.F.N. Baldwin in his Stanley Racing Car in
1909.
   From 1905 until 1911, the climb sponsored by the Worcester
Automobile Club was one of new automobile industry's major tests,
annually attracting more than 10,000 spectators.
   The race was first recreated in 1985 by a company celebrating
its centennial, and this year three other 100-year-old companies
joined in staging it.
   The event attracted 56 antique autos. One of the slowest took
eight minutes to climb the hill, but most managed in about three
minutes.
   ``It's an event I'm glad to see re-enacted,'' said Peter Morgan
of Morgan Construction, one of the sponsors. ``It's fun to go up
the hill and be cheered at every crest.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can win for losing after all if you bought a
ticket for Saturday's Michigan Lottery Daily-4 game bearing the
number 9696.
   The actual winning number was 9690. But the number 9696 was
written down by a lottery employee to be read during a live
television broadcast of lottery numbers.
   Holders of tickets bearing both numbers will receive prizes,
officials said.
   ``Although the correct Daily-4 numbers were furnished to news
media and the retail ticket outlets, lottery officials have vowed
to pay on both numbers rather than disappoint players who would
have won with the number that was announced,'' Lottery Commissioner
Michael Carr said in a statement.
   Payouts on either number will range from $104 to $5,000,
depending on the order in which they were played, said Jack
Schaffer, Carr's chief deputy. Daily-4 tickets cost $1.
</TEXT>
