<HEAD>Last Ballots in Robins Reorganization Arrive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voting ended Monday on the A.H. Robins Co.
reorganization plan, which specifies that the maker of the Dalkon
Shield intrauterine birth control device would be purchased by
American Home Products Corp. of New York.
   Stockholders, creditors and claimants in Dalkon Shield
litigation faced a 5 p.m. deadline for delivering ballots to
Corporation Trust Co., a Wilmington, Del., firm hired by Robins to
tabulate the results.
   Robins was forced to file for protection under Chapter 11 of
federal bankruptcy law in 1985 after thousands of women sued the
company, saying they were injured by the Dalkon Shield.
   Under the reorganization plan, Dalkon Shield claimants would
share from a trust of $2.31 billion to $2.735 billion. Also,
Robins' creditors would be paid in full, and stockholders would
receive $29 per share of their Robins stock.
   The results of the vote will be released at Monday's hearing in
U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Robins spokesman John Taylor said.
</TEXT>
