<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--TimeCapsule     07-11 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Time Capsule,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peach Pit Among Items Found In Time Capsule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A peach pit and barber tools were among
the items found in a 100-year-old time capsule from the cornerstone
of the Benton County Courthouse.
   The capsule was opened Saturday as part of ceremonies
rededicating the building.
   Secretary of State Barbara Roberts pried the lid open, then
helped State Archivist Layne Sawyer removed the contents as County
Commissioner Dale Schrock broadcast the discovery to a crowd of
about 300 people.
   Besides the pit, the officials found tools from Jesse Spencer's
Barbershop and Bathing Salon, a pewter and silver teapot, and
several coins, including an 1871 Indian head penny, an 1888 nickel,
an 1876 dime and an 1854 half-penny.
   Also in the capsule were a leather-bound copy of The General
Laws of Oregon and newspapers, including a July 4, 1888, copy of
the Morning Oregonian.
   A new capsule with 1988 items is to be placed in the cornerstone
this fall.
</TEXT>
