<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HelicopterEscape 4thLd-Writethru a0587 07-11 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Escape, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0587,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Helicopter Escape, Aerial Chase From New Mexico Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs, chopper was met by three state police
officers at Mid-Valley Airport, quote from Caviness on escape not
envisioned, picking up 8th graf pvs, ``The inmates were xxx</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY80</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter plucked two convicted
murderers and a thief from a state prison yard under fire from
guards today, but the chopper was forced down and those aboard were
captured after an 80-mile aerial chase, officials said.
   The helicopter flew into the Penitentiary of New Mexico about
9:50 a.m. and picked up the three inmates, said Don Caviness, a
spokesman for the New Mexico Corrections Department.
   It flew to Mid-Valley Airport in Los Lunas, about 80 miles south
of here, where it was met by three state police officers, Caviness
said.
   Two of the inmates got out of the helicopter, and one of them
was wounded and captured in a gun battle, according to Ronni Crago,
spokeswoman for the Bernalillo County sheriff's department. The
helicopter took off again and the other inmate fled into on foot
and was being hunted, Crago said.
   The chopper was then chased across the Albuquerque area by a
U.S. Customs Service helicopter and other aircraft and forced down
at Albuquerque International Airport. Two people were taken into
custody at the airport, authorities said.
   Caviness said about 100 inmates were in the prison recreation
yard at the time of the escape. He said guards opened fire from two
towers, but he didn't know if the helicopter was hit.
   The penitentiary was immediately locked down and a head count
was taken to determine who escaped, Caviness said.
   Caviness, when asked whether today's type of escape ever was
envisioned, said: ``This is beyond what we had planned for.''
   The inmates were identified as Daniel Mahoney, 30, serving life
plus 60 years for second-degree murder and armed robbery in
Florida; Francis Preston Mitchell, 26, serving life for
first-degree murder in Utah; and Randy Mack Lackey, 19, of Curry
County, N.M., serving a nine year sentence for larceny.
   Mahoney and Mitchell were being held under an interstate compact
that provides for exchange of prisoners. Caviness said Lackey was a
helicopter pilot and was wounded in the gun battle at Los Lunas.
   In a previous helicopter escape in November 1986, a woman
serving time for bank robbery was snatched from the yard of a
federal prison at Dublin, Calif., by her lover. The couple were
caught 10 days later in a shopping mall while picking up a set of
wedding rings.
   The escape prompted federal prison officials around the country
to build ``chopper stoppers,'' massive wire grids covering prison
yards and other open areas. About 20 of 47 federal prisons had such
barriers in place or under construction by the end of 1986, the
federal Bureau of Prisons said.
   In December 1987, two prisoners fled a maximum-security in
Britain's first helicopter escape. The helicopter had been
chartered to fly over a golf course, then the pilot was forced at
gunpoint to land at the prison.
   In July 1987, a man awaiting trial for bank robbery escaped from
prison in Nice, France, by grabbing onto a rope dangling from a
helicopter. He and an accomplice were captured because some
children thought they were seeing a movie being filmed and followed
the men to their hideout.
   The New Mexico prison suffered one of the most deadly riots in
U.S. prison history when 33 inmates were killed by fellow prisoners
on Feb. 2-3, 1980.
   The prison suffered a mass escape on July 4, 1987, when seven
prisoners broke out. All were eventually recaptured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
