<DOCNO> AP880711-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SeasideMystery Bjt   07-11 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seaside Mystery, Bjt,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beach Town Angered, Frustrated by Girl's Disappearance</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PD2</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First name ``Tiac'' in 12th graf is correct.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GEARHART, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of residents of this coastal town
showed up to help search a beach where a missing teen-ager's
bicycle was found hidden in the brush.
   Within days, state police concluded that 15-year-old Dorene
Raterman had been killed at Del Ray Beach, just a half-mile from
her home, and then two men were arrested in connection with her
death.
   But Dorene's body has not been found. And that leaves the case
resting largely on the testimony of one of the men under arrest,
described as slightly retarded, who says the other one admitted
killing the girl. The second man denies it.
   And as frustration and anger grow, there's been talk in town of
vigilantism.
   ``My son works in a plywood mill and he says that's all they
talk about,'' said Jon G. Blissett, operator of the Gearhart
Chevron station for 26 years. ``There's a lot of people who would
like to get these two guys out of jail. They'd get them to talk.''
   For Judy and Jack Raterman, parents of five boys, waiting for
final word on their only daughter is a nightmare.
   ``It's the most helpless thing in the world,'' Mrs. Raterman
said in an interview. ``There's nothing anybody can do. It's like
being stabbed with a knife _ every day.''
   Dorene left a note to her parents on June 15, saying she would
return home soon from a bike ride to Del Ray Beach.
   ``The beach is something we all frequent,'' Mrs. Raterman said.
``It's just a very quiet, peaceful place. Normally it doesn't get a
lot of traffic like some of the other beaches do.''
   Police got their first major break in the case when a man
reported seeing a girl on a bicycle and two men in a gold MGB
sports car near the beach the evening of June 15.
   The description of the car led them to Tiac K. Eastman, 25, of
Astoria, son of a former county sheriff. Eastman admitted he and
Anthony P. Mullins, both dishwashers at a hotel in nearby Seaside,
had driven to the beach that night in Eastman's car to drink beer
and talk, according to a court affidavit.
   Eastman told police he and Mullins saw the girl, and Mullins
went to talk to her. He said he later heard a scream and that when
Mullins returned he told Eastman he had strangled the girl with a
small chain he carried to secure his wallet, the affidavit said.
   Although Eastman indicated several areas where the body might be
found, searches yielded nothing. He was indicted on a charge of
hindering prosecution for allegedly driving Mullins from the scene.
   The affidavit also said police seized blood-stained clothing and
a set of radio earphones from the apartment of Mullins' father in
Seaside. Mullins, 20, stayed there until he left for San Francisco,
where he was arrested June 29.
   The blood was the same type as Dorene's, and the Ratermans told
police they believed Dorene had her portable radio when she went to
the beach, the affidavit says.
   Mullins has said he's innocent, and an automatic innocent plea
was entered at his arraignment Monday. He was held without bail on
kidnapping and murder charges.
   Police won't speculate publicly on a motive.
   ``It wasn't a premeditated act. It was just a crime of
opportunity,'' said Ed Hauer Jr., coordinator of the Clatsop County
Search and Rescue Team.
   District Attorney Steve Gerttula won't speculate whether he has
enough evidence to convict Mullins.
   Without the body, the case appears to rest heavily on the
testimony of Eastman. If his testmony is thrown out of court,
Mullins could be set free, Gerttula said.
   That could put Mullins in greater trouble in the community.
   When Mullins was taken to court for arraignment last week, he
wore a bulletproof vest. When Eastman was arraigned, the hearing
was held in secret because the judge feared for Eastman's safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
