<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0894</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY44,JO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MABLETHORPE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sherry Dorey swiveled her way to
victory in the first British Belly Dancing Championship, topping a
field of eight contestants to claim the $255 first prize.
   Mrs. Dorey, 32, learned her art in the United Arab Emirates on
the Persian Gulf. She competed Sunday in Mablethorpe, on the
eastern England coast.
   Mrs. Dorey, who performs under the stage name Shareena, said she
one night earned $3,400 in the Emirates.
   ``Good belly dancers are highly respected people in the Middle
East,'' said Mrs. Dorey, who works as an assistant in a law firm.
   She said she dances around Britain, sometimes taking along her
husband, Ian, who plays bongo drums.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. John Jenrette, a
recovering alcoholic, says helping an organization for children of
alcoholics is a way to repay his former district.
   Jenrette said he will be spokesman for the new John Jenrette
Center for the Children of Alcoholics, which was organized by some
of his associates.
   The center will focus on pre-teens and direct people to drug and
alcohol abuse programs. It will also sponsor a summer camp for
children who have an alcoholic parent.
   ``I've seen these children. They're generally neglected and
cannot communicate. They keep it inside and it comes out later.
It's a big undertaking but it could be of massive benefit,'' he
said.
   Jenrette, a Democrat, has said his own alcoholism contributed to
his involvement in the federal Abscam scandal. He was convicted in
1980 of conspiracy and accepting a bribe.
   Jenrette, who represented South Carolina's 6th District for six
years, lost his bid for re-election in 1980. In April, he scrapped
plans to try to reclaim the seat.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Denise St. Aubyn Hubbard, 64, battled
equipment failures and went without food and sleep for the final 24
hours of her 34-day journey to become the oldest woman to sail
across the Atlantic Ocean alone.
   The Great Britain resident was the 70th sailor to finish the
Carlsberg Single-Handed Transatlantic Yacht Race when she arrived
in Newport on Saturday. Frenchman Philippe Poupon won the race with
a 10-day ocean crossing that ended June 15.
   Along the way, St. Aubyn Hubbard jury-rigged her automatic
steering equipment after the main and backup systems on her 42-foot
yacht failed, and hauled in yards of sodden canvas when an
automatic furling mechanism broke and a sail fell into the water.
   She managed without food and sleep in the final 24 hours to cope
with a failed navigational system.
   St. Aubyn Hubbard said she rejected the idea of heading for the
Azores for a stop after her troubles began.
   ``I'm not someone who likes going backward,'' she said. ``I had
a strong feeling that I would make it to this side.''
   A 1948 Olympic diver, St. Aubyn Hubbard was breaking world
women's swimming records at 14. She said she took up sailing in the
mid-1960s as a way to earn a living after her marriage broke up.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beauty is in the eye of the beholder, and for
fashion photographer Francesco Scavullo, the six most beautiful
women on television are Nicollette Sheridan, Kim Alexis, Delta
Burke, Phylicia Rashad, Diane Sawyer and Courteney Cox.
