<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1537EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrashHoax     07-11 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Hoax,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Crash Hoaxer Sentenced To A Year In Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of faking a plane crash
during a blizzard was sentenced Monday to a year in prison and
ordered to have a psychiatric evaluation.
   The radio report of a downed jet with three dead passengers and
a badly injured pilot sparked a search that cost $50,000 and
involved as many as 100 people, 20 aircraft and six police agencies.
   Mark Blair, 29, was convicted May 4 of making a false report to
the government, which carries a maximum penalty of five years in
prison and a $10,000 fine.
   Blair said he was not surprised by the sentence, but insists he
is innocent and plans to appeal. ``I feel that the jury didn't
listen,'' Blair said.
   U.S. Circuit Court Judge Hugh Bownes, standing in for ailing
U.S. District Judge Shane Devine, said at the sentencing that Blair
must have known the report would set off a massive ground and air
search.
   ``It seems obvious to me ... that there is some kind of mental
aberration involved for a normal person to set this kind of event
in action,'' said Bownes, who recommended that Blair be sent to a
federal prison in Butner, N.C., that has psychiatric facilities.
   He also ordered Blair to seek counseling during two years'
probation after he serves his sentence.
   At Blair's trial, David Webster, a Navy reservist and Delta
Airlines pilot, said he and his Navy crew tracked the voice of a
man who talked sporadically saying he was loosing blood, was
chilled and weak, and that at least one person in his plane was
dead.
   They were on a flight from Florida to Maine on Jan. 8 when they
were asked to assist in the search. Webster testified the crew was
overcome by emotion when the man said he heard the Navy plane
overhead.
   ``People in my plane were screaming and yelling. ... I got tears
in my eyes thinking, `We're going to get this guy out,' '' Webster
said.
   Blair testified he couldn't have committed the hoax because he
was asleep.
   But one of his neighbors in Laconia, about 20 miles north of
Concord, said he heard the sound of a two-way radio through Blair's
window and a voice crying out for help.
   Bownes denied a request that Blair be released while he appeals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
