<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1540EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Minnelli     07-11 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Minnelli,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liza: Learned to Be a Friend to Myself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though still an extrovert at heart, Liza
Minnelli says she is cultivating a quiet and reflective side of her
personality.
   ``I'm learning to be a friend to myself,'' she says in the
August issue of Ladies' Home Journal. ``Once a day, you say to
yourself, `How are you, honey? How are you doing?'''
   After years of drinking and taking pills, she kicked her
chemical dependencies during a stay at the Betty Ford Center.
   ``Chemical dependency is a sad, lonely story that millions of
women share,'' she said. ``The only solution is education. If I can
spare somebody from going through what I went through, I'll gladly
do that.''
   Now she dances and does 200 sit-ups a day to stay in shape.
``I've never felt so wonderful in my whole life,'' she says. ``I
feel younger than I've ever felt. Carefree.''
   And she's learned to accept herself. ``We can't all look like
Elizabeth Taylor but we can look like that inside,'' she said. ``If
you get your mind right, you can do anything.''
</TEXT>
