<HEAD>Settlement Reached Over Using Boy In Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A settlement has been reached in a lawsuit
involving a juvenile used in an undercover investigation of male
prostitution.
   The $12.5 million lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in 1985
against the Lexington Urban County Government, alleged that police
used a 14-year-old boy in the 1984 investigation without obtaining
consent from him or his mother.
   Attorneys for the American Civil Liberties Union, who
represented the mother, would not release the amount of the June 27
settlement at the request of Lexington officials.
   The case had been scheduled for trial later this summer.
   Police Chief John McFadden said new guidelines were put in place
on how to deal with similar undercover investigations before the
lawsuit was filed.
