<DOCNO> AP880711-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Anti-ApartheidWall     07-11 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Apartheid Wall,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yale Says Anti-Apartheid Wall Can Stay Up Until Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 40-by-8-foot wall denouncing apartheid
in South Africa will remain under police protection at its
prominent Yale University site until school officials decide its
fate this fall.
   Yale Secretary Sheila Wellington said Sunday the school will
review its policies on freedom of expression when students and
faculty return, and ``it did not seem to be the mature thing to do
to destroy the wall before the review.''
   University officials originally told anti-apartheid activists
the plywood wall, which replaced symbolic shanties destroyed by
arson June 5, could stay for four days. However, the school later
decided it could be erected periodically if it were dismantled and
put in storage for the summer.
   ``Obviously, to react in haste while the university is not in
session and (while) we cannot have the benefit of the ideas and
opinions of faculty and staff and students seems to us to raise
problems accordingly,'' Wellington said.
   Yale's Coalition Against Apartheid, which built the wall,
declared the decision a victory.
   The coalition had said it would not dismantle the structure
until Yale sold all its stock holdings in companies that do
business in South Africa.
   Wellington said it was not a victory for the coalition, but a
decision by Yale President Benno C. Schmidt and herself to
carefully review the school's position.
   Yale has provided 24-hour police protection for the structure,
which Wellington said has been the subject of several arson threats.
   The wall was built June 16 to replace a shantytown that had
stood in the same location for more than two years.
</TEXT>
