<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MultipleKillings     07-11 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Attempt To Intervene In Simmons' Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R. Gene Simmons, convicted of two
murders and accused of 14 others, was competent when he decided not
to appeal his death sentence, the state Supreme Court ruled Monday.
   The ruling means Gov. Bill Clinton may set a new execution date
for Simmons, 47, who had been scheduled to die June 27. The court
issued a stay of execution June 20 at the request of the Rev. Louis
J. Franz, who also sought to be appointed Simmons' legal
representative to pursue appeals Simmons rejected.
   The court said Monday there was no legal basis to grant the
request by Franz, of Star City, head of the anti-death penalty
Arkansas Churches for Life. His attorney, Mark Cambiano of
Morrilton, said an appeal was likely.
   ``I don't know whether we'll try to go straight to the U.S.
Supreme Court or what,'' Cambiano said. ``I'm disappointed. I felt
and I still feel that we are correct in our assessment of the
situation.''
   Simmons was convicted May 12 of two counts of murder in a
rampage Dec. 28 in Russellville in which four other people were
wounded. Police later found the bodies of 14 relatives on his
property north of Dover and he is charged in those deaths.
   Simmons gave up his right to appeal, asked that no one interfere
in his case and said he wanted to die at the earliest possible
date. Franklin County Circuit Court Judge John S. Patterson ruled
May 16 that Simmons knew what he was doing in giving up the appeal.
Franz appealed.
   Lawyers for Simmons, following Simmons' instructions, opposed
Franz' attempt to become his representative. So did the state and
Prosecuting Attorney Johm Bynum of Russellville.
   The Supreme Court said Monday it would review cases of a people
sentenced to die who decided against appeals, but refused to
declare that review of death sentences is mandatory.
   It said Simmons was competent to give up his right to appeal.
</TEXT>
