<HEAD>Cruise Preemie Stable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baby girl born seven weeks prematurely aboard a
cruise liner last week was in stable condition Monday at Miami
Children's Hospital, a spokeswoman said.
   The 2-pound, 11-ounce girl was rushed by Coast Guard helicopter
to the hospital Wednesday after her mother, Wylene McCollum, gave
birth in the infirmary of the Emerald Seas cruise ship off Little
Stirrup Cay in the Bahamas.
   Mrs. McCollum named her surprise passenger Emera Cay McCollum
after the ship and the island where the girl was born.
   ``She's in stable condition, but still in the ventilator,''
hospital spokeswoman Ava Osle said Monday, adding that she did not
know when the baby would be released.
