<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HijackingSuspect     07-11 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijacking Suspect,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jordanian Witnesses To Hijacking Give U.S. Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two crew members of a Jordanian airliner
hijacked in 1985 have entered U.S. protective custody in order to
testify against a suspected Lebanese terrorist charged in the case,
a prosecutor said Monday.
   The disclosure that the two unidentified members of the Royal
Jordanian airliner had entered the federal witness protection
program was made at a pre-trial hearing in the case of Fawaz
Younis, charged with leading the June 11, 1985 hijacking.
   The former airline employees left their homes in the Middle East
and were placed under U.S. protection following ``their decision to
testify in the trial,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Ramsey Johnson told
U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker.
   A Middle Eastern man who identified Younis at a court-ordered
lineup is also being sought as a witness, Johnson said.
   The FBI is trying to locate the man, who was a passenger on
board the hijacked airliner, because ``we believe he is an
excellent witness,'' he added.
   A former member of Lebanon's Shiite Amal militia, Younis was
arrested last September after he was lured aboard an FBI-chartered
yacht in the Mediterranean by the prospect, according to FBI
agents, of completing a drug deal.
   Jamal Hamdan, a former resident of Cyprus who cooperated with
the FBI's efforts to entice his former friend onto the yacht, is
also in protective custody.
   The federal witness protection program gives people new
identities and helps them set up life in a new location to protect
them from reprisals for testifying against criminal defendants.
   Younis is awaiting trial on charges that he led a group of five
armed men who stormed the Boeing 727 at Beirut International
Airport and forced it to fly to several locations around the
Mediterranean before it returned to Beirut.
   The plane's 74 passengers and crew members, including several
Jordanian sky marshals, were let off the plane before it was blown
up on the runway.
   Parker indicated that he had found a classified document that
contradicts an earlier prosecution statement that the FBI never
considered placing a defense lawyer on the Navy ship where Younis
was interrogated four days after his arrest.
   The secret document was forwarded to the U.S. Court of Appeals
here, which is considering whether Younis' confession to FBI agents
should be admitted as evidence.
   Parker ruled in February that the confession was illegally
obtained because Younis, suffering seasickness and pain from two
broken wrists, was in no condition to exercise his constitutional
right to remain silent.
   Younis suffered the two wrist fractures when FBI agents slammed
him to the deck of the yacht.
   In his opinion, which prosecutors have appealed, Parker said he
couldn't understand why the FBI, during its lengthy planning of the
arrest operation, had not considered putting an attorney aboard the
Navy vessel to advise Younis during the interrogation.
   At Monday's hearing, the judge noted that Johnson had previously
told him the idea ``just didn't come up.''
   Parker, indicating the secret document he had examined
contradicted that answer, told Johnson: ``You are charged with the
knowledge of the information contained'' in the secret documents
turned over to the court.
   On June 30, the appeals court ordered Parker to conduct a
hearing on admitting the document into evidence under the
Classified Information Procedures Act.
   The appeals court said the document ``raises questions that go
directly'' to Younis' claim he was denied a right to counsel during
his interrogation.
   Parker gave Johnson 48 hours to contact government agencies
about declassifying the document and scheduled a hearing for July
18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
