<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Gorbachev Bjt   07-11 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Gorbachev, Bjt,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Leader Urges Breaking Impasse on Conventional Arms</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WAR50,51,52</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev offered
Monday to withdraw an unspecified number of air forces from Eastern
Europe if NATO drops plans to deploy 72 U.S.-built, F-16
fighter-bombers in Italy.
   Gorbachev also said that East and West European leaders should
informally explore ways to break the impasse in negotiations aimed
at reducing conventional forces in Europe.
   The Communist Party chief made the proposals in an address to
the Polish parliament, the Sejm, at the start of a six-day visit to
Poland.
   ``Verbally everyone is for the necessity of reducing
conventional arms and in practice they are still expanding military
reserves,'' said Gorbachev.
   The Soviets want to break that pattern, he added.
   ``For instance, we are ready to withdraw our analogous air
forces from the extended bases in Eastern Europe if NATO agrees not
to deploy its 72 F-16 fighter-bombers.''
   Gorbachev also reiterated a Soviet plan for resuming
conventional arms talks with an exchange of troop data and an
initial withdrawal of 500,000 troops from both NATO and Warsaw Pact
forces in Europe.
   The Soviet leader offered to explore informally with the Western
powers ways to break the deadlock that has long blocked progress
toward a conventional arms reduction agreement.
   The sides have never agreed on how to count their respective
armies and have found no starting point for force reductions.
   ``If NATO shows such readiness, we can discuss the problem of
the lack of balance before the start of official talks about the
data concerning troops,'' he said. Western observers claim Warsaw
Pact forces far outnumber NATO units facing them in Europe.
   NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner expressed skepticism
about the new Soviet offer.
   ``We are committed to establishing a stable and secure balance
of conventional forces at lower levels in Europe,'' Woerner said in
a statement issued in Brussels, Belgium.
   ``A focus on aircraft does not meet this central requirement,''
he added. ``We need asymmetrical reductions, notably in tanks and
artillery, in order to eliminate the most worrying disparities.''
   Referring indirectly to a sore point in the relations between
the Soviet Union and Poland, Gorbachev pledged to pursue the search
for facts explaining the ``blank spots'' in Soviet history.
   But Gorbachev did not mention the massacre of 4,500 Polish
military officers in the Katyn forest shortly after the outbreak of
World War II.
   A joint study commission already has been established to
investigate what happened during Soviet dictator Josef Stalin's
rule, and there had been speculation before Gorbachev's arrival
that he would acknowledge Soviet responsibility for the slaughter.
   ``One cannot change history,'' the Soviet leader said. ``But one
can and should draw conclusions from it.''
   ``We condemn Stalinist repressions,'' Gorbachev said. ``As it is
known, they also covered many Polish communists,'' who disappeared
after being summoned to Moscow by Stalin.
   Several youths staged a demonstration in central Warsaw before
Gorbachev's speech, waving banners saying, ``We demand the truth
about Katyn. Reparation for deportations.''
   The Polish Communist Party chief, Wojciech Jaruzelski, greeted
Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, when their Aeroflot jet arrived at
Warsaw's Okecie Airport.
   The Gorbachevs then approached a crowd of several hundred
flag-waving citizens, and Gorbachev paused to sign several
autographs and chat with people in the crowd.
   Gorbachev's motorcade made an unannounced stop at a traffic
circle in Warsaw, where the Soviet leader got out to greet
onlookers and sign copies of his book, ``Perestroika.''
   Gorbachev and Jaruzelski then conferred privately for two hours
at communist party headquarters. The official news agency PAP said
the two exchanged views on economic, political and social renewal
taking place in their countries.
   The visit to Poland, to be capped at week's end with a summit
meeting of the Warsaw Pact countries, marks Gorbachev's first major
public appearance since the July 1 close of the Soviet Communist
Party Conference in Moscow.
   Government and opposition leaders in Poland expressed hope the
Soviet leader would reinvigorate the movement for Polish economic
reforms.
   The leading opposition group, the outlawed labor union
Solidarity, issued a statement welcoming Gorbachev and lauding his
effort to increase open debate.
   Solidarity said it hoped the visit would lead to significant
changes in Poland and in Soviet-Polish relations.
   But Gennady Gerasimov, the Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman,
told reporters asking about Solidarity, ``I think it would be
better if these forces join the process of socialist renewal, and
not inhibit it as sometimes happens today.''
</TEXT>
