<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1700EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Teamsters     07-11 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Teamsters Official Eyed For Top Union Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Brotherhood of Teamsters'
top official in New England, William J. McCarthy, is emerging as a
possible consensus challenger to Jackie Presser's choice for the
union's presidency, sources close to the Teamsters said Monday.
   Presser, who died Saturday night in a suburban Cleveland
hospital after an 18-month battle against lung and brain cancer,
had turned over temporary control of the government-besieged union
in May to Secretary-Treasurer Weldon Mathis, naming him interim
president for 120 days.
   Mathis, 62, is still considered the odds-on-favorite to succeed
Presser, but not without a challenge from some of the 16 regional
vice presidents and board members unhappy with with the way he has
run the union while Presser was incapacitated most of the past year.
   One Teamster insider said ``the big question'' is whether enough
of those 16 vice presidents, many of whom would like the top job,
can unite behind one challenger to Mathis.
   Sources said that McCarthy, of Boston, a Teamster vice president
since 1969, has support from at least five other vice presidents
for mounting a challenge.
   Under the Teamsters' constitution, Mathis and the 16 vice
presidents are required to meet within 15 days of Presser's death
to elect a successor.
   The jockeying is intensifying just two weeks after the
government, claiming all of the Teamsters' top leaders are
influenced by racketeers, filed suit to place the entire union
under the control of a court-appointed trustee.
   The government contends in the suit that crime bosses in New
York and Chicago engineered the elevation of Presser and his
predecessor, Roy Williams, to the union's presidency in 1983 and
1981, respectively.
   Teamster officials have vehemently denied the allegations and a
federal criminal court jury in New York two months ago found that
the government had insuffient evidence to back them up.
   Meanwhile, spokesmen for the union are mum about Presser's
successor.
   ``Nobody's talking about it except the press,'' Duke Zeller, the
Teamsters director of information, said Monday. ``Nothing is going
to happen until after the funeral (Tuesday).''
   Zeller said no executive board meeting has been scheduled yet,
adding that the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta and a
conference meeting of Michigan Teamsters, both next week, may be
complicating factors.
   Until Presser's death, Mathis had intended to host a reception
next week in Atlanta, his home town and base of power in the union,
symbolizing an end to the Teamsters' 32-year enchantment with
Republican presidential candidates.
   Presser picked Mathis to be his number two official in 1985. A
year later, Presser initiated a rewriting of the Teamsters'
constitution so that Mathis, rather the Joseph Trerotola of New
York, the union's ranking vice president, would assume interim
control if he were disabled.
   Mathis, according to Teamster insiders, angered many of the
``old guard'' vice presidents in the way the reins were passed to
him two months ago. Eight of them boycotted the first board meeting
that he convened afterwards.
   In addition, Mathis' strength has been weakened by majority
rank-and-file ``no'' votes on the union's two biggest contracts
this year _ the National Master Freight Agreement, covering most of
the unionized interstate trucking industry, and a three-year accord
with United Parcel Service.
   Because it takes a two-thirds membership vote to disapprove a
contract, they were declared ratified.
   But in a rare departure from the Teamsters' tradition to keep
dissent at the top within the family, McCarthy challenged the terms
of the freight accord openly in conversations with reporters and
addresses before local union halls.
   ``What's amazing is that all this infighting has sloshed out in
the open,'' said Ken Paff, an organizer for a 10,000-member
dissident faction called Teamsters for a Democratic Union.
   Other names that have surfaced as possible challengers to Mathis
for succeeding Presser include Vice Presidents Arnie Weinmeister of
Seattle, Joseph Morgan of Hallandale, Fla., and Walter Shea of
Washington.
   Sources said Weinmeister and Shea have pulled themselves out of
the running, although both, along with Trerotola, are considered to
have the ability to sway other votes on the board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
