<DOCNO> AP880711-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti-Murder     07-11 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Murder,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Activist Stabbed To Death in Haiti, Government Blamed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Lafontant Joseph, a prominent human
rights activist, was found beaten and stabbed to death Monday in a
jeep near the Port-au-Prince airport, police said.
   ``This murder is a very serious incident,'' Jean-Claude Bajeux,
director of the Ecumenical Center for Human Rights, told The
Associated Press. ``It means that the lives of all militants for
human rights in Haiti are in danger.''
   Paul Latortue, a former senatorial candidate who lives in exile
in Puerto Rico, blamed the murder on government leader Lt. Gen.
Henri Namphy.
   ``I have no doubt that this is a political killing,'' he said.
``It's connected with the government.''
   Joseph, 54, director of Haiti's Center of Education for Human
Rights, was found dead in his four-wheel drive vehicle near Mais
Gate International Airport, just outside the capital. A passerby
recognized the dead man and contacted his family.
   The activist's nephew, physician Ronald Joseph, said Joseph had
been stabbed once in his chest and two or three times in his back.
``The body looked mutilated,'' he said.
   Army Maj. Joseph Baguidy, head of Haiti's Bureau of Criminal
Investigation, said police found blood about 500 yards from the
car, indicating Joseph was killed outside the vehicle.
   There appeared to be more than one assailant, Baguidy said. He
did not elaborate.
   The police official said the seats of the car were found in a
horizontal position and that police discovered a pair of women's
sandals in the vehicle.
   He said it was possible a woman may have been in the car with
Joseph, but that no other body had been located.
   ``We are now examining the blood to see whether there was
another victim,'' he said.
   Radio Metropole, an independent station, said Joseph was last
seen alive by his wife, Raymonde, whom he dropped off at their home
Sunday night. Mrs. Joseph, director of the Haitian Women's
Committee Against Torture, was the first to identify her husband's
body.
   Joseph, a lawyer, founded the Center of Education for Human
Rights in 1986 and was a co-founder of the League of Human Rights.
   In November 1980, under dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier, he was
arrested, jailed and tortured for his outspoken criticism of the
government. Joseph was then ordered to leave Haiti, but refused to
do so.
   Before the national elections scheduled for November 29, which
were suspended because of civil violence, Joseph was a candidate
for a Senate seat on the leftist National Front ticket.
   At the time of his death, the activist was director of the
Elliot Pierre High School.
   Latortue said the killing was connected with an incident last
week in which four men in black uniforms with Uzi machine guns
burst into the home of sociologist Laennec Hurbon while he was
away, ransacked the premises and stole $1,300.
   Joseph and Laennec were both prominent members of the National
Congress of Democratic Movements, a political group working to
organize Haitians and uphold the constitution.
   ``It's an attempt to kill one by one those who argue for
democratic development,'' said Latortue, whose brother Gerard was
foreign minister in the government of President Leslie Manigat, who
was ousted in June.
   ``We have entered a different phase in Haiti now where political
killings in the street are going to take place. They don't arrest
you, they kill you in the streets and make it appear that it is the
work of bandits.''
   ``Haitians now live within a system which gives the lives and
property of its citizens no protection. Anything can happen and no
one can prevent any determined gang of killers from doing as it
sees fit,'' Bajeux said.
   Namphy, who took power in a coup June 19, suspended the
constitution Haitians approved in a March 1987 referendum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
