<HEAD>Train Crash Injures 80 In Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train carrying about 300 passengers
crashed into a stalled cargo train in southeastern Brazil on
Monday, and railroad authorities said 80 people were injured.
   Valeria Hartt, a spokeswoman for the Sao Paulo State Railroad
Co., said in a telephone interview that only one person was
seriously injured.
   The accident occurred in the city of Valinhos 55 miles northwest
of Sao Paulo, South America's largest city.
   ``The passenger train, heading for Sao Paulo, crashed into the
rear of the cargo train which had stalled on the same tracks
because of a mechanical failure,'' Ms. Hartt said.
   Both trains were partially damaged and the track was expected to
be cleared by Monday night when normal service would resume.
   Ms. Hartt said an investigation would be held to determine why
the passenger train was not warned about the stalled cargo train.
