<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TransplantDeath     07-11 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transplant Death,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domino Transplant Recipient Dies 14 Months After Procedure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clinton House, who survived 14 months with a
donated heart and lungs he received after donating his own healthy
heart in the nation's first domino donor transplant, died Monday,
Johns Hopkins Hospital said.
   House, 29, a Baltimore refrigeration mechanic who suffered from
cystic fibrosis, died of complications related to rejection,
according to Phil Kibak, a spokesman at Johns Hopkins.
   House had received the heart and lungs of a brain-dead accident
victim in a 17-hour operation May 10-11, 1987, and donated his
otherwise healthy heart to John Couch, 39, of Yardley, Pa., Kibak
said.
   Couch is reported to be doing well, Kibak said.
   In February, House was placed on a list awaiting a second double
transplant, Kibak said.
   ``Clint never really took off (with the new organs). He had
problems now and again, primarily related to the rejection,'' Kibak
said.
   Cystic fibrosis causes the production of a thick, sticky mucus
that clogs the lungs and digestive system. It is the nation's most
common inherited disease, afflicting about 30,000 Americans, and
usually kills victims by the time they reach their mid-20s.
   House had awaited the new heart and lungs for a year before a
donor was found.
   The heart-lung procedure was the first so-called domino
transplant performed in the United States. Doctors in Great Britain
had earlier performed a similar procedure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
