<HEAD>In Downpour, Tallahassee Buries Officer Slaying In Shoot Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first policeman ever shot and
killed on duty in Florida's capital was buried in a driving rain
Monday after a long funeral procession carried family, friends and
other officers through the downpour.
   The motorcade took slain Officer Ernest Ponce de Leon to his
grave after mourners heard Officer William Scott eulogize him as a
``winner'' who had triumphed over personal setbacks.
   Ponce de Leon, 40, had dropped out of high school but later
returned to earn a diploma and attended Florida State University,
Scott said.
   Troopers, sheriff's deputies and officers from Florida, Georgia
and Alabama packed the Tallahassee church where funeral services
were held. Mourners jammed aisles and spilled onto the lawn.
   Ponce de Leon was killed while checking out the occupants of a
car. Three of the people in the car turned out to be Maryland
prison escapees. All have been charged with first-degree murder.
