<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     07-11 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Informal Weekend Talks Fail To End Strike, But Progress Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Informal weekend talks between the striking
Writers Guild of America and TV and movie producers failed to end
the 19-week strike that has nearly crippled the industry, but at
least one side reported progress.
   ``We're heartened at this point that these informal talks are
continuing,'' guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said Monday.
   The talks between WGA West Executive Director Brian Walton and
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers negotiator J.
Nicholas Counter III have been held by telephone and in person.
They are in contact daily.
   Guild sources, while refusing to predict when the strike might
end, have indicated substantial progress is being made. ``We're
trying to get this town back to work,'' Walton said Monday.
   The guild and the producers alliance are divided on payments for
reruns of one-hour television programs and shows broadcast
overseas. The strike, which began March 7, has triggered sweeping
layoffs throughout Hollywood and has obliterated the fall
television season.
   The guild's negotitating committee met extensively over the last
several days exploring strategies that might end the strike. The
committee met for four hours Friday and five hours Saturday.
   Herb Steinberg, a spokesman for the alliance, discounted the
importance of the informal talks. ``Negotiations are closed. They
are over,'' Steinberg said. ``Our last contract offer is final.''
Steinberg did not deny, however, that Counter and Walton were
meeting.
   Meanwhile, some of Hollywood's top writer-producers joined
forces Friday to discuss other means of resolving the labor
dispute. Among those participating in the meeting were Gary David
Goldberg of ``Family Ties,'' Glenn Gordon Caron of
``Moonlighting,'' Stephen J. Cannell of ``Wiseguy,'' and Steven
Bochco of ``L.A. Law.''
   Some of the entertainment industry's leading agents also are
interceding on a regular basis in an effort to encourage a strike
settlement.
</TEXT>
