<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1914EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ComatoseWoman     07-11 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Comatose Woman,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Feeding Tube Can Be Removed From Comatose Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of a 56-year-old comatose woman
can order doctors to remove the feeding tube keeping her alive and
grant what relatives say would have been her wish to die, a judge
ruled Monday.
   Carol McConnell, a registered nurse who suffered permanent brain
damage in a car accident three years ago, remains in a coma at a
Danbury nursing home. She can breathe but is fed by a tube
connected to her stomach. Doctors said she will die if the tube is
removed.
   In a ruling released Monday, Superior Court Judge Anne C.
Dranginis gave the defendants, including the state attorney
general's office, 20 days to appeal.
   ``This is a wonderful decision in favor of the family, but much
more in favor of the public's right to have its wishes carried out
when a person becomes permanently vegetative and expresses clearly
that they didn't want'' to be kept alive by artificial means, said
Stephen Wise, lawyer for McConnell's family.
   During a trial in June, lawyers for the state argued that a 1985
statute regarding the removal of life-support systems prohibits
withholding ``nutrition and hydration.''
   Wise said Mrs. McConnell's three children believe their mother
was a ``totally informed person who knew about life-support systems
and clearly expressed her wishes that they not be administered.''
   Mrs. McConnell's husband, John McConnell, tearfully told
Dranginis last month that his wife wouldn't have wanted to be kept
alive through extraordinary means.
   Mrs. McConnell was head nurse in the Danbury Hospital emergency
room at the time of her car accident.
   The Society for the Right To Die said Connecticut is one of six
states with laws excluding feeding tubes from the life-sustaining
procedures that can be withheld with a relative's permission or
because the patient has so instructed previously in writing in a
so-called ``living will.''
   Seven states permit removal of feeding tubes, while the
legislation is ambiguous in 12 states and the remainder don't have
laws dealing with the subject, the society said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
