<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Vendors 1stLd-Writethru a0637 07-11 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vendors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch's Peddler Patrol Begins; Vendors Stay Off Streets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `By 2 p.m...' to UPDATE with 3rd cart taken.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peddlers of hot dogs and sushi, frozen yogurt
and hot soup have for five years ignored a law that would keep them
off the sidewalks where business is best. On Monday, the vendors
fell victim to politics.
   In an effort to rid some of the city's busiest corners of
congestion, police armed with forklifts were sent for take out: not
food, but the pushcarts that sell quick and affordable lunches and
snacks. The vendors were there, with their familiar orange-and-blue
umbrellas, but the pushcarts weren't.
   ``We're trying to spoil the policemen's party,'' said hot dog
vendor Thomas Michaelides. ``They'll get no blood from me today.''
   The vendors called their gathering a protest. A spokesman for
Mayor Edward I. Koch called it capitulation to the law that imposes
fines up to $1,000 and storage costs for impounded pushcarts of $65
a day.
   By 5 p.m., only three carts had been confiscated, police said.
   ``They were faced with confiscation and fines and we warned them
of those consequences and as a result we don't have any carts in
those banned areas,'' said Koch spokesman Cliff Chanin.
   ``So we choose to see it as compliance of the law.''
   Koch admitted the crackdown was political arm-twisting to get
the City Council to pass a new law which would allow six vendors,
chosen by lottery, to work each prime street block, three on one
side and three on the other.
   Vendors and council members balked at that, prompting the
crackdown.
   As angry vendors congregated along Sixth Avenue, handing out
leaflets, the M. Parpis Food Distribution Co., which owns 50
vending carts, went to court to fight the ban. Parpis' lawyers
argued in state Supreme Court that the law is an unreasonable use
of regulatory power. Justice Irving Kirschenbaum disagreed.
   John P. Goros, 38, who owns M. Parpis, said he would appeal.
   The 1983 law bans vendors from Manhattan corners between 34th
and 59th streets and between Third and Eighth avenues _ an area
that includes busy Times Square and Rockefeller Center _ in the
Wall Street area; along First Avenue near the United Nations; and
in Fulton Market in Brooklyn.
   There are 3,300 vendors with permanent licenses and an
additional 1,000 allowed to sell food only in summer, according to
the Health Department.
   As Koch was at City Hall telling reporters, ``I'm not an enemy
of peddlers. I'm the friend of peddlers,'' the police unit hit the
streets.
   What did the police action mean to Michaelides, who's been
hawking hot dogs for 25 years, and whose father did it for years
before him?
   ``It means I've got two kids and I'm out of work now,'' said
Michaelides, whose spot on West 57th Street and Broadway is on the
city hit list.
   Ahmed Abelhady said he could not say what he would like to tell
the mayor, but ``it would not be nice.''
   Abelhady, who doles out chicken and beef sandwiches, said he
doesn't like the lottery system because it would force him to
change locations every year.
   ``I know my customers by name. I know what they like,'' he said.
``They're like friends to me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
