<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionRuling     07-11 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Ruling,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Strikes Down Georgia Abortion Notification Ruling _
Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday struck down a Georgia law
requiring minors to tell their parents before getting an abortion,
the second time in as many years the law has failed to pass
constitutional muster.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Hall granted a preliminary injunction
sought by Planned Parenthood to stop implementation of the Parental
Notification Act.
   The law, which requires girls under 18 to notify their parents
before getting an abortion, was to have taken effect July 1. Hall
had blocked its implementation pending his ruling.
   Hall voided a similar but more stringent statute last year after
the Atlanta and Augusta chapters of Planned Parenthood challenged
it, saying it placed too great a burden on teen-age girls.
   The law was rewritten to ease some requirements during the 1988
General Assembly, but the two Planned Parenthood chapters and
Atlanta physician Orrin Moore, who performs abortions, again
challenged it on virtually the same grounds. Their suit was filed
on behalf of more than 4,000 teen-age girls who received abortions
in 1985.
   Under the rewritten law, teen-age girls in some cases would have
had to wait 24 hours after notifying their parents for the abortion
to be performed. The lawsuit challenged that section and also said
the act failed to guarantee anonymity to some girls.
   The suit also challenged a provision of the law that allows a
girl to go to Juvenile Court to obtain a waiver if she does not
wish to notify her parents. The suit said the time involved in
getting such a waiver, sometimes three weeks or more, is too long.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880711-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1922EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     07-11 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corn-Soviets,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Purchase Additional Corn From US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
175,000 metric tons of corn from the United States for delivery
this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two
countries, the Agriculture Department said Monday.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 175,000 tons of
corn would be about 6.9 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.84 per bushel at the
farm level, meaning that the sale could have a farm value of around
$19 million.
   The corn is part of the grain the Soviet Union is committed to
buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls
for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of U.S. grain.
The pact expires Sept. 30, and there have been negotiations for a
new one.
   According to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to
include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. The
Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as
wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two
tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain
equivalent.
   With the latest purchases, the Soviets now have bought 4.54
million tons of corn, plus more than 9 million tons of wheat;
830,700 tons of soybeans, and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
