<1ST_LINE>d w AM-BRF--Cooper-Justice     07-11 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cooper-Justice,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Official Joining Washington Law Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles J. Cooper, assistant attorney general
in charge of the Justice Department's Office of Legal Counsel, is
joining the Washington office of the law firm McGuire, Woods,
Battle & Boothe, it was announced Monday.
   Cooper is to be a partner at the full-service Richmond,
Va.-headquartered law firm, the largest law firm in Virginia with
more than 300 lawyers in eight offices, the firm said in a news
release.
   Cooper will be a litigating attorney before federal agencies and
courts.
   In addition, Michael A. Carvin, Cooper's top aide as deputy
assistant attorney general for the legal counsel's office, also
will join the law firm's Washington office as a litigating attorney.
   Cooper has headed the Office of Legal Counsel for nearly three
years and before then worked in the department's civil rights
division for four years, where he worked closely with William
Bradford Reynolds, who has helped spearhead the Reagan
administration's controversial civil rights policies. Carvin has
been at OLC since May 1987 and before then spent four years in the
department's civil rights division.
