<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Copyright     07-11 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copyright,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Urged to Approve Protection Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said Monday that
U.S. participation in a century-old international accord could help
trim America's $2 billion annual loss to film and recording pirates.
   Assistant Secretary of State Eugene McAllister appeared before
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee to argue for U.S. membership
in the Berne Convention for the Protection of Literary and Artistic
Works, created in 1886.
   ``Today we are experiencing a technolgical revolution involving
such innovations as computers, communications satellites, optical
discs and many more,'' McAllister noted. ``Many international
copyright experts here and abroad believe that the Berne Convention
is a comprehensive and dynamic instrument which meets the
challenges brought on by the new technologioes.''
   McAllister said the Berne Convention could protect U.S.
copyrights in 79 countries, 24 of which do not belong to the
Universal Copyright Convention. The United States is already a
member of that accord.
   Copyright official Ralph Oman testified that U.S.
representatives recently visited Turkey and Egypt with complaints
of pirating, but were told that since the United States did not
belong to the Berne Convention, U.S. rights were not legally
protected in those countries.
   Other countries on the list of 24 are mainly African, including
South Africa. Romania, Thailand and Uruguay are also among them.
   Oman said the list covers ``minor markets but major pirates.''
He did not further identify any of the pirating countries.
   He noted the spread of U.S. popular culture all over the world.
   ``For the first time U.S. films and recorded music now make more
money abroad than in the United States,'' he said.
   The House already has approved the bill for U.S. membership,
which now awaits action by the Senate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880711-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1748EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Airliner-Compensation     07-11 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Compensation,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Compensation Details Yet To Be Worked Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Airliner Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With few comparable parallels to go by, the
Reagan administration began work Monday on the ``huge job'' of
assembling the data necessary for compensating the families who
lost relatives aboard an Iranian airliner downed by a U.S. missile
last week.
   A State Department official said the task will be ``highly
discretionary'' because of the unique nature of the incident, in
which a U.S. Navy warship fired on the passenger plane after
mistaking it for an F-14 fighter.
   It is not clear yet, the official said, whether a flat amount
will be paid for each victim or whether the age, number of
dependents and earnings of the victims will be taken into account
in assessing compensation.
   Also to be determined is what role Congress will be required to
play in providing the funding, said the official, who briefed
reporters on the condition that he not be identified.
   ``We have a huge job ahead of us,'' he said. ``We have a lot of
facts to investigate.''
   The official said it is common practice in such incidents for
the government to seek a statement from the families of each victim
releasing the U.S. government from further liability for the
accident.
   He added that the outcome of a Navy investigation will not
affect the government's decisions on compensation.
   The decision to compensate was based on humanitarian concern,
the official said, adding that such issues as negligence or
culpability by either Iran or the United States will not influence
the process.
   The law does not specify a maximum amount the U.S. government
may pay in such cases.
   Besides Iran, citizens from six other countries werre aboard the
plane when it was shot down on July 3. The official said
compensation won't be based on the nationality of each citizen.
   Complicating the task for the administration is the absence of
diplomatic relations between the United States and Iran. The
official said the Red Crescent, an arm of the Red Cross that
operates in the Middle East, would be an acceptable organization
for making the payments.
   At least two of the precedents that could have a bearing on
amounts of compensation to be paid involve Israel.
   In 1980, Israel agreed to pay the U.S. government $6 million in
compensation for an attack by Israeli forces on an American naval
vessel at the outbreak of 1967 Middle East war. The attack on the
USS Liberty in the eastern Mediterranean left 34 American sailors
dead and 75 wounded.
   Like the Iran plane incident, Israel decided on an ``ex gratia''
payment _ meaning it was made out of sympathy but without an
admssion of fault or liability.
   There also was the case of the Israeli downing of a Libyan
passenger plane that strayed over Israeli territory in the early
1970s. Israel paid families of the victims $30,000 per person.
   In addition, the United States has compensated individuals for
damage done by troops on maneuvers in Central America, and is
paying owners of a fishing boat shot up by mistake in the Persian
Gulf.
   Iraq has agreed to pay compensation to the United States for an
incident in which an Iraqi jet, in another case of mistaken
identity, fired on the USS Stark in May 1987, leaving 37 sailors
dead. Negotiations are continuing.
   But the United States denied liability for damages to neutral
embassies in Tripoli, Libya, in a 1986 bombing raid. And similar
requests were turned down when neutral shipping was struck during
the bombing of Haiphong harbor during the Vietnam war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
