<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MediaCenter-Streets     07-11 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media Center-Streets,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convention `Streets' Bear Famous and Not-So-Famous Names</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Neel is cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The blue and white banners hanging above the
passageways of the media village at the Democratic National
Convention are street signs bearing the names of the famous and
not-so-famous.
   Thomas Jefferson Avenue, Woodrow Wilson Boulevard and other
signs designate each major thoroughfare in the village that was
still being assembled Monday in the Georgia World Congress Center.
   The so-called streets run between trailers of electronic
equipment and blue-curtained makeshift newsrooms. There are no
traffic lights and pedestrians take their chances, stepping over
cables, dodging carts and scooters, ladders and lifts.
   ``We had a huge space,'' said Neel Lattimore, press gallery
supervisor for the DNC. ``So we had to come up with something''
that would enable convention staffers and media personnel to find
their work areas in about 339,000 square feet of exhibit halls.
   The village will accomodate approximately 13,500 reporters and
editors from about 125 news organizations during next week's
convention.
   Jim Thompson, manager of the general contracting firm for the
World Congress Center, suggested the passageways be named after
Democratic presidents, Lattimore said.
   That worked fine through Franklin D. Roosevelt, Harry S. Truman,
John F. Kennedy, Lyndon B. Johnson, Jimmy Carter and even Grover
Cleveland, but then the media arrangements staff ran into a problem.
   ``We ran out of Democratic presidents,'' Lattimore said with a
grin.
   So the side streets are Myers Lane, Podrazik Lane and Lattimore
Lane _ named after himself and co-directors of media arrangements
Cindy Myers and Wally Podrazik.
   ``We take it very seriously, trying to make sure everybody gets
what they need, but this is kind of fun,'' Lattimore said.
   The street sign is the closest Lattimore, who works for a public
relations company in Washington, D.C., will come to fame during the
convention _ he hopes.
   ``Next Monday, if somebody knows my name, there's a problem,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
