<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2003EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HealthCareQuality     07-11 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Health Care Quality,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Planning For Health Care Costs Difficult</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Planning long-range expenditures for Medicare
and other health programs is similar to budgeting defense spending
in that it can be difficult to know what programs will work in the
future, a Democratic senator said Monday.
   ``It's sort of like new missiles in a pipeline,'' said Sen. Jay
Rockefeller of West Virginia. ``Will they work or will they not.
You're talking about what does and doesn't work (in health care)
and we don't necessarily know. ''
   Anticipating ``an avalanche of dollars for the future'' as both
public and private health care costs continue to rise, Rockefeller
proclaimed the matter of setting priorities ``a very scary
business.''
   His comments came after former Health and Welfare Secretary
Joseph Califano told a Senate panel that a growing body of research
is bearing out assertions of many analysts that ``at least 25
percent of the money we spend on health care is wasted.''
   That figure, said Califano, translates to $125 billion a year
and is likely to grow as the United States moves toward allocating
15 percent of its total gross national product to health spending
by the end of the next decade.
   As difficult and dangerous as it is to channel spending toward
medical practices with proven effectiveness, Califano said, ``The
greater danger of hurting people is if we don't embark upon a
program like this.''
   The exchange came as the Senate Finance health subcommittee
opened what is expected to be a protracted series of hearings on
ways to measure the quality of health care.
   Dr. William Roper, head of the federal agency that runs Medicare
and Medicaid, complimented Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine, for
holding the hearings.
   Roper noted that Congress has approved his request for the
Health Care Financing Administration to use $10 million in Medicare
trust funds to devise better methods of relating quality medical
outcomes to costs. But he said that evolving field of research is
too big for the government to undertake alone and urged the
academic community to play a larger role.
   Califano, who headed what is now the Health and Human Services
Department under President Carter, said government health cost
containment measures to date have ``basically played musical
chairs, moving health delivery from this setting to that setting.''
   ``We're pretty much near the end of the road in that kind of
approach,'' said Califano, who is a private consultant to the
Chrysler Corp. and other major companies on health insurance.
   The next hurdle, said Califano, is to get a realistic handle on
which medical procedures are worth performing and which are not for
a particular patient.
   ``It's really doctors that have to make that determination,'' he
said.
   Califano ticked off several instances of drastic differences in
medical costs that apparently have no relationship to quality care.
   Three studies released in conjunction with the hearing concluded
that hospital mortality statistics released on the nation's 6,000
hospitals last December were not an accurate measure of the quality
of care given at those institutions.
   They particularly noted that the HCFA statistics did not account
for differences in the severity of illness among patients at the
various hospitals.
   However, Roper acknowledged at the time that the major
shortcoming on the data was lack of a severity of illness
adjustment. He said HCFA officials were studying a number of
alternative methods of injecting such a measure into subsequent
annual releases of the billing data supplied by hospitals.
   ``The main usefulness of this information is for doctors and
hospitals to look carefully at what they're doing and improve what
they're doing for Medicare beneficiaries,'' said Roper.
   ``It is also useful to consumers as a screening tool so that
they can pose useful questions, thoughtful questions for their
doctor or their hospital administrator. Consumers shouldn't use
this information on its own as a guide to picking a hospital.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
