<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Noriega-Drugs     07-11 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega-Drugs,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Witness Says Noriega Bragged Of Bush Friendship, Drug
Traffic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In disputed Senate testimony, a convicted drug
racketeer said Monday that Panama's military strongman, Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, told him he planned to control the flow of drugs
through Central America and bragged of his ties to the CIA and Vice
President George Bush.
   The witness, John McCann, serving a sentence of life plus 110
years, told Senate Foreign Relations Committee narcotics
investigators that Noriega told him in a private 1983 meeting:
``I'm very friendly with the CIA, they let me do what I want.''
   McCann, who said Noriega conversed with him for nearly an hour
in halting English, added: ``He mentioned he was a very good friend
of the vice president, that he was the man responsible for holding
Central America together and keeping the communists out, and as
long as he did that he could do anything.''
   But some senators questioned McCann's account of a private,
detailed conversation in English with Noriega.
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., quoted both U.S. and former
Panamanian officials as saying Noriega always used interpreters
because his English is poor and not capable of sustaining a
lengthy, substantive conversation.
   McConnell quoted Michael Kozak, the State Department official
who conducted lengthy negotiations with Noriega after he was
indicted on U.S. narcotics charges as saying ``Noriega was not
proficient enough in English to conduct an intelligible
conversation.''
   McCann insisted that he had such conversations with Noriega on
four occasions between 1982 and 1984 and that while Noriega spoke
in ``pigin English,'' his meaning was plain.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who had led McCann through a detailed
description of narcotics dealings in Colombia, Bolivia, Panama and
elsewhere, asserted that McCann has no reason to lie and would be
subject to further punishment if he were convicted of perjury.
   ``I don't think I'd ever get out of jail for the rest of my
life,'' said McCann, who is serving his long prison sentence at the
federal correctional facility at Petersburg, Va.
   Responding to questions, McCann said Noriega may have overblown
any relationship he may have had with Bush.
   ``He told me he was friendly with Vice President Bush and I'm
sure he just said that to impress the point that he had friends in
high places,'' the witness testified.
   McCann said he had successfully sought help from Noriega in
assuring that shipments of cocaine through Panama were not
intercepted.
   He said he once offered the Panamanian general $250,000 in a
closed briefcase but that Noriega refused it, offering no
explanation.
   McCann testified that Noriega later told him to cut his ties
with drug rings in Bolivia, Colombia and other countries and to
deal exclusively with him.
   ``He said I could buy any of the things I wanted right in
Panama, heroin, cocaine, marajuana, antything,'' McCann said.
   The testimony came in the latest round of hearings led by Kerry
to explore the international narcotics racket and the effectiveness
of U.S. efforts to deal with it.
</TEXT>
