<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PeaceConvoy     07-11 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peace Convoy,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Convoy Member Arrested Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAREDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of a peace group was arrested for
the second time in three days Monday when trucks laden with food
and medical supplies bound for Nicaragua tried to cross a bridge
into Mexico, officials said.
   Two vehicles were stopped by U.S. Customs officials when they
attempted to cross the bridge about 1:30 a.m., said Tess Koenig,
spokeswoman for the group calling itself the Veterans' Peace Convoy.
   Louis DeBenedette, the driver of one of the trucks, was arrested
after he refused to leave the bridge, Ms. Koenig said.
   ``He stepped out of the truck, they (police) handcuffed him and
he went to jail,'' Ms. Koenig said. The two trucks were then driven
back into the United States by other group members, she said.
   Convoy members have said they intend to leave the vehicles and
their cargo of food and medical supplies in Nicaragua, but federal
officials say the donation would violate a U.S. trade embargo
against the leftist Nicaraguan government.
   DeBenedette, 45, of Sparta, N.J., was charged with obstructing a
public roadway and bond was set at $500. DeBenedette told other
group members that he wished to remain in jail overnight rather
than post bond, said convoy spokeswoman Irene Rivera.
   DeBenedette was one of eight people arrested Saturday. He was
charged with obstructing a public roadway and resisting arrest. He
was released Saturday night on his own recognizance and fined
$1,250, Ms. Rivera said.
   The eight arrested had rushed a blockade set up by local police
and U.S. Customs officials.
   About 10 tons of supplies remain on the trucks and buses. Convoy
leaders say an additional 280 tons of supplies are being sent by
ship.
   The convoy originally tried to cross the border here June 15.
</TEXT>
