<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CaneWorkers     07-11 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cane Workers,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugar Cane Workers Excluded from Residence Status Under Proposed
Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Monday published a proposed
regulation that would prevent thousands of foreign sugar-cane
harvesters from qualifying for permanent U.S. residence status
under a program for seasonal farm workers.
   The Agriculture Department published the proposed regulation to
comply with an order issued last month by a judge who found the
agency had procrastinated in revising rules he had previously
struck down.
   Last spring, U.S. District Judge Thomas F. Hogan ruled that the
USDA had arbitrarily excluded sugar-cane workers from the seasonal
agricultural worker program.
   Under the 1986 Immigration Reform and Control Act, seasonal
workers who enter this country to harvest perishable farm
commodities have until Nov. 1 to apply for permanent U.S. residency.
   Hogan, in ordering the USDA to redraft its regulations, said
that the department had not justified excluding sugar cane from its
list of perishable commodities and held the agency's definition of
vegetable was ``arbitrary and capricious.''
   In the response published in Monday's Federal Register, the USDA
stood by its previous position but produced a more extensive
definition of vegetable.
   It defined vegetables as ``the human edible herbaceous leaves,
stems, roots, or tubers of plants, which are eaten, either cooked
or raw, chiefly as the principal part of a meal, rather than as a
dessert.''
   The proposed regulation noted that ``sugar cane is not eaten
(cooked or raw) during the main course of a meal, either as a
principal dish or as a side dish.''
   ``While the juice of the sugar cane is digestible, the cane
itself is not digestible by humans,'' the USDA said. ``USDA is
unaware of the use of sugar cane as a vegetable as that term is
defined in horticultural science and in this proposed regulation.''
   The department also noted that `sugar cane did not meet the
definition of `other perishable commodities' because the production
of sugar cane does not involve critical and unpredictable labor
demands.''
   Opponents of the proposed regulation have until July 26 to file
comments with the USDA, according to the terms of Hogan's order.
   Steven Routh, an attorney representing two organizations that
help sugar-cane workers, said he was ``disappointed that the agency
has continued in its past pattern of taking action that's really
designed to keep sugar cane workers out of the ... program.''
   ``They start with the premise that they are going to keep
sugar-cane workers out and reason to that conclusion,'' Routh said.
``There has been a consistent, clear reluctance on their part not
to include sugar cane workers.''
   Routh vowed to return to court next month if the USDA does not
change its position.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880711-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Malta     07-11 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Malta,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maltese Leader Opens US Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maltese Prime Minister Eddie Fenech Adami,
seeking a better image for his Mediterranean island nation, opened
talks Monday with Reagan administration officials in a drive to
improve ties with the West.
   Apparently he is succeeding. After a meeting with Deputy
Secretary of State John C. Whitehead, a U.S. official spoke warmly
of Malta's desire to improve relations with the United States.
   ``The United States very much values its friendship with
Malta,'' said Thomas Switzer, a State Department press officer.
   The Maltese government, meanwhile, said in a full-page
advertisement in The Washington Post that military ties with Libya
would not be observed and links with North Korea reduced.
   Fenech Adami calls on President Reagan on Wednesday. It will be
the first meeting between a Maltese prime minister and an American
president in 19 years.
   Fenech Adami, a Christian Democrat, was elected last year after
16 years of Socialist rule. He said before leaving on the visit
that he wanted to repair a ``somewhat distorted'' image the United
States had of Malta during the Socialists' rule.
   Under former Prime Minister Don Mintoff, Malta strengthened its
bonds with Communist nations and with Libya, which the United
States has attacked as a supporter of terrorism.
   Mintoff also tried to persuade Europea rain fell at regular
monitoring stations of the National Weather Service. Forecasters
said an approaching Pacific front might bring thunderstorms, but no
steady rainfall was anticipated.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NEBRASKA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Rain over the weekend helped some still-parched areas, but crops
still need about an inch of rain a week to protect potential
yields, a climatologist said.
   Ken Hubbard, director of the High Plains Climate Center at the
University of Nebraska-Lincoln, said soil in the root zone still is
dry in most areas.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NORTH DAKOTA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dry weather has evaporated at least half of the ``prairie
potholes'' ducks use for nesting, and this year's duck hatch is the
worst he's ever seen, said Dale Henegar, commissioner of the state
Game and Fish Department.
   ``A lot of the major marshes are dried up, and the birds paired
up early ... and just simply didn't nest,'' Henegar said. ``The
whole thing looks pretty grim.''
 
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OHIO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Thundershowers ahead of a cool front helped alleviate the heat,
but farm experts said the rainfall was probably too little and too
late. The rain was the first measurable precipitation in the state
this month.
   In Hardin County in north central Ohio, 16 truckloads of hay
from Vermont arrived at the county fairgrounds for distribution to
Amish farmers and other area growers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTH DAKOTA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Despite widely scattered rain over the weekend, rainfall in some
locations remains more than 6 inches below normal for the year. The
driest parts are in the northeast quadrant of the state. The only
above-normal precipitation was reported in localized areas of the
south central and west central portions of the state.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TENNESSEE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Residents in drought-stricken areas may notice fewer mosquitoes
but more spider mites that attack house plants and landscape
shrubs, an entomologist said.
   ``Mosquitoes have to have moisture to be able to complete
development,'' said entomologist Jaime Yanes.
   The drought also affects fleas and ticks, but since they are not
dependent on water to reproduce like mosquitoes, they are stronger
in hot, dry conditions, Yanes said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
