<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Reagan-Duarte 1stLd-Writethru   07-11 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Duarte, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0630,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ailing Duarte Returns and Vows To Complete Presidential Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, with Duarte back in El
Salvador.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
saying he is ``not cured, but strong,'' returned to El Salvador on
Monday and vowed to complete his term despite his terminal cancer.
   ``I am here now to reassume the presidency, in order to continue
working for what I most love: democracy,'' Duarte said in a brief
statement.
   Duarte, 62, arrived aboard one of the U.S. Air Force's
presidential Boeing 727 after an absence of nearly six weeks. He
left May 31 for diagnosis and treatment of cancer at Walter Reed
Army Medical Center in Washington, where he visited President
Reagan on Monday morning before flying home.
   ``President Reagan and President Duarte are personal friends,''
said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater. ``The president
visited him in the hospital last week and invited him to the White
House on his departure for El Salvador.''
   Surgeons removed most of Duarte's cancerous stomach last month.
He then underwent chemotherapy to slow the advance of liver cancer.
Duarte's doctors have said he has between six and 18 months to live.
   Duarte's five-year term ends June 1, 1989.
   The president was leaner than when he left and his face was
somewhat drawn. But his step was firm and his embrace appeared
strong as he greeted Rodolfo Castillo Claramount, the vice
president and acting chief executive, and other officials on the
tarmac of Ilopango Airport outside the capital.
   He was greeted by an honor guard of paratroopers and the air
force band, and by members of the diplomatic corps.
   ``I certainly am not cured. But I am strong. I have the capacity
and the strength to carry out both the medical requisites my
disease demands and my work for the people,'' Duarte said.
   He promised to continue working with the military against
leftist guerrillas ``in order to bring peace to my people ... in
that way I will make it to the first of June and hand power over to
he who is elected by the people.''
   Duarte's governing Christian Democratic Party is in the deepest
crisis of its 28-year history. Each of two bitterly feuding
factions has nominated a presidential candidate.
   The rightist opposition won municipal and legislative elections
in March. The March voting outcome, along with the Christian
Democrats' internal problems, has created the impression that the
rightists could win the March presidential election.
   Fitzwater said in Washington: ``President Duarte simply wanted
to thank the president for his hospitality here and for the support
the United States has shown to El Salvador.
   ``Similarly, President Reagan commented on the outstanding
contributions that President Duarte has made to the growth of
democracy in El Salvador and the president expressed his
appreciation for all of his efforts in the regional peace talks.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
