<DOCNO> AP880711-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Airliner-Investigation     07-11 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Investigation,0732</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Investigators Trying To See If Airliner Received Warnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With UN-Airliner, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. investigators probing the Iranian
airliner tragedy want to know if an Iranian air force plane tried
to tell the jet it was being warned off by an American warship,
U.S. military sources said Monday.
   They said another question is whether the civilian air traffic
controller on duty at Bandar Abbas, which the Iran Air Airbus had
just left, heard the U.S. ship's radio messages but did not relay
them to the pilot.
   U.S. officials say the jetliner was shot down July 3, killing
all 290 people aboard, after it did not respond to messages sent by
the USS Vincennes on military and civilian radio channels. The
missile cruiser fired in the belief that the aircraft was an F-14
fighter threatening to attack, they said.
   The questions about the patrol plane, a U.S-built P-3 Orion, and
the air controller emerged on the sixth day of the inquiry by a
team of six U.S. officers.
   A U.S. source, who like the others spoke on condtiion of
anonymity, said: ``The inquiry is trying to look at everything. If
any attempts were made to alert the Airbus, they would of course
want to know that. It would be up to Iran to provide that kind of
information.''
   No indication has emerged whether the U.S. investigators would
have an opportunity to interview Iranian officials. A senior U.S.
officer here said last week it appeared ``highly doubtful.''
   It also was not known whether Iran would let U.S. investigators
review data from the jetiliner's ``black box'' flight recorder if
it is recovered.
   On Monday, they awaited the analysis of computer tapes from the
Vincennes and a second U.S warship that was in the Strait of Hormuz
at the time. The tapes were sent to the United States last week for
scrutiny at a Navy laboratory.
   The U.S. sources said the P-3 apparently was airborne in the
Hormuz area about the time the shootdown occurred, but said they
did not know how close it was or if it monitored the radio traffic
leading up to the Airbus' destruction.
   The P-3, a military version of the Lockheed Electra turboprop
aircraft, is used by the U.S. Navy for long-range anti-submarine
surveillance.
   Iran acquired six P-3s in the mid-1970s and at least one is
still flying, U.S. officials say. It is a familiar sight on almost
daily patrol missions over the Strait of Hormuz and southern
Persian Gulf.
   A British newspaper quoted the air traffic controller on duty at
Bandar Abbas the day the Airbus was shot down as saying Iranian
controllers hear U.S. warships issuing warnings on the radio
``every day,'' but ``we never reply to them.''
   The Times of London identified the controller as Hossein Pirouzi
and quoted him as saying, ``The Americans have no right to be in
the gulf challenging our legitimate right to fly our air routes _
so why should we reply to them?''
   The Vincennes remained at anchor of Bahrain as the investigation
continued. Its crew has been restricted to the ship for security
reasons, with sailors allowed ashore only in small groups to make
telephone calls home.
   Rear Adm. William M. Fogarty leads the investigating team, which
has a 15-day deadline U.S. officials said could be extended.
   The six officers, operating in secrecy, include a military
lawyer and technical experts. Most of the work is being done aboard
the Vincennes and the Navy's gulf flagship, the Coronado.
   One team member, Capt. John J. Kieley III, commanded the U.S.
missile frigate Reuben James in the gulf earlier this year and now
has a Navy staff assignment in the Pentagon.
   Navy sources said computer tapes from the Vincennes and the
frigate Elmer Montgomery, which was nearby, were vital to resolving
such questions as the altitude of the Iranian Airbus when it was
hit by two surface-to-air missiles.
   The Vincennes and Elmer Montgomery skirmished with Iranian
attack boats, sinking two, less than an hour before the Airbus was
shot down, U.S. officials said that might have helped make the
Vincennes' commander, Capt. Will C. Rogers III, believe his ship
was under air attack.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
</TEXT>
