<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia-Sihanouk     07-11 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia-Sihanouk,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Resigns as Leader of Caombodian Resistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Norodom Sihanouk announced his
resignation as president of the Cambodian guerrilla alliance
Monday, two weeks before the coalition is to open peace talks with
the Vietnamese and Cambodian governments.
   Sihanouk has made the same gesture previously, then returned to
head the fractious alliance of his followers, the radical communist
Khmer Rouge and former Premier Son Sann's anti-communist forces.
   On Monday, Sihanouk also said he was not abandoning efforts to
end more than a decade of war in Cambodia.
   ``No, I will continue my efforts to help my country and my
people,'' he said at the Bangkok airport as he left for Paris. He
said his son, Prince Nodorom Ranariddh, would replace him at the
talks beginning July 25 in Indonesia.
   Roland Eng, Sihanouk's spokesman, said the prince's decision to
resign as head of the coalition came so suddenly that everyone had
their bags packed for the trip to Indonesia. Sihanouk did not say
why he resigned.
   Eng said one reason was that the prince was upset by an article
Sunday in the newspaper The Nation detailing his relations in
Cambodia in the 1960s and 1970s with the Khmer Rouge and Son Sann.
   Sihanouk was deposed as head of state in March 1970 and the
monarchy abolished. The Khmer Rouge defeated the U.S.-backed
government of Lon Nol in April 1975, and independent observers say
more than 1 million Cambodians were killed under its regime.
   Vietnamese forces invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ousted the
Khmer Rouge and installed another communist administration. The
Khmer Rouge then began guerrilla warfare against the Vietnames and
were joined by forces loyal to Sihanouk and Son Sann.
   The Indonesia talks will be the first among the warring parties.
   Sihanouk was the central figure at the meeting last week of the
foreign ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) and their Western partners. They said he should have a
major role in creating a new Camdobidan government.
   Among those at the meeting were Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda
of Thailand, Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Sosuke Uno,
the Japanese foreign minister.
   In a letter published in The Nation on Monday, Sihanouk objected
to allegations in an article that said his government forced
peasants to sell rice to the state at low prices in 1967. He said
the Khmer Rouge fomented the peasant-related violence of that year.
   The 65-year-old prince was asked at the airport if he would
change his mind again about resigning and said: ``No, I will not.''
   His resignation was announced in a statement issued from his
Bangkok office. It said: ``For serious reasons that are, for the
moment, impossible for me to enumerate and to explain, please allow
me today to resign as president of Democratic Kampuchea
(Cambodia).''
   Shultz, in Indonesia, said Monday he did not know how to
interpret Sihanouk's action. He said Sihanouk seemed in their
recent meetings to take a ``constructive'' approach to the
Cambodian problem.
   The foreign ministers of Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia, at a
conference Monday in Phnom Penh, Cambodia, declared they were
commited a political solution to the Cambodian conflict.
   In a joint communique, they repeated that all Vietnamese troops
will leave Cambodia by 1990 or sooner if a political solution is
reached, but the settlement must guarantee the Khmer Rouge will not
return to power. Vietnam has an estimated 140,000 military
personnel in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
