<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CandidateMistakes 1stLd-Writethru a0588 07-11 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidate Mistakes, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0588,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Vows Aid For Candidates Who May Be Thrown Off Ballot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with governor vowing to call
special session if elections board disqualifies candidates. Picks
up 8th graf pvs, `The state...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Edward D. DiPrete said Monday he
would call a special session of the General Assembly if necessary
to restore a four-term congresswoman and a two-time gubernatorial
candidate to the ballot.
   After meeting with legislative leaders for more than an hour,
DiPrete said Republican Rep. Claudine C. Schneider and Democratic
gubernatorial candidate Bruce G. Sundlun should try to win their
ballot slots from the state Board of Elections before the
legislature would take action.
   But if the board rules against the candidates, or lawyers advise
that the board is likely to do so, the Republican governor said he
would call on the legislature to step in.
   ``I personally feel that both Bruce Sundlun and Claudine
Schneider should have their names on the ballot,'' DiPrete said.
``In the final analysis, if I have to call a special session, I
will.''
   Referring to Sundlun, DiPrete said, ``Even if he is my opponent,
I think he should be on the ballot.''
   Schneider and Sundlun face disqualification from the November
election because the signatures and addresses on their candidacy
declarations are not identical to those on their voter registration
cards.
   The Narragansett Board of Canvassers, which must certify a
candidacy, on July 1 discovered that Schneider's declaration
included her middle initial and listed her address as 56 Central
Ave. Her registration omits the initial and lists her address,
correctly, as 56 Central St. The canvassing board referred the
matter to the state Board of Elections.
   Sundlun signed his declaration with his initials and listed his
Providence address as 79 Prospect St. His registration spells out
his first name and omits the word ``street.''
   The Providence Board of Canvassers certified Sundlun's candidacy
despite the discrepancies. However, a political opponent checked
Sundlun's paperwork after the Schneider case became publicized and
complained to the election board.
   The state Board of Elections meets July 25 to determine if
Schneider and Sundlun may remain on the ballot. If the board rules
against them, they could launch write-in campaigns.
   Chairman Joseph R. DiStefano won't say what the board might do,
but said candidates have been disqualified ``time and time again''
for such mistakes.
   The law requiring signatures and addresses to match exactly has
been in effect since 1950 and has survived a state court challenge.
   House Minority Leader Bradford Gorham, who headed a commission
that extensively revised Rhode Island's election laws last year,
said, ``No one, absolutely no one, called for change in this
particular provision.''
   Schneider has served in Congress since 1980. Sundlun lost to
DiPrete in 1986.
</TEXT>
