<HEAD>Reagan Goes To Bat For Nebraska Senator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan went to bat Monday for the
re-election of the newest U.S. senator, Nebraska's David Karnes,
telling a Karnes fund-raiser that GOP presidential candidate George
Bush needs a Republican Senate he can work with.
   ``He needs a Republican Senate so our accomplishments of eight
years will not be undone,'' Reagan said.
   Karnes was appointed by Gov. Kay A. Orr last year to fill the
vacancy caused by the death of Sen. Edward Zorinsky, a Democrat.
   Addressing his remarks to the governor, who he said would see a
television picture of the event, Reagan said: ``Come election day,
people of Nebraska are going to confirm your wisdom in appointing
Dave Karnes to the Senate.''
   Karnes told the audience of about 200 that he had been
privileged to work in the Reagan administration as a White House
fellow in 1981-82 and that he learned ``we have true leadership in
this president.''
   The senator's opponent in November is former Gov. Robert Kerrey.
   The fund-raising event was held at a hotel two blocks from the
White House.
