<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-OilRig 1stLd-Writethru a0683 07-11 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0683,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adair Views Burning Platform But Cannot Board to Work</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with names of two Americans on
platform during disaster. PICKS up 4th pvs, Hammer said ...; ADDS 6
grafs, former superintendent says platform ``bomb waiting to
explode.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas oil troubleshooter Red Adair
inspected the burning Piper Alpha platform on Monday from a basket
suspended above the flames and smoke, but rough weather in the
North Sea halted his plans to clear debris.
   Chairman Armand Hammer and other officials of Occidental
Petroleum Corp., the platform's operators, rejected allegations
that warnings of gas leaks went unheeded in the days before
Wednesday night's disaster, which killed 166 of the 230 men on
board.
   Occidental executives have said they believe a gas leak caused
the explosions that rocked the structure 120 miles east of
Scotland, but have maintained the rig complied with all safety
standards.
   Police meanwhile released the names of two Americans involved in
the disaster. They said Carl Busse, 28, of Navasota, Texas, was
among those listed as missing and believed dead. Joseph Wells, 33,
from Santa Barbara, Calif., survived the blaze without injury, they
said.
   Hammer said the explosion was so powerful it overwhelmed the
structure's sophisticated safety system.
   ``Our oil rig had every safety device on it that we could
possibly have,'' Hammer said during a visit to Tel Aviv on Monday,
where he anounced plans for an offshore drilling project in Israel.
   About claims by former employees and families of survivors that
gas leaks discovered earlier were linked to the explosion, Hammer
said:
   ``Our people say that whatever leaks there were were corrected,
and they also were not in the place where we believe the explosion
took place.''
   He said the blast destroyed sensors and alarms before the
automated safety system could shut the platform down.
   ``We had sensors which would have detected ordinary leaks and
would have given us warning, but this explosion was so tremendous
that no sensors would operate there,'' Hammer told the news
conference.
   David Martin, president of Occidental Oil and Gas Corp., the
subsidiary which operates the rig, said in Aberdeen he had ``no
confirmation'' of any leaks prior to Wednesday's explosion but was
aware of reports that some workers had smelled gas.
   Adair, 73, and two assistants had to postpone plans to board the
platform when winds of 35 mph buffeted the site, said an Occidental
spokeswoman who would not give her name. Adair has worked on the
site since Friday and must clear the platform of debris to gain
access to the wellheads and seal them.
   About 30 percent of the debris has been cleared.
   The spokeswoman said the Houston disaster specialist and his
team returned to their base on the semi-submersible service vessel
Tharos.
   It was the second time in two days that Adair's efforts to work
on the platform were frustrated. He was forced to cancel a visit at
dawn Sunday because of heavy seas, high winds and flames shooting
into the air from one of the three wellheads still burning.
   In Red Deer, Alberta, a Canadian who was a former platform
superintendent on the rig, was quoted on Monday as saying the Piper
Alpha rig was ``a bomb waiting to explode.''
   ``I was glad to get off that thing,'' Ralph Miller of Red Deer
was quoted as saying by the Canadian Press news agency.
   Miller, who worked on the rig from 1980-82, said the problem
stemmed from the rig's productivity, according to the news agency.
   The Piper Alpha rig was one of the best producers at 120,000
barrels of oil a day and one of the most profitable in the British
section of the North Sea.
   Miller was quoted as saying that pressure to keep the oil
flowing led to lax maintenance, with valves sometimes not turning
and an inch or more of grease on some of the working decks.
   ``Basically, it went down to neglect. They had safety meetings,
but how much did it help?'' Miller was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
