<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-ABC 1stLd-Writethru a0713 07-11 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-ABC, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Denies Security Agents Impersonated ABC Crew</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs to Restore first name of Pazner. PICKS up
3rd pvs bgng, Pazner said he ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on
Monday denied allegations by the American television network ABC
that Israeli security agents impersonated one of its news crews to
deceive and arrest a Palestinian.
   Israeli officials investigated and ``found no evidence that
Israeli security personnel impersonated ABC News persons in
arresting a Palestinian Arab'' last month, Avi Pazner told The
Associated Press.
   Pazner said he informed ABC News president Roone Arledge of the
results. Arledge sent a protest telex to Shamir last week demanding
an investigation.
   Dean Reynolds, ABC's Israel correspondent, said Monday: ``ABC
stands by its story. The facts were corroborated by informed
Israeli sources.''
   The network reported last week that Nizar Dakdouk of Salfit
village in the occupied West Bank was arrested by Israeli civilians
posing as ABC News personnel, and it had learned ``the impostors
were members of the Israeli secret security service Shin Bet.''
   Reynolds told the AP on Monday he was not satisfied with the
investigation and had asked Pazner which Israeli agency was
responsible for Dakdouk's arrest.
   ``Mr. Pazner acknowledged that the government didn't even ask
the central question of who arrested this young man,'' Reynolds
said. ``So much for a thorough investigation.''
   Pazner responded: ``The answer I got came from people
representing all the security services, and that includes the army
and the Shin Bet. This was a thorough investigation.''
   Reynolds said ABC learned of the incident June 26, two days
after it allegedly occurred, and complained to police, the army and
Shamir's office. It publicized the complaint last Tuesday because
it had not receive a satisfactory response, Reynolds said at the
time.
   According to the ABC News report, Israeli troops demolished
Dakdouk's home on June 16 on grounds he had thrown a firebomb at a
bus. The young man and his mother said on Israel television the
next day the army should have arrested him if he was suspected of
something, not blown up the house.
   A week after the appearance, Israeli civilians posing as an ABC
News crew arrived at the Dakdouk family's temporary home in two
cars and said they wanted to interview Dakdouk and his brother at
the site of the destroyed house, the report said. They agreed to go.
   One of the cars sped off with Dakdouk later and he was arrested,
ABC said.
   Since the Palestinian rebellion began Dec. 8 in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip, Palestinians have claimed repeatedly that
Shin Bet agents patrol the territories in cars marked ``foreign
press'' and film protesters for purposes of identification and
subsequent arrest.
   Pazner said in his letter to Arledge: ``In the past, such and
other accusations have been circulated by Palestinians and ...
after investigations they were proved to be gross exaggerations or
pure fabrications.''
   Reynolds read the letter to the AP.
</TEXT>
