<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-Food     07-11 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Food,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says People Demand `Stern Measures' Against Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry Vietnamese demanded ``stern
measures'' against officials after revelations that a food shortage
has made 10 million people hungry and caused 21 to die of
starvation, a Vietnamese newspaper said.
   In an exchange unusual even for communist Vietnam's current
spate of self-criticism, a group of voters in Ho Chi Minh City also
questioned the National Assembly's choice of a premier, the report
said.
   About 300 people attended a briefing July 2 by a delegation of
assembly deputies, it said. On June 22, the assembly chose
conservative Do Muoi to be premier instead of Vo Van Kiet, a
pioneer of of Western-style economic reforms.
   A text of the article in the July 5 edition of the newspaper
Young Age in Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon, was obtained Monday
from a Western embassy in Bangkok.
   It said Ly Chanh Trung, head of a delegation of assembly members
that met with the voters, criticized a newspaper report that Thanh
Hoa province near Hanoi enjoyed a bumper harvest and the food
shortage in the north had ended.
   ``This is not true,'' Trung was quoted as saying. ``According to
statistics released by the Council of Ministers, about 10 million
people faced hunger, 4 million people faced serious hunger and 21
people died of starvation in various northern provinces.''
   The Council of Ministers is the Cabinet the premier heads.
   According to the article, ``Many voter representatives were
shocked and became angry upon learning of this fact. They then took
turns to bombard the delegation with questions.''
   A man named Doan Ngoc Tu said: ``Stern measures must be taken
against leading cadres in charge of those localities because they
have failed to cope with the situation.''
   Nguyen Ba Nghe, of a liaison committee for the Industrialists
and Traders Association, said the government should let foreigners
invest directly instead of only through state agencies.
   ``Most of the voters' questions were about the election of the
chairman of the Council of Ministers,'' the article said.
   ``Some voters expressed their opinion as follows: `We need time
to judge the correctness of the National Assembly's decision.
Nevertheless, now that the National Assembly has made a choice, we
must ... join hands in seeking solutions to our current, very
difficult economic, political, and social problems.'''
   Previous official reports from Vietnam said the northern
provinces suffered food shortages and ``near-famine'' because
drought, cold weather, storms and insects devastated last year's
rice crop.
   Kiet, a deputy prime minister, told the National Assembly
session in June the food crisis became worse because the Council of
Ministers did not anticipate it and officials did not take urgent
relief measures.
   Reports in the official media say better harvests early this
year have provided more food for Vietnam's 63 million people, most
of whom live in the impoverished countryside.
   The U.N. World Food Program said June 24 it was sending $9.1
million in food aid to help 1.5 million drought victims in Vietnam.
It said U.N. officials confirmed a serious deterioration of food
supplies for 12 northern provinces.
   Vietnam appealed for more emergency aid but got little because
the policy of most non-communist countries is to isolate the
Vietnamese until they end their occupation of Cambodia, which began
with an invasion in December 1978.
</TEXT>
