<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-USTrawler 1stLd-Writethru a0564 07-11 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-US Trawler, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0564,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Skipper Faces Charges After Skirmish in North Atlantic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New throughout to UPDATE with court appearance, charges,
quotes and background. Corrects spelling of captain's name to
Sheaffer and hometown to Edgartown. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The skipper of a U.S. trawler was
charged Monday with unlawful fishing and obstruction after Canadian
patrol boats stopped him from sailing off with four fisheries
officers who had ordered him into port.
   Roy Sheaffer, 39, of Edgartown, Mass., was ordered held in
custody until a bail hearing Wednesday. He did not have to enter a
plea.
   Sheaffer was charged with two counts under the Coastal Fisheries
Protection Act and a third charge of obstruction for refusing to
obey orders from fisheries officers to sail to a Canadian port.
   The 69-foot Mary Elizabeth was loaded with nearly 3 tons of
lobster and flounder when it was found inside Canada's 200-mile
limit, officials said.
   The incident began late Saturday when four Canadian officers
boarded the vessel, based in New Bedford, Mass., on the Georges
Bank fishing ground.
   ``The vessel was found fishing inside Canadian waters and a
boarding was carried out'' by the officers from a patrol boat, said
Bob Prier, regional enforcement director for the Fisheries
Department.
   Sheaffer refused to sail into Halifax and ``attempted to steam
away with four of our officers on board,'' Trade Minister John
Crosbie told Parliament in Ottawa.
   Another Canadian patrol vessel was nearby and caught up with the
Mary Elizabeth. Armed officers went on board and after some
argument arrested Sheaffer, according to Prier.
   ``He's a big man and it took a bit of time to get him under
arrest,'' Prier said. He reporteed there were no injuries.
   Fisheries officers in the area were issued with pistols and
submachine guns last year, and Prier said he doubted whether
Sheaffer would have been apprehended without guns.
   ``A year ago, it's likely the vessel would be heading into
Boston, not into Halifax,'' he said.
   Canadian willingness to use armed force against the Mary
Elizabeth should send a signal to other Americans tempted to fish
in Canadian waters, Prier said. ``They know we have the capability
now of arresting their vessels.''
   At least five American captains were convicted last year of
illegally entering or fishing in Canadian waters, mostly on Georges
Bank, an area of shallow water and lucrative lobster and scallop
beds.
   Sheaffer's three crewmembers, all from the New Bedford area,
were not charged and remained aboard their boat at a federal wharf,
according to officials.
   They said the vessel's catch of 1,700 pounds of lobster and
3,960 pounds of flounder was seized and sold to a local fish
market. The profit will be returned to Sheaffer if he is acquitted
or used toward fines and port charges if he is convicted.
   A conviction under the Coastal Fisheries Protection Act could
result in a fine of up to $750,000 ($622,500 U.S.) plus forfeiture
of the catch.
</TEXT>
