<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-Farm 1stLd-Writethru a0685 07-11 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Farm, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Hits Reagan Administration Farm Policies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 4 grafs with later veep comment, fixes category code</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson told a farm group Monday that
all Americans will pay a price for ``the double disaster''
afflicting agriculture: the drought and Reagan administration
policies that have hurt family farmers.
   Jackson, who followed Vice President George Bush to the podium
at a meeting of farm broadcasters, editors and educators, said that
in the seven years of the Reagan administration, ``We've lost
600,000-plus family farmers _ the most efficient farmers in the
history of the world.''
   ``Something has gone awry when this many farmers are driven from
the land while we import food from abroad subsidized by the U.S.
government,'' Jackson told 450 people at the U.S. Agricultural
Communicators' Congress.
   He said the drought was not simply a farmers' problem but ``a
national crisis. It's a national security issue.
   ``All of us must bear the burden...of the double disaster: the
Reagan-Bush family farm policies and this lack of rain.''
   He charged the commodity markets were in ``a profiteering
frenzy'' and said, ``There is good reason to be concerned about
profiteering Pentagon-style'' on the part of mammoth agribusinesses
that could jump in and take over distressed farms.
   The audience included Earl Butz, the colorful and controversial
secretary of agriculture for five years under President Richard
Nixon, who told Jackson, ``You and I came from family farms. We're
part of the exodus....Why do we want to stop it now?''
   Jackson, a South Carolina sharecropper's son, said, ``We left
the family farm coming to get a job....Now the job is not there
either.''
   ``While we leave (farms), fewer insensitive corporations...own
more and control us more. That comes as a threat to me,'' said
Jackson, who called for an international conference ``to address
the implications of food distribution, prices and stability around
the world.''
   Jackson said farming, subject to drought, floods, bugs and other
calamities, cannot operate under classic free-market rules.
   ``Even Pharaoh in ancient Egypt knew that when the drought came
the rest of his system was in trouble,'' he said. ``A new system
was in order. A new vision was in order. New leadership was in
order.''
   Butz, who has an office at Purdue University and lectures across
the country, said afterwards that the farm population is shrinking
less now than it was in the 1960s and 1970s under both Democratic
and Republican administrations. He said he once heard Soviet leader
Leonid Brezhnev lament that 40 percent of his population was on the
farm.
   Butz said that when he was born 40 percent of the American
population was involved in agriculture. ``We'd be a nation of
peasants clear across the board today if someone had had that
philosophy then,'' Butz said.
   After addressing the farm group, Jackson met with Paul Brountas,
a top aide to Michael Dukakis who is coordinating the expected
nominee's search for a running mate.
   Jackson emerged from the meeting and told reporters that he
would accept the No. 2 spot on the ticket if it were offered.
   It was the first time he said publicly he would accept a vice
presidential offer. He has frequently pressed his demand for an
offer, but refused until Monday to say whether he would accept it.
   ``If it was offered to me, I would accept it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
