<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-11 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Coast Bakes; Texas Gets Wet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The East Coast could have sung an anthem ``Helter-Swelter'' as
hot, humid air continued in the region Monday, while parts of Texas
were deluged with a half-foot of rain.
   Temperatures approached the 100-degree mark and either broke or
threatened to break records for the date in several Eastern cities.
   The Big Apple again became the Baked Apple, as New York City hit
98 degrees, breaking a 77-year-old record by one degree. It marked
the fifth day in the last six that New Yorkers had to put up with
90-degree-plus heat.
   Newark, N.J., shattered its 98-degree record set in 1936 by
reaching 101 degrees Monday afternoon, the 16th day of 90
degrees-plus there this year.
   Other cities setting record highs for the date were Baltimore,
100; Bridgeport, Conn., 93; and Philadelphia, 100.
   But a cold front across the eastern Great Lakes should bring
relief from the heat to the Northeast and mid-Atlantic region, the
National Weather Service said.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered along the cold front
from northern New England through much of the Ohio and middle
Mississippi valleys into the southern Plains.
   Numerous thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain in parts of
south-central Texas, where rainfall measurements ranged from 3 to 6
inches. More than 6 inches of rain was measured just east of Hunt,
Texas, while areas west of Medina, Texas, received 6 to 7 inches.
   Rivers across much of the region rose by as much as 8 feet
because of the heavy rainfall. A flash flood watch remained in
effect Monday for much of south-central Texas. At least five
drownings were reported in Texas late Sunday and Monday.
   Elsewhere, more than 2 inches of rain was reported in parts of
Kentucky, resulting in some minor street flooding. Thunderstorms
also were reported from the lower Mississippi Valley across the
Southeastern states, and showers and thunderstorms were scattered
across parts of Nebraska and western Iowa. Other showers were
isolated in northern Idaho.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Bellingham, Wash., to 102 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The
early-morning low in the nation was 36 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Tuesday, the weather service forecast scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the northern Rockies through the northern
Plains, the lower Missouri and middle Mississippi valleys, the
lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the eastern Gulf Coast and
Florida, and the Atlantic Coast. Scattered showers were also
expected in Washington state.
   High temperatures were predicted for the 80s or 90s across much
of the nation. Highs should reach the 70s along the Pacific Coast,
the Pacific Northwest, and much of the Great Lakes region, while
highs of 100 to 110 degrees were forecast in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
