<DOCNO> AP880711-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Thatcher     07-11 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Thatcher,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Prime Minister Chats Long-Distance With Soviet Citizens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher held a live radio
phone-in with Soviet citizens Monday on topics ranging from
``glasnost'' to household chores and invited a Leningrad schoolgirl
to visit her.
   Mrs. Thatcher fielded 15 calls during the 55-minute program
broadcast live to the Soviet Union on the British Broadcasting
Corp.'s Russian Service. The BBC said more than 200 Soviets called
in.
   Speaking in English translated simultaneously into Russian, the
prime minister was lavish in her praise for Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev and said she hoped the clock will not be turned back on
his policies of glasnost, or openness, and economic reform.
   ``I think that some things are irreversible, but I don't think
that they would go forward with anything like the same momentum if
Mr. Gorbachev were not there,'' she said.
   Moscow dissident Valery Senderov called to solicit her views on
the reforms Gorbachev has already implemented.
   ``I think it's remarkable that after 70 years of what I might
call the old-fashioned kind of communism,'' Mrs. Thatcher said,
``that Mr. Gorbachev should have been able to see that it was not
producing either the standard of living that people wanted or the
standard of social services.''
   To Moscow resident Karin Saakiyan, a Hare Krishna recently
released from a psychiatric hospital, Mrs. Thatcher expressed
optimism about religious freedom in the Soviet Union.
   Reporter Alexander Volkov of Radio Moscow's International
Department asked Mrs. Thatcher whether she still believed the U.S.
Navy was justified in shooting down an Iran Air jetliner on July 3,
killing 290 people.
   The Sunday Times of London reported a British intelligence
agency monitored radio communications in the Persian Gulf before
the incident and determined the plane was on course and climbing,
not descending toward the American warship Vincennes.
   Mrs. Thatcher said that while ``you will know many, many things
now that were not known to that captain,'' warships cannot be asked
to defend commercial ships unless they have the right to defend
themselves when they believe they are under attack.
   But she added:
   ``Yes, there will be times when they make a mistake and this
tragic accident ... underlines the need for an early end to the
Iran-Iraq conflict conflict including an end to all attacks on
shipping by both sides.''
   On a lighter note, Mrs. Thatcher told one curious inquirer from
Leningrad that she has no live-in help at the apartment she and her
husband, Denis, share at No. 10 Downing St. She told the man that
she does most of the cooking when they are not attending banquets
or official lunches.
   Schoolgirl Masha Kuznetsova called to invite young Britons to
visit her family in Leningrad, and was instead invited to meet the
British prime minister in London.
   ``Oh dear, if you come over and your school comes over, I will
ask our ambassador to let me know because I would like to see
you,'' Mrs. Thatcher said. Perhaps you'll come to No. 10 Downing
St. where I live. We'll look forward to a visit.''
   Edited highlights of the program were broadcast later Monday on
the BBC's English-language World Services.
   A BBC spokesman said that until January 1987, the Soviet Union
discouraged its citizens from listening to the BBC Russian Service
by widespread electronic jamming.
   An estimated 18 million people in the Soviet Union listen to the
BBC, company officials have said.
</TEXT>
