<DOCNO> AP880711-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Veterans     07-11 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veterans,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Votes To Let Veterans Take VA Appeals To Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, on the verge of passing a bill to
raise the Veterans Administration to Cabinet level, voted Monday to
let veterans appeal to the courts when their claims for benefits
are denied by the VA.
   The claims bill, passed on an 86-11 vote, also would repeal a
Civil War-era law that limits to $10 the amount a lawyer may charge
for pressing a veteran's claim.
   For several hours, senators debated a bill to create a
department of veterans' affairs as the 14th Cabinet department but
they put off a final vote until Tuesday. Passage of the popular
bill is virtually certain.
   ``Veterans ask only that their voice be heard at the Cabinet
table,'' said Sen. Frank Murkowski of Alaska, senior Republican on
the Senate Veterans' Affairs Committee.
   The Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, headed by Sen. John
Glenn, D-Ohio, concluded that elevation of VA to the Cabinet
``would best serve America's veterans, the American public and,
ultimately, the president of the United States through
strengthening of the Cabinet as a policymaking mechanism.''
   The Senate defeated an amendment that would have permitted
President Reagan to name the first secretary of veterans' affairs
immediately. Thus, the first appointment will be left to the next
president.
   The House already has voted to raise the VA to Cabinet level but
has refused four times in recent years to pass any bill allowing
court review of VA benefit decisions.
   Nevertheless, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., chairman of the
Senate Veterans' Affairs Committee, said, ``I think this time we
have enough momentum to get this (review) measure approved by the
full Congress.''
   The Senate rejected by a 61-36 margin an amendment by Murkowski
that would have allowed review only of VA regulations, not of the
agency's factual findings about a veteran's claim.
   The Senate-passed bill would permit a court to overturn an
adverse finding by the VA's Board of Veterans' Appeals only when
the court finds the decision ``so utterly lacking in a rational
basis in the evidence that a manifest and grievous injustice would
result if such finding were not set aside.''
   Allowing court review ``would raise veterans to full first-class
citizenship in the nation they fought so courageously to preserve
and defend,'' Cranston said.
   ``Why is it that food stamp recipients ... SSI (welfare)
recipients ... prisoners and those threatened by deportation can go
to court and veterans cannot?'' asked Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
   ``Does anyone, anywhere have evidence that the system is so
broken that without federal court intervention in thousands of
individual claims our veterans are going to be deprived of a fair
shake?'' asked Murkowski. He cited statistics that the Board of
Veterans' Appeals reverses up to 25 percent of claim denials and
said the bill would add about 4,500 cases a year to the nation's
backlogged courts.
   Cranston said the old law limiting attorney fees in VA benefit
cases actually works against veterans.
   ``Whatever behavior characterized the legal profession at the
time the original limitation was enacted following the Civil War
... it is no longer credible to insist that attorneys would prey on
innocent veterans,'' Cranston said.
   Voting against the court-review bill were: Sens. Christopher
Bond, R-Mo.; Orrin Hatch, R-Utah; Howell Heflin, D-Ala.; Richard
Lugar, R-Ind.; James McClure, R-Idaho; Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.;
William Proxmire, D-Wis.; William Roth, R-Del., Warren Rudman,
R-N.H.; Steven Symms, R-Idaho, and Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.
   Sens. Joseph Biden, D-Del.; Jake Garn, R-Utah, and Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., did not vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
