<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Sociologist     07-11 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Sociologist,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sociologist Adviser to Solidarity Dies from Beating</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sociologist who was an adviser to the
banned trade union Solidarity died Monday from injuries sustained
in a mysterious assault nearly two weeks ago, colleagues and the
official media reported.
   Jan Strzelecki, who was about 60, was found June 30 in grave
condition lying near the Vistula River in Warsaw.
   According to police, he apparently had been dragged from his
car, beaten and thrown down an embankment, the official news agency
PAP reported.
   He never regained consciousness after the assault and died
Monday morning, said Ewa Haberka, an official of the Polish
Sociological Society.
   Although he was not a prominent member of Solidarity, Strzelecki
was an active supporter of it, said friends and other union
activists. He was employed as an associate professor and a
researcher for the Institute of Philosophy and Sociology of the
Polish Academy of Sciences.
   ``Evidence seemed to indicate that he had fallen victim to a
robbery assault, an especially brutal one,'' PAP said, adding that
an intensive investigation was continuing.
   The Polish Sociological Society has posted a reward of $2,325
for information leading to the arrest of the attackers.
</TEXT>
