<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Carlucci-Florio     07-11 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Carlucci-Florio,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Concerned About Unisys Payment To Defense Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman expressed concern Monday about
Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci's receipt of deferred compensation
year from a weapons contractor on whose board he once served and
which now is under investigation in the Pentagon contracting probe.
   Rep. Jim Florio, D-N.J., said Carlucci received the money in
March from the Detroit-based Unisys Corp., on whose board of
directors Carlucci served from 1984 through 1986. Carlucci, after
his appointment last year, disqualified himself from any decisions
involving Unisys.
   Florio, in a letter to Carlucci, wrote, ``While I understand
that this payment was deferred compensation, I am concerned that
such a payment to a secretary of defense who is in charge of
investigating the same defense contractor creates a serious
appearance of a conflict of interest.''
   The payment is explained on a financial disclosure form filed by
Carlucci in May as a ``deferred compensation plan for directors of
Unisys cashed out.''
   An earlier disclosure, filed in November, listed the value as
$82,482. The payment is dated in March, about four months after
Carlucci was reassigned by President Reagan from national security
advisor to secretary of defense.
   Carlucci also transferred into an insurance annuity an annual
pension of $14,300 due from Unisys, according to the disclosure
forms.
   Carlucci left the private sector in January 1987 to rejoin the
administration in the national security post.
   Florio said he questions if the payments _ originally planned
for after Carlucci left federal service _ are appropriate, given
Carlucci's post and the ongoing probe.
   ``I am concerned about the credibility of a secretary of defense
investigating a defense contractor who recently provided him with
compensation,'' Florio said.
   According to Pentagon officials, Carlucci himself is not
directly involved in the investigation of contract fraud.
</TEXT>
