<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Rape-Trial,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Trial In San Diego Case Postponed Until September</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first trial stemming from a reported
abduction and gang rape of a 19-year-old woman was postponed
Monday, after the prosecutor said he needed more time find
impartial jurors in this closeknit town.
   Many potential jurors in this southern Texas town of about 5,000
are related to the victim or defendants or have been exposed to
extensive media coverage of the woman who told authorities she was
kidnapped, raped and sodomized by as many as 20 men March 26.
   Assistant district attorney Rodolfo Gutierrez, the prosecutor,
said unrelated trials scheduled in the court would have forced the
case to be rushed, had it been tried this week.
   ``We'd be under pressure to finish this case this week, and we
just felt it was a little unrealistic at this point, because we
don't know how long it's going to take to select a jury,''
Gutierrez said.
   Orlando Garza and Corando Perez Jr., both 23, were to stand
trial on sexual assault charges Monday, but 229th Judicial District
Judge Ricardo Garcia and defense attorneys agreed to Gutierrez's
request. The date was moved to Sept. 12.
   The woman told police the assaults took place over a four-hour
period and began at a rural area north of town where a late-night
cockfight was taking place. Those at the cockfight, she said,
either ignored her pleas for help or joined in the attacks in the
back seat and on the hood of a car.
   Ten men were indicted April 11 on charges ranging from
kidnapping and aggravated kidnapping to sexual assault. The
prosecutor said some of the rape cases may be combined.
</TEXT>
