<HEAD>Singer's Bail Set at $50,000, Release Contingent on Drug Center
Enrollment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bail for singer Robert DeBarge, who faces
cocaine smuggling charges, was set at $50,000 Monday on the
condition that he be released to a residential drug treatment
center.
   ``We wanted him detained until trial,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Steven G. Madison after U.S. Magistrate Joseph Reichmann
set bail. ``The defendant's own mother confirmed he has had an
ongoing drug problem since 1980 and said perhaps the arrest was a
blessing in disguise.''
   A hearing was set for July 22 on whether DeBarge should be
transferred to Michigan for trial. No trial date has been set.
   DeBarge, 32, who enjoyed success as a member of the singing
group Switch, and his 22-year-old brother, Jonathan, were indicted
last week by a Michigan grand jury that charged them with
conspiring to sell 2.2 pounds of cocaine brought to Michigan from
California.
   The two are members of a large Grand Rapids, Mich., family known
for both its singing talent and the legal troubles of several
members.
   The family's most famous brother, El DeBarge, was fined $100 and
ordered to perform 80 hours of community service after pleading no
contest to assault and battery charges in Grand Rapids in September
1986.
   Robert DeBarge was arrested in April 1986 after he allegedly
told a flight attendant on a flight from Chicago to Grand Rapids
that he was a terrorist and had a bomb. The charge was later
dismissed.
   Tommy DeBarge, another Switch member, received six months in
jail after pleading guilty to cocaine possession in March 1986.
</TEXT>
