<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Airliner-Congress 2ndLd-Writethru a0599 07-11 0876</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airliner-Congress, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0599,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Says Congress Receptive to Compensation, But Others
Doubtful</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 15th graf pvs, bgng: ``But Wright ...''
to INSERT Nunn comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is likely to be receptive to
President Reagan's request for compensation to families of those
killed in the U.S. shootdown of an Iranian airliner, House Speaker
Jim Wright said Monday.
   But some lawmakers called the request premature because
unanswered questions remain about the incident, and others
continued to call for release of U.S. hostages in Lebanon as a
requirement for any aid. Wright's chief Democratic vote-counter
said approval of the aid was far from a sure thing.
   Offering payments to the bereaved survivors of the 290 victims
would be ``a voluntary act committed by a nation that is both
generous and genuinely regretful'' of the incident, Wright,
D-Texas, told reporters. He said he expected quick action once
Reagan formally makes a request of Congress.
   ``If the president is satisfied (that payments are warranted), I
would imagine the Congress would be satisfied,'' Wright said.
Leading members of the congressional foreign policy and defense
committees have spoken out in favor of making such payments.
   But it was unclear whether approval could be taken for granted.
House Democratic Whip Tony Coelho of California, the party's chief
vote-counter, said he believed the request would ``have some
problems'' and said he was personally opposed to it.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said as long as Americans remain as
hostages in Lebanon, ``there will be resentment to any payment, to
any Iranian, under any circumstances.'' He said he believed Reagan
had made the offer as an emotional response to the downing of the
jetliner.
   The bipartisan leadership of Congress was scheduled to meet with
Reagan on Tuesday, and the compensation issue was expected to be
high on the agenda.
   Wright said it is important that the gesture not be seen as an
acknowledgement of guilt and that it not be routed through the
Iranian government, either of which would make it tougher for
Congress to swallow.
   The administration has emphasized that the compensation would be
distributed through non-governmental channels in Iran.
   A national Washington Post-ABC News poll last week found that 61
percent of those surveyed opposed the idea of paying compensation
and an even greater majority, 71 percent, believed the captain of
the USS Vincennes was justified in firing the missiles that downed
the commercial A300 Airbus.
   But Wright said he believed that was a misleading reading based
on early impressions that payment of compensation would somehow be
an apology to the Iranian government or an admission of U.S.
liability.
   ``It is a different proposition the way in which I think the
president stated it,'' he said.
   Several members of Congress have said the payments ought to be
linked to the release of American hostages being held in Lebanon by
radical factions said to be under Iranian control.
   McCain said letting the hostages go ``would show the Iranians
are interested in peace and concerned about the lives of innocent
human beings.'' He said the payments ``will be perceived as a
payoff to Iran, whether we like it or not.''
   But Wright said there should be no attempt to link the two
issues. ``That would appear to be a form of ransoming our hostages,
which we have refrained from doing,'' he said. Because the payments
would be made directly to bereaved families, no
government-to-government conditions could be attached, he added.
   The chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, Sen. Sam
Nunn, D-Ga., said his reaction to the president's announcement was
``generally positive,'' but that payment should hinge on whether
the Persian Gulf becomes a safer place.
   ``The actual payment should be made in connection with the end
of the (Iran-Iraq) war or at least the end of attacks by Iran and
Iraq on innocent shipping in the gulf,'' he said.
   Coelho was skeptical about the president's request. ``I'm not
inclined to provide payments to Iranians,'' he said. ``I want to
know who is at fault and everything about it ... Maybe we have
another secret Iran-Contra deal working. I don't understand why
they're trying to move it along.''
   It remained unclear precisely what legal authority would be used
to make the payments, or how they could be negotiated and arranged,
since the United States has no diplomatic relations with Iran.
   But Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., noted that ``if you are
interested in paying money, it's not hard to find a way.'' He said
he supported Reagan's proposal to ``show the Iranian people that
the people of the United States are a just society and that the
propaganda they get from their government about the United States
is false.''
   The payments would be what lawyers call ``ex gratia'' _ made
voluntarily without admitting guilt or liability. Under
international law, nations have no legal liability for damages
caused as a result of war or hostilities.
   But some administration advisers have been concerned that the
United States not be likened to the Soviet Union, which refused to
make compensation after shooting down a Korean Air Lines passenger
plane over the Sea of Japan in 1983, according to congressional
sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
