<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-11 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Envoy Fears Upsurge In Afghan Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. special envoy Diego Cordovez said Monday
there could be a brutal intensification of the war in Afghanistan
after the scheduled pullout of half of the Soviet military
contingent by Aug. 15.
   At a news conference after returning from his latest trip to the
region, Cordovez appealed anew for a Sept. 1 cease-fire and
establishment of a new Afghan government without Soviet-backed
President Najib and including political leaders from both sides of
the conflict.
   Cordovez said his mission is to solve a ``very serious political
impasse'' and he noted divisions among the various groups in the
seven-party Afghan guerrilla alliance.
   After mid-August ``there could be a very brutal intensification
of the military confrontation'' in the 10-year-old civil war, the
diplomat said.
   Cordovez made the cease-fire proposal in Islamabad, Pakistan, on
Saturday after separate talks with Afghan, Pakistani and Iranian
officials and with Soviet military commanders in Kabul, the capital
of Afghanistan.
   He did not meet with Afghan guerrilla leaders, who have vowed to
continue fighting until the government is toppled.
   His trip was aimed at resolving administrative and technical
problems involving the implementation and monitoring of the Afghan
accords that were signed in Geneva last April.
   Cordovez said he received assurances from Soviet and Afghan
officials that U.N. observers deployed under the agreement will
have access to Afghan airports to watch Soviet troops leave.
   The agreement calls for withdrawal of all Soviet troops by Feb.
15, with the first half to leave by mid-August. It includes
Afghan-Pakistani pledges of non-interference and for a safe return
of Afghan refugees. There are about 3 million refugees in Pakistan
and hundreds of thousands in Iran.
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979
to help the Marxist government battle the Islamic, anti-communist
guerrillas and has had an estimated 115,000 military personnel in
the country.
</TEXT>
