<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Protest 1stLd-Writethru a0760 07-11 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0760,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 200 Detained, 8 Injured In Anti-Government March</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-3 UPDATE with 200 detained, more injured. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, The march ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police used tear gas and water
cannons Monday night to scatter hundreds of anti-government
demonstrators who staged a ``March of Hunger'' to protest the
military regime's economic policies.
   Five buses were set afire, police said. A bus driver and a
firefighter were badly burned and were hospitalized in serious
condition, the official news agency Orbe said.
   About 200 demonstrators were detained, Orbe reported. It said
one police officer and five demonstrators were injured, none
seriously.
   The march was called by several communist-controlled
organizations of slum dwellers and joined by hundreds of other
demonstrators, most of them students.
   Police fought running skirmishes with the protesters for almost
three hours. Scattered groups of demonstrators were repatedly
dispersed by police, but quickly regrouped at a different
intersection to resume their protest.
   The demonstrators blocked traffic, sometimes with flaming
barricades, at a number of busy downtown intersections, as
thousands of office workers returned home from work.
   Earlier in the day, a dozen bombs went off at various points in
this capital city of 4.5 million people, causing damage but no
victims, according to police.
</TEXT>
