<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DroughtRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0671 07-11 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0671,0924</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scattered Rain But States Say Drought Still Threatening</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 3rd graf, `A cold ...' to UPDATE with
smog, ozone levels elevated in rural areas. Picks up 4th graf, `In
Washington ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Kentucky's governor blasted the federal government Monday for
being too slow in dealing with the drought, and Iowa's governor
warned that farmers there still face potential disaster despite up
to 5 inches of rain over the weekend.
   Crews began installing pumps on barges Monday to haul fresh
water to southern Louisiana towns plagued by rising salt levels in
the lower Mississippi River, which has been so weakened by the
drought that salty seawater is forcing its way inland.
   A cold front brought showers and lower temperatures to parts of
the Midwest and Plains, but a heat wave lingered in the East. New
York City hit a record 98 degrees, its fifth day in six of highs of
90 or better, and downtown Baltimore reached a record 102.
Connecticut's Department of Environmental Protection said air
quality was unhealthful to very unhealthful.
   Meanwhile, the hot, dry weather has brought big-city smog to the
countryside from Maine to Georgia during the past two weeks, a
Pennsylvania State University professor said Monday.
   Accumulated city pollutants _ mostly from car exhaust _ have
spread across the region, at times pushing ozone levels beyond
federal air quality standards, said John M. Skelly, a professor of
plant pathology who researches the effects of air pollition and
acid rain on forests.
   Much of an area from Maine to Georgia and as far west as Chicago
recorded ozone levels higher than 120 part per billion for 10
straight days ending Friday, he said.
   A reading of of more than 120 for one hour on two consecutive
days violates U.S. Environmental Protection Agency air quality
standards. Levels of 100 or higher can cause shortness of breath,
raspy throats, sore eyes and irritated mucous membranes.
   In Washington, House Speaker Jim Wright said he hopes a drought
relief package with disaster payments of up to $100,000 per farmer
will win committee approval and be ready for floor action in
Congress this week. He said the bill being drawn up would make
farmers in more than 1,880 counties in 37 states that have been
called disaster areas eligible for payments.
   Officials said the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers is still weeks
away from deciding whether more Great Lakes water should be
diverted to the Mississippi for barge traffic. That is opposed by
most Great Lakes governors and the government of Canada.
   The drought could even force dozens of Kentucky's small
thoroughbred horse operations out of business because it is forcing
up the price of oats and hay, an industry official says.
   In addition, dusty, dry fields cause more respiratory problems
for horses, resulting in higher medical bills, says Nick Nicholson,
executive vice president of the Kentucky Thoroughbred Association.
Kentucky has about 4,000 horse farms and in 1986 public auctions of
horses generated $520 million.
   Some parts of Iowa got up to 5 inches of rain over the weekend,
but totals of about one-half inch were more common.
   ``We're certainly not out of the emergency situation,'' Iowa
Gov. Terry Branstad said. ``Some of the corn crop has already been
severely damaged. They're going to have to have additional moisture
in the very near future, the next 10 days or so.''
   Branstad said farmers who have private crop insurance should be
eligible for public aid programs, even though they'll receive
partial payment for their losses from that coverage, to encourage
more people to get such protection.
   Widespread rain has alleviated the drought across Louisiana but
means only a partial recovery, Agriculture Commissioner Bob Odom
told the Louisiana Farm Bureau Federation convention Monday.
   Of about 700,000 acres of cotton planted across Louisiana, he
said, an estimated 100,000 acres will be abandoned or plowed under
and replanted in soybeans. That could mean a loss of $35 million to
$40 million, he said.
   Hundreds of Kentucky's city and county officials met Monday to
hear predictions that the drought could get worse.
   Because so much ground moisture already has been lost in
Kentucky, ``a return to normal rainfall won't break the drought,''
said state climatologist Glen Conner. ``Severe or extreme
conditions likely will persist through September.''
   Kentucky Gov. Wallace Wilkinson scored Agriculture Secretary
Richard E. Lyng and the U.S. Department of Agriculture for saying
it was too early to determine how much crop yield had been lost.
   ``I don't think Washington has acted strongly or swiftly
enough,'' Wilkinson told reporters. ``Anybody who couldn't
determine that yields have been damaged before now shouldn't be in
agriculture.''
   Parts of Ohio got scattered light rain Monday, the first to fall
this month. Mercer County extension agent Earl J. Beiler told of
two farmers within five miles of each other near Rockford who
reported widely varying amounts.
   ``One had two-tenths (of an inch) and the other had
seven-tenths,'' Beiler said. ``As dry as it is, the seven-tenths
will probably get down and do some good, but the two-tenths is
hardly enough to wash the dust off.''
   Not everyone suffers from too little water.
   Three to 6 inches of rain fell on parts of Texas, flooding some
low-lying roads. Verde Creek reportedly rose 7 feet and the weather
service said the Llano River's north fork near Roosevelt swelled 22
feet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
