<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JobbersCanyon     07-11 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jobbers Canyon,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Begins In Suit To Save Jobbers Canyon, Historic District
In Omaha</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Trust for Historic Preservation
asked a federal magistrate Monday to stop the demolition of a
historic warehouse district where a food company wants to build a
$50 million corporate headquarters and research complex.
   The trust, a group calling itself People for Responsible Omaha
Urban Development and others want an injunction preventing ConAgra
Inc. from leveling the Jobbers Canyon warehouse district.
   The hearing before Magistrate Richard Kopf was expected to last
a week.
   The 20-acre district near downtown and the Missouri River
consists of turn-of-the-century warehouses and is on the National
Register of Historic Places. Several buildings in the district
already have been razed.
   Steve Achelpohl, who represents the trust, argued that plans for
the riverfront development project should be subject to approval of
the Interstate Commerce Commission, the National Park Service and
the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.
   He said the federal agencies must approve various aspects of the
project, including railroad track abandonment and changes in flood
control procedures.
   But assistant U.S. attorney Paul Madgett, who represents the
federal agencies, moved for dismissal of the case, saying the
agencies weren't involved in the project and there was no
indication any federal money would be involved.
   Kopf took Madgett's motion under advisement.
</TEXT>
