<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TexasStorms 1stLd-Writethru a0718 07-11 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Storms, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0718,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Rivers Flood After Storm; Five Drown, One Missing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with description of victim,
waters receding, other detail. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The
flooding...'. ADDS 3 grafs on end with further quotes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain sent creeks and rivers raging out
of their banks Monday in central Texas, drowning at least one
motorist and stranding others after killing four other people in
the western part of the state.
   In the central Texas Hill Country, Kerr County authorities
searched for a 33-year-old man missing after a truck was swept away
by the rapidly rising Guadalupe River near Hunt. The body of his
13-year-old brother was found about 100 yards downstream.
   The river had risen 21 feet by midafternoon near Hunt,
destroying piers and docks at summer camps along its banks.
Barrels, picnic tables and small rafts floated downstream. But the
waters were receding late in the day.
   Authorities did not release the names of the dead boy or his
missing brother. A third person in the truck, Dan Knight, escaped
harm after vain attempts to save his companions.
   The flooding came nearly a year after 10 teen-agers drowned when
the church bus and van they were in was swept away by the Guadalupe
river near Comfort.
   Sgt. Mike West of the Kerr County sheriff's office said that all
campers seemed to be safe this time. ``A lot of the camps are more
alert now because of what happened last year,'' he said.
   Farther west, Cipriano Enriquez Rodriquez told Pecos County
authorities that he and four family members were caught by flooding
in Perkins Draw late Sunday while driving a state highway to Del
Rio.
   The draw normally is a dry creekbed, but up to 8 inches of rain
Sunday caused flash floods, officials said.
   Rodriquez, 47, of San Jose, Calif., survived by clinging to a
tree overnight, then walked about 4 miles to Sheffield, said Pecos
County Sheriff Bruce Wilson.
   His wife, son-in-law and two grandchildren drowned, officials
said. Their bodies were found Monday morning.
   In the central Texas incident, Knight said he tried to help his
two companions, whom he declined to identify.
   ``I got the both of them (out of the truck) and I put them on my
chest,'' he said. ``In the water they don't weigh that much. We
floated about a half-mile down to the bend and I was still holding
to them. A log hit my head and arm pretty hard and I had to let
them go.''
   ``He risked his own life to save them,'' said a witness, Evelyn
Hickey. ``He had made several attempts at the boy, but the other
man pulled them down. When he couldn't help them anymore, he got
out a long way down stream.''
</TEXT>
