<HEAD>Shultz calls Nicaraguan Expulsion of US diplomats Outrageous</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Secretary of State George P.
Shultz said Tuesday the expulsion of the U.S. ambassador and seven
other American diplomats from Nicaragua was an `` absolute
outrage.''
   Shultz made the remark when reporters asked him to comment on
the expulsions, ordered by the leftist Sandinista government on
charges that U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton and the seven others
were undermining the Managua government.
   ``Well, it's an absolute outrage,'' Shultz said of the expulsion
order. He did not say what action he planned to take.
   ``When they talk about destabilizing Nicaragua, it's the
government of Nicaragua that's detabilizing Nicaragua because of
the way they are conducting themselves, including, just yesterday,
breaking up a rally with tear gas and things of that kind,'' Shultz
added.
   The expulsion order came a day after police in Nicaragua clashed
with thousands of anti-Sandinista demonstrators.
   Shultz arrived in Manila Monday for talks with President Corazon
Aquino and other officials. Shultz's 36-hour visit in the
Philippines is his fourth stop on a nine-nation tour of Asia.
