<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HousingIntegration     07-11 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Integration,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Families Enter South Boston Project Without Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two black families moved into apartments in a
formerly all-white housing project without incident Monday as
authorities kept bystanders and the media at a distance.
   Boston police watched as movers carried furniture and belongings
into the three-story brick buildings at the South Boston project,
which has been without black tenants for more than 10 years.
   South Boston, a predominantly white neighborhood, was the scene
of racial violence when public schools were integrated under a
federal court order more than a decade ago.
   The families were granted three-bedroom apartments as part of an
emergency Boston Housing Authority program.
   The move, however, was unconnected to an integration plan
affecting 31 of Boston's 69 projects. The plan by Boston Mayor
Raymond L. Flynn and the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development seeks to provide subsidized housing for an estimated
500 black families passed over for placement in South Boston and
the city's Charlestown section since 1983.
   City officials hope successful implementation of the plan will
stall a lawsuit by minority groups.
   Boston police spokesman James Jordan said authorities have a
``public safety plan'' for the South Boston project, adding,
``should anything happen, the police response would be virtually
immediate. It's an intensive plan, but with a low visibilty as far
as uniforms are concerned.''
   ``I'm no pioneer,'' said one of the new black residents, Bessie
Payne, on the eve of the move. ``I'm just almost a homeless person
_ and I don't like that feeling at all. I'm looking forward to
making a new home and getting my life straightened out again.''
   Many residents watching the families move in said the black
families would not encounter problems from neighbors.
   ``I really think the press has blown it out of proportion,''
said 18-year-old Kelly Manion, watching movers carry furniture
through a doorway decorated with shamrocks. ``We'll get along
together. In fact, it just might be good for the people living
here.''
   Another neighbor, who refused to give her name, said: ``It's
just like any family moving in. They won't be treated any different
than anyone else new to the project.''
   But Julie Jellow was less optimistic about tranquility in the
project. Jellow, 29, said she has received threats and abuse
because of her two children fathered by a black man.
</TEXT>
