<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Perot-PostalContract     07-11 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Perot-Postal Contract,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Board Again Asserts Its Jurisdiction Over Postal Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Services Administration appeals
board on Monday reiterated its contention that it has jurisdiction
over a Postal Service contract with Texas billionaire H. Ross Perot
and ruled that it will hear complaints about the contract.
   The Postal Service maintains the GSA does not have authority
over the contract, but on Friday suspended its contract with Perot
because the GSA's Board of Contract Appeals had ordered the pact
suspended.
   ``The Postal Service continues to believe that the contract
appeals board does not have jurisdiction,'' said Jim Van Loozen, a
spokesman for the Postal Service.
   But ``we would hope that they would now bring those matters to
some conclusion ... and rule promptly on those protests,'' Van
Loozen added.
   At least two competitors of Perot had complained to the
contracts board about the pact, under which Perot agreed to study
ways to improve the agency's efficiency.
   Van Loozen said the contract dispute concerns whether the Postal
Service complied with the Brooks Act, a law outlining contracting
procedures for most federal entities.
   ``We have already agreed that we did not comply with the act.
The postal reorganization act of 1970, that set up the Postal
Service as an independent agency, gives us specific authority to
contract for ourselves,'' said Van Loozen.
   The agency last week asked the federal appeals court to rule on
whether the GSA contracts board has jurisdiction over its
activities. No date has been set for that hearing.
</TEXT>
