<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DigestBriefs     07-11 1196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Digest Briefs,1246</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: This package does not contain the following items from the
News Digest: PIRAEUS, Greece _ Greece-Ship Blast; WASH _ Airliner
Rdp; ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Helicopter Escape; UNDATED _ Political
Rdp.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Security Council convenes Tuesday to debate
the shooting down of an Iranian airliner by a U.S. warship, and
Iran wants the Americans condemned for killing the 290 people
aboard.
   The United States, Britain and France are expected to use their
veto power as permanent council members to stop any censure
resolution or demand that the U.S. fleet leave the Persian Gulf.
   Requesting the debate is a turnabout for Iran, which has
boycotted council sessions for years because, it says, the
15-nation body bows to pressure from Washington and is biased
against Iran in the 8-year-old war with Iraq.
   It was not clear Monday whether a resolution would be presented
for a vote. Iranian officials have said they seek condemnation of
the United States and a demand that the U.S. Navy withdraw.
   The White House announced Monday that President Reagan has
approved U.S. compensation for the families of the 290 people who
died aboard the Iranian jet. Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
amount of compensation had not yet been decided upon and the
payments could be subject to congressional approval.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A vote tally released Monday gave the
government party's candidate for president a majority, but the slow
count fed rumors of party infighting and fraud.
   Interior Secretary Manuel Bartlett said early Monday that Carlos
Salinas de Gortari of the governing Institutuional Revolutionary
Party, known as the PRI for its Spanish initials, had 52.89 percent
of the votes counted.
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the leftist National Democratic Front was
second with 29.10 percent and conservative National Action Party
candidate Manuel Clouthier third with 16.68 percent, Bartlett said.
Election officials said 13.24 million votes had been counted from
Wednesday's election but did not say how many of the nation's 38
million registered voters cast ballots.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has chosen former
Pennsylvania Gov. Dick Thornburgh to replace Edwin Meese III as
attorney general during the remaining six months of the Reagan
presidency, a knowledgeable administration source said Monday.
   The source, who declined to be identified by name, said that
Thornburgh, a moderate Republican who once headed the Justice
Department's criminal division, had accepted the offer.
   Elsie Hillman, head of George Bush's presidential campaign in
Pennsylvania and a Republican National committeewoman, said in
Harrisburg, Pa., that she was told by Bush campaign officials that
Thornburgh had been asked to take the job. Thornburgh served two
four-year terms in the Pennsylvania state capital, Harrisburg.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's military chief of staff
announced Monday an agreement designed to ease superpower friction
through creation of a ``military-to-military working group,'' but
said the Red Army plans no unilateral withdrawal from Central
Europe.
   Ending a weeklong tour of the United States, Marshal Sergei
Akhromeyev met with President Reagan at the White House before
unveiling the agreement at the Pentagon with the chairman of the
U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William Crowe.
   Along with creation of the joint working group, designed to head
off brushfire incidents between the two sides, the two officials
also announced future tour exchanges among top commanders and
several other steps designed to enhance mutual understanding,
including port visits by warships.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev offered
Monday to withdraw an unspecified number of air forces from Eastern
Europe if NATO drops plans to deploy 72 U.S.-built, F-16
fighter-bombers in Italy.
   Gorbachev also said that East and West European leaders should
informally explore ways to break the impasse in negotiations aimed
at reducing conventional forces in Europe.
   The Communist Party chief made the proposals in an address to
the Polish parliament, the Sejm, at the start of a six-day visit to
Poland.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Umm Issam held her year-old granddaughter
outside her ruined cement-block shanty in Beirut's Chatilla refugee
camp, where invaders and factional wars have killed her husband and
four sons since 1982.
   An artillery shell hit her home a few days ago, destroying it
for the fourth time in six years.
   What was left of Chatilla from earlier battles lies in ruins
after two months of fighting between Palestinian factions.
Guerrillas of Saeed Mousa's Fatah-Uprising faction, backed by
Syria, overran it June 27 and ousted Yasser Arafat's Fatah
loyalists.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peddlers of hot dogs and sushi, frozen yogurt
and hot soup have for five years ignored a law that would keep them
off the sidewalks where business is best. On Monday, the vendors
fell victim to politics.
   In an effort to rid some of the city's busiest corners of
congestion, police armed with forklifts were sent for take out: not
food, but the pushcarts that sell quick and affordable lunches and
snacks. The vendors were there, with their familiar orange-and-blue
umbrellas, but the pushcarts weren't.
   ``We're trying to spoil the policemen's party,'' said hot dog
vendor Thomas Michaelides. ``They'll get no blood from me today.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the 69th General Convention of the
Episcopal Church reaffirmed the church's opposition to abortion
Monday and narrowly upheld a policy that lets dioceses decide
whether to bar homosexuals from the priesthood.
   A resolution expanding ``access to the selection process for
ordination'' for all people, including homosexuals _ but refusing
to recognize a right to ordination _ fell one vote short of passage
by lay members of the House of Deputies.
   The 900-member House of Deputies, divided between lay and
clerical church members, and the 200-member House of Bishops
establishes policy for the 2.7 million-member church, whose
nine-day convention ended Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GEARHART, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of residents of this coastal town
showed up to help search a beach where a missing teen-ager's
bicycle was found hidden in the brush.
   Within days, state police concluded that 15-year-old Dorene
Raterman had been killed at Del Ray Beach, just a half-mile from
her home, and then two men were arrested in connection with her
death.
   But Dorene's body has not been found. And that leaves the case
resting largely on the testimony of one of the men under arrest,
described as slightly retarded, who says the other one admitted
killing the girl. The second man denies it.
   And as frustration and anger grow, there's been talk in town of
vigilantism.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Breakdancing? That's old. If you want to be cool
in Beijing this summer, pool is the game.
   Pool tables have appeared on sidewalks all over the city in a
craze that participants attribute to television coverage of a
recent international pool tournament in Beijing.
   Never mind that many of the tables tilt or rock slightly because
of uneven sidewalks, or that the players miss shots more often than
not.
   In a city where most residents flee their tiny, hot apartments
on summer evenings and mahjong and card games are the only
diversions, pool is a welcome discovery. The tables are set up
outdoors because few people have the space inside.
</TEXT>
