<DOCNO> AP880711-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--SovietHeartland Adv24-1stAdd   07-11 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Soviet Heartland, Adv 24-1st Add,0741</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 24</NOTE>
<HEAD>ASHKHABAD, U.S.S.R.: Central Asians.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Even government officials and members of the Communist Party
``pander to obsolete views'' and take part in Moslem rituals,
Gorbachev noted while on a 1986 tour of Uzbekistan. He ordered such
people held ``strictly to account.''
   ``Almost one third of the people in our republic remain under
the control of Islam,'' Murod N. Khudoyev, deputy propaganda chief
for Tadzhikistan's Communist Party, remarked with obvious
disapproval. ``Half of those with a middle-school education see no
difference between the words `Tadzhik' and `Moslem.'''
   Still, Gorbachev's rise to power has tightened the Kremlin's
hold on the area. In the three years since he became general
secretary, party bosses in all five republics have been replaced
and many of their underlings sent into political obilivion.
   One high-level ouster showed how the region's ethnic differences
and latent hostility toward the politically dominant Russians can
flare into violence. In December 1986, Dinmukhamed Kunaev, a
Kazakh, was fired as party boss in corruption-riddled Kazakhstan,
and replaced by a Russian, Gennady Kolbin.
   Thousands of young Kazakhs rioted in the republic's capital,
Alma Ata, and went on a two-day rampage of looting and arson in
which two people were killed, 200 injured and dozens arrested.
   More commonly, though, the Central Asians co-exist with the
large European populations that began flowing southward with the
establishment of czarist power in the 19th century.
   But this is not a melting pot.
   In Dushanbe, Tadzhikistan's sycamore-dotted capital city of
600,000, only about 5 percent of the marriages join Tadzhiks and
Russians. In the countryside, where two-thirds of the republic's
4.8 million people live, laborers in the fields do not understand
simple questions in Russian.
   Nevertheless, Russian is the language of power and prestige and
of local elites.
   In Tashkent, the region's most populous city with 2.1 million
inhabitants, there is only one Russian child among the 829 pupils
of Middle School No. 9, where instruction is in Uzbek.
   But Russian language courses are mandatory.
   ``It's the language of culture and of contact,'' explains the
principal, Natalya A. Mamutova.
   In education, sanitation and health care, the new Soviet seems
more Third World than superpower. In Turkmenia, 55 of every 1,000
babies die before their first birthday, giving the swath of desert
north of Afghanistan and Iran the Soviet Union's highest infant
death rate, a figure more than twice the national average of 25 per
1,000.
   Local officials proudly note that although not a single
university existed in Central Asia before the 1917 Bolshevik
Revolution, Kazakhstan alone now has 275,000 students in its
institutions of higher learning.
   But an army general has complained publicly that Uzbek school
graduates learn so little in school that they have to be taught in
the army to scrub their teeth and that they don't understand the
simplest orders in Russian.
   In some areas of Central Asia, the infant mortality rate is as
high as 70 per 1,000 live births _ seven times the U.S. figure _
the labor daily Trud reported recently.
   Ashkhabad's Maternity Hospital, where seven-pound, one-ounce
Murad Khydyrov was born, is a microcosm of sanitation problems. Its
green walls were streaked with dirt, and a pair of forceps lay on
the floor in the room where Murad was swaddled.
   A special SWAT team of doctors from the European Soviet Union
was dispatched recently to the fabled ancient cities of Samarkand
and Bukhara in Uzbekistan to combat an outbreak of hepatitis.
   With the area's population rise, those problems seem fated to
increase, as well as the knotty task of finding work for Central
Asia's new sons and daughters.
   Tadzhikstan now has 234,000 residents classified as ``not taking
part in social production,'' and Umarov, the economist, says
300,000 new jobs must be created in the next seven years to keep
pace with the birthrate.
   Nevertheless, local elites stress the progress made in the
region under Soviet rule, voice their faith in perestroika and
compare their lands not with Europe, but with neighboring Asian
countries.
   ``If you want to see what Soviet power has done for our people,
go to the peaks of our Pamir mountains, and look down at
Tadzhikistan, then at Afghanistan across the border and compare,''
says Dushabne Mayor Makhsud M. Ikramov.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 24</NOTE>
