<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The unemployment rate sank to a 14-year low of
5.3 percent in June, spurred by a boom in summertime work for
teen-agers, the government reported.
   Joblessness among black youths fell more than 6 percentage
points to its lowest level on record, according to Friday's report.
   The 0.3 percentage point drop from May's 5.6 percent jobless
rate was caused by a seasonally adjusted surge of 820,000 people _
three-fourths of them youths 16 to 24 years old _ onto the nation's
payrolls, the Labor Department said.
