<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NameChanges     07-11 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Name Changes,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record 931 Corporations Change Names In First Half Of 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record number of American corporations changed
their names during the first six months of 1988, with financial
institutions and manufacturing companies heading the list,
according to a corporate identity survey.
   Of the 931 name changes, 53 percent were because of mergers and
acquisitions, the survey by Anspach Grossman Portugal Inc. found.
Another 21 percent stemmed from divestitures, spinoffs, leveraged
buyouts and sales of assets, the survey showed.
   But some companies created new names hoping for a new corporate
image, said the report released today.
   Last year, 1,753 corporations changed their names, 919 in the
first half.
   ``Special circumstances apply to every name change situation,''
said Joel Portugal, a principal of Anspach Grossman Portugal.
``It's difficult to generalize, to say real names are better than
created names or vice versa.''
   Eighteen of the newly named companies are listed on the New York
Stock Exchange, including three whose names became initials during
the first half of 1988. Allegis Corp. returned to UAL Corporation;
Bell Canada Enterprises Inc., changed to BCE, Inc.; and Sealed
Power Co. became SPX Corp.
   Three Japanese corporations operating in the United States
simplified their names: Konishiroku U.S.A. changed to Konica U.S.A;
Nippon Kogaku became Nikon Corp.; and Nippon Kokan America is now
NKK America.
   Some known names disappeared during the first half of the year.
Standard Oil is now BP America after a merger; and Diamond Crystal
Salt has become DSLT Inc. after selling its salt operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
