<HEAD>Dollar Steady After Reported Central Bank Intervention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar steadied in moderate but nervous
trading in Europe today in response to what appeared to be
concerted central bank intervention. Gold prices rose.
   The central banks of West Germany, Switzerland, Italy, the
Netherlands and Belgium intervened, selling dollars in the open
market when the U.S. currency reached 1.8435 West German marks
early today, dealers said.
   The amount of intervention was not known, but it was sufficient
to put a lid on the dollar's advance, traders said.
   ``I think the dollar is a bit high. Some profit-taking will
prevent it from moving much higher,'' a trader in Rome said.
   But another Rome trader said he expected the dollar to continue
its advance.
   ``For now, the market is going only in one direction,'' he said.
   He added that some profit-taking was likely this week ahead of
the U.S. trade figures for May, to be released Friday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 1.36 Japanese yen to a closing 133.33
yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 133.31 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.8410 West German marks, up from 1.8378; 1.5313
Swiss francs, up from 1.5295; 6.1925 French francs, up from 6.1820;
2.0769 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0605; 1,364.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,355.50; and 1.2095 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.6978, compared
with $1.7015 on Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $438.90 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $438.50. At mid-morning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$439.65.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $439.50, unchanged from late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 96 cents to close at a bid
$442.04.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $7.04 a troy
ounce, up from Friday's $7.01.
</TEXT>
