<HEAD>Dollar Up Sharply, Stocks Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed sharply higher against the
Japanese yen today, while prices on the Tokyo stock market gained
moderately.
   After opening at 133.60 yen, the U.S. currency eased to finish
the day's trading at 133.33 yen, up 1.36 yen from Friday's closing.
Trading ranged between 133.10-133.65 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average index of
25 selected issues, the market's main barometer, closed today at
27,985.99 points, up 68.91 points, or 0.24 percent.
   ``There is a strong wait-and-see attitude in the market,'' a
trader with a major Tokyo brokerage said. ``But the rise in the
Nikkei reflected the market's overall energy.'' The Nikkei index
was a 188.95-point winner Friday.
   Volume on the market's first section was 1.1 billion shares,
down from 1.4 billion traded Friday. Only 400 million shares were
traded on the first section during the afternoon session, when
foodstuffs, constructions and real estates were being sought.
   Traders said the market was nervous about higher interest rates,
and showed concern about reports today that analysts expect the
U.S. Federal Reserve to tighten monetary policy and perhaps raise
the official U.S. discount rate this week.
   Exchange dealers were believed to be reacting to improved
economic indicators in the United States, including the jobless
rate, which fell 0.3 percentage points in June.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said the
dollar also rose on a comment by an unidentified U.S. government
official Friday that Washington would tolerate the greenback's rise
to about 135 yen.
   The dollar came close to that level last Monday, reaching 134.80
yen, its highest closing since late November.
</TEXT>
