<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drought-SeedCorn     07-11 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Seed Corn,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seed Corn Companies Look to South America In Drought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say there should be no shortage
of seed corn for next year's crop even if this year's drought
decimates 1988 yields, but seed corn producers aren't taking any
chances.
   With Midwest fields withering, American seed corn companies are
looking south for crops this winter to replenish their stockpiles.
   ``We are looking in Texas, Argentina and Chile,'' said Joan
Olson, a spokeswoman for Northrup King Co., one of the top five
seed corn producers for the U.S. market.
   The nation's largest seed corn producer, Pioneer Hi-Bred
International of Des Moines, is negotiating for more corn
production in Chile and Argentina if the U.S. drought results in
crop widespread crop failure, said Owen Newlin, a senior vice
president at the company.
   He said Pioneer already grows seed for the local market in South
America, and has processing plants that can shell and dry corn
there.
   ``We will be increasing their capacity considerably,'' Newlin
said.
   He added that after pollination of the U.S. seed corn crop in
about two weeks the company will decide how much production it will
need from South America, as well as from Florida and Texas.
   ``We haven't got all of our plans firmed up,'' Newlin said. ``We
don't really know how bad things are going to be here.''
   DeKalb Corp., the second-largest seed corn producer in the
United States, still expects to ``get a crop in the U.S. large
enough'' to meet its needs, said spokesman Bob Pritchard.
   But he noted that the company has a processing plant in Chile,
and ``obviously we're considering all the options.''
   Despite the drought, there are no predictions of shortages of
seed corn for next spring.
   About a fourth of hybrid seed corn is grown under irrigation,
and enough leftover seed sits in company warehouses to plant up to
half of this year's corn acreage again, observers say.
   But a short harvest this year will likely result in expanded
planting next year. Many seed corn companies expect 1989 corn
acreage to increase 10 percent to 15 percent.
   ``I think there will be ample seed corn to plant, but a good bit
of it will be lower quality simply because it's carry-over,'' said
Craig Carver, a stock analyst with Dain Bosworth in Minneapolis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
