<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-11 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened sharply lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to substantial
weekend rains in some key growing areas of the drought-stricken
Midwest.
   Prices of some contracts for future delivery of corn, oats and
soybeans dropped their limits for daily trading immediately after
the opening bell. Wheat also was sharply lower.
   ``It's all because of the improved weather,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``We had a
foreshadowing of this last week when the grains sold off, and over
the weekend we had the rains.''
   Weekend showers brought relief to parts of Wisconsin, Michigan,
Indiana and Iowa, where some areas received up to five inches of
rain.
   Lespinasse said private forecasters expected scattered showers
to continue in the Midwest for the next couple of days, which
should keep the pressure on grain futures prices.
   Cautious trading was expected ahead of Tuesday's special crop
report from the Agriculture Department, which will provide
planted-acreage totals and revised supply-demand projections.
   In early trading, wheat was 9{ cents to 13 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.85 a bushel; corn was 14}
cents to 15 cents lower with July at $2.95{ a bushel; oats were 10
cents to 12 cents lower with July at $2.81 a bushel; soybeans were
31 cents to 42{ cents lower with July at $8.82 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mostly
lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .55 cent lower to .53 cent higher with August
at 65.55 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to 1.05 cents
higher with August at 75.30 cents a pound; hogs were 1.35 cents
lower to .05 cent higher with July at 45.40 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .20 cent to 1.40 cents lower with July at 32.80
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed and pork futures finished lower on
Friday.
</TEXT>
