<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Beecham     07-11 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Beecham,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beecham Sells U.S. Cosmetics Business for $91.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beecham Group PLC, a major British pharmaceuticals
company, said Monday it sold its last U.S. cosmetics business,
Beecham Cosmetics Inc., for $91.5 million.
   The buyer of Beecham Cosmetics, which owns the Jovan and
Vitabath brands, is a consortium organized by the division's
management and Bankers Trust Co. of New York.
   The sale marks the completion of Beecham Group's withdrawal from
the U.S. cosmetics business, although it still has interests in
pharmaceuticals and toiletries in the United States. It sold its
Germaine Monteil and Diane von Furstenberg cosmetics businesses in
the United States in March 1987.
   A Beecham spokeswoman, who spoke on condition that she not be
identified, in accordance with British practice, said the company
decided to withdraw because its cosmetics interests were not large
enough to compete adequately in the U.S. market.
   Beecham intends to concentrate on developing its pharmaceuticals
and toiletry business in the United States, she said.
</TEXT>
