<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-MGMSale 1stLd-Writethru   07-11 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MGM Sale, 1st Ld-Writethru,0515</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with announcement. Includes byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The MGM movie and television production
company will be split off from MGM-UA Communications Co. by
majority owner Kirk Kerkorian in a restructuring worth $400
million, it was announced today.
   Investor Burt Sugarman and two movie producers will acquire 25
percent of MGM, formerly the Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures studios,
with its familar roaring lion logo. Kerkorian will retain at least
57 percent.
   MGM-UA stock was off $1 a share at $14.75 in midday trading,
after formal announcement of the deal by MGM-UA and Sugarman's
Barris Industries Inc.
   Rumors of a sale or restructuring have been circulating for
weeks. The transaction announced today was first reported Sunday in
the Los Angeles Times.
   Sugarman, the Beverly Hills investor who recently failed to gain
control of Media General Inc. of Richmond, Va., in a bitter proxy
battle, will team up with movie producers Jon Peters and Peter
Guber to buy 25 percent of MGM.
   Present stockholders of MGM-UA will be offered the right to buy
new MGM stock for $8 a share, the same price paid by the Sugarman
group.
   Kerkorian, holder of 82 percent of MGM-UA, will exercise all his
subscription rights to the new MGM stock, and will buy any MGM
stock which isn't purchased by others, the announcement said.
   That will give Kerkorian at least 57 percent of MGM as well as
retaining controlling interest in the original company, to be
renamed United Artists.
   Under the arrangement, MGM-UA will sell 50 million shares of new
stock in MGM for $8 a share. Of the proceeds, $100 million would
come back to MGM and the rest would be used to repay MGM-UA debt.
   Both companies will continue to produce movies and MGM will have
a 50 percent share in the present MGM-UA distribution system. The
deal is expected to close in the fall, the companies said.
   MGM's library of 3,000 movies was sold to Turner Broadcasting
System Inc. in 1986 for more than $1 billion, and its studio lot
was later sold to Lorimar-Telepictures Corp. The deal is expected
to close in the fall, the companies said.
   Guber will be MGM's chairman and chief executive officer and
Peters will be president and chief operating officer. The pair has
produced such movies as ``The Color Purple,'' ``Witches of
Eastwick'' and ``Caddyshack.''
   Peters and Guber manage Barris Industries, producer of TV's
``The Newlywed Game'' and ``The Dating Game.''
   A hint that further shuffling may be in the offing was contained
in a company statement attributed to MGM-UA president Stephen
Silbert: ``We are still considering further transactions which, if
they come to fruition, could result in MGM-UA's stockholders being
offered the opportunity to dispose of all or part of their shares.''
   MGM-UA, which has endured several quarters of losses, produced
the successful movie ``Moonstruck'' and TV's ``thirtysomething.''
It has a library of 1,000 titles, including the ``Rocky'' and
``Pink Panther'' movies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
