<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Textron-Raycon     07-11 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Textron-Raycon,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textron to Sell Raycon Unit to George Fischer Corp.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Buyer's parent company name, Georg Fisher AG, is CQ.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textron Inc. announced Monday it plans
to sell its Raycon unit to George Fischer Corp. of Mount Prospect,
Ill. for an undisclosed amount.
   The sale is expected to close sometime this month, Textron
officials said.
   According to Textron, Raycon is among the leading producers and
distributors of electrical discharge machines worldwide and also
develops and markets industrial laser systems.
   Raycon was founded in 1965 and became part of Textron after the
Ex-Cell-O acquisition in 1986. The company employs 160 people at
its manufacturing facilities in Ann Arbor and Owosso, Mich.
   Textron has operations in aerospace technology, commercial
products and financial services.
   Textron earned $256 million on revenue of $7.2 billion in 1987,
but does not break figures for the Raycon unit, said spokesman
Raymond W. Caine Jr.
   George Fischer Corp. is a subsidiary of Georg Fisher AG of
Schaffhausen, Switzerland. The Swiss company was founded in 1802
and employs 14,500 people _ 500 of them in the United States. Its
businesses include foundries, piping systems, manufacturing
technology and plant engineering and construction.
</TEXT>
