<DOCNO> AP880711-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1525EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-11 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures dropped to their lowest
levels in about a month Monday as weekend rains in the thirsty
Midwest prompted a third straight day of plummeting prices on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Most contracts traded down their daily limits within minutes of
the opening bell. The contracts for July delivery, on which the
limits have been removed pending their July 20 expiration,
continued to trade _ generally lower.
   July soybeans fell 66 cents a bushel to $8.58, the lowest price
for that contract since June 3. Corn for July delivery dropped 20{
cents to $2.89 a bushel, the lowest level since June 15.
   Weekend showers that brought widespread relief to Midwestern
croplands eased fears of drastic yield reductions, analysts said.
   Some private forecasters expected scattered showers to continue
in the Corn Belt for the next couple of days, which should keep the
pressure on grain futures prices, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   But, he cautioned, ``if the weather goes back to hot and dry,
and that persists for a week or 10 days, we will go back up again.
One rain does not make a crop.''
   At the close, wheat was 16} cents to the limit 20 cents lower
with July at $3.68 a bushel; corn was 12{ cents to 20{ cents lower
with July at $2.89 a bushel; oats were 14{ cents to 27 cents lower
with July at $2.66 a bushel; soybeans were 38 cents to 66 cents
lower with July at $8.58 a bushel.
</TEXT>
