<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 0.4 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production rose to 1.841 million tons in
the week ended July 9, an increase of 0.4 percent from the previous
week's 1.834 million tons, the American Iron and Steel Institute
reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 86.3 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 86 percent in the previous week, a
figure corrected by the institute from the previously reported
figure of 82.2 percent.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
52.764 million net tons, an increase of 21.4 percent from the
43.462 million net tons in the previous year.
   Production so far this year used 90.2 percent of capacity,
compared with 74.4 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended July 9: Northeast
Coast, 292,000; Pittsburgh, 175,000; Youngstown, 109,000; Lake
Erie, 160,000; Detroit, 155,000; Chicago, 476,000; Midwest,
172,000; Southern, 208,000; and Western, 94,000.
