<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 1657EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Coupons     07-11 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coupons,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumers Used $2.84 Billion in Coupons To Shop in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shoppers traded in $2.84 billion worth of
coupons in buying food, pharmaceuticals and other consumer goods
last year, a 6 percent increase from 1986, a marketing firm
reported Monday.
   But of the 215.2 billion coupons distributed by companies to
promote their products, more than 208 billion went unused,
according to a study by Manufacturers Coupon Control Center, which
is a subsidiary of Dun & Bradstreet Corp.
   Slightly more than 3 percent of the total, or 7.15 billion, were
redeemed, which was a fraction ahead of 1986, the report said.
   ``The lack of strong growth this year reflects a maturing
industry,'' the study said. ``After several years of innovative
marketing techniques, including using coupons to introduce new
products, couponing has achieved a level of penetration that makes
significant growth in the immediate future unlikely.''
   While the number of coupons redeemed leveled off, their average
value increased 14 percent, to 39.7 cents from 37.6 cents, the
report said.
   Since 1983, coupon distribution has grown 51 percent and last
year more than 2,000 companies used coupons to promote their
products and boost sales, the report said. During the same period,
the number of coupons redeemed grew by 29 percent.
   Newspaper inserts continued to be the most popular form of
coupon distribution in 1987, while all other media forms, except
direct mail, declined, the report said.
   Grocery coupons inside and outside product packaging tended to
be the most popular with consumers, with a 14 percent and 13
percent redemption rate, respectively, compared with other methods
of distribution.
   Grocery coupons contained in Sunday newspaper inserts were
redeemed at a 3.6 percent rate and those printed inside newspapers
averaged 2 percent, the study found.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
