<HEAD>Anheuser-Busch Announces Plans To Build Brewery In Cartersville</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARTERSVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anheuser-Busch Companies Inc. said
Monday it plans to build a $300 million brewery near here that will
employ more than 450 workers upon completion.
   Chairman August A. Busch III said at a luncheon that the plan
``reflects our confidence in the future of our company, and in the
kind of leadership and business climate we have found in
Cartersville and the state of Georgia.''
   Anheuser-Busch officials said 1,000 workers will be employed at
the peak of construction of the brewery.
   Hiring of the permanent work force will begin early in 1990, and
the brewery is expected to be completed in the spring of 1992. The
brewery will employ more than 450 workers, the company said.
   The brewery will be the St. Louis-based company's 13th brewing
facility in the United States, with the capability of producing up
to 6 million barrels of beer a year. The facility will primarily
serve Georgia, Alabama and Tennessee but also will supply beer to
other Southeastern and Mid-Atlantic states.
   Anheuser-Busch and its subsidiaries recorded gross sales of more
than $9 billion in 1987. In addition to brewing, its subsidiaries
include baking and frozen food products, container manufacturing,
family entertainment and the St. Louis Cardinals baseball team.
