<HEAD>Discount Retailer Closes 35 Stores in Seven States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NITRO, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially troubled Heck's Inc. said
Thursday it would close 35 of its 120 discount department stores as
part of a federal bankruptcy court reorganization plan.
   Company spokesman Bill Bragg said the affected stores were in
West Virginia, Virginia, Indiana, Kentucky, Maryland, Ohio and
Pennsylvania.
   Bragg said the stores being eliminated were closed Saturday for
inventory. He said they would reopen later this week for
liquidation sales.
   Federal Bankruptcy Judge Ronald Pearson last week gave Heck's
permission to close 40 stores.
   The company said it would eliminate 700 to 1,000 jobs by closing
the stores, which company President John Isaac said ``have
demonstrated in the past and present that they have not contributed
to the company.
   A disclosure form filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission earlier this year said Heck's, which has lost $94.5
million since December 1983, had closed 53 stores since December
1986, not counting the 35 closings announced Thursday.
   The Nitro-based chain had a high of 166 stores in 1985.
