<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EasternPassengers     07-11 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Passengers,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passenger Decline Reported for June</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines on Monday reported a 15.7 decline
in June passenger traffic in what the company called a reflection
of the continued ``downsizing'' of the financially pressed carrier.
   Revenue passenger miles _ the amount of miles flown by paying
passengers _ were down 18.6 percent for the first six months of
1988 compared to the first half of 1987.
   Spokeswoman Paula Musto noted that available seat miles in June
dropped 14.1 percent, while capacity from January through June was
off 13.5 percent over last year.
   ``There's no question it's part of a trend. Eastern has been
downsized,'' she said. ``Of course, you would like to have the
airline grow.''
   The company, which wants to cut labor costs by some 30 percent,
blames union intransigence as a major reason for cutting back on
its flights.
   The June figures were 2.53 billion revenue passenger miles
compared with 3.00 billion a year ago, on capacity of 3.98 billion
available seat miles this year and 4.63 billion in June 1987.
   Six-month traffic this year was 15.64 billion revenue passenger
miles, down from 19.20 billion the year before, while capacity was
25.44 billion available seat miles against 29.40 billion.
   Eastern lost $241 million last year and reportedly is losing $1
million a day.
   Meanwhile, the company took out full-page newspaper ads Monday
in Miami, New York, Washington, Boston, Atlanta and Philadelphia
calling attention to last week's management-labor agreements to
improve communications and discussion of safety concerns.
   The ad carried the heading, ``Hope for a breakthrough.''
   ``Given the stiff financial challenges facing the company, it's
clear that a successful future depends on the quick resolution of
our labor contract negotiations over economic issues _ and anything
that improves the environment between management and labor can only
help in these ongoing efforts,'' said the ad, the latest in a
series of full-page advertisements taken out by both sides.
</TEXT>
