<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp Bjt   07-11 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, Bjt,0902</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Dive To 5-Week Low On Rain Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices tumbled to their lowest levels in more
than five weeks Monday as weekend rains in the parched Midwest
prompted a third straight day of plummeting grain prices on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Trading on other commodities exchanges also featured extreme
price movements. Cattle futures soared while most pork futures were
sharply lower; sugar took a hard hit; platinum plunged its daily
limit, leading other precious metals down; energy futures sank; and
stock-index futures advanced.
   In Chicago, prices on most corn, oat and soybean contracts fell
their daily limits within minutes of the opening bell. But the
contracts for July delivery, on which the limits have been removed
pending their July 20 expiration, continued to trade _ generally
lower.
   July soybeans dropped 66 cents a bushel to $8.58, the lowest
settlement price for that contract since June 3. Corn for July
delivery dropped 21\ cents to $2.88\ a bushel, the lowest level
since June 15.
   Weekend showers brought fairly widespread relief to Midwestern
croplands, easing fears of drastic yield reductions and spurring
profit-taking in the trading pits, analysts said. Forecasts for
more rain in the Corn Belt later this week forced further
reductions in the market's estimate of prospective grain values.
   Oat futures prices reached a record $3.94 a bushel on June 28.
Corn for near-month delivery hit $3.59 a bushel on July 5.
   But experts say soybeans, which have fallen about 22 percent
since reaching a 15-year high of $10.99{ on June 23, still could
rally beyond that point.
   ``Soybeans generally go through the major pod-setting stage from
the end of July through August,'' said Cathy Leow, an analyst with
Thomson McKinnons Securities in New York. ``We did not get enough
rain to bring the crop back and basically we're still in a weather
market.''
   ``It all depends on the weather,'' agreed Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``Unless the weather goes
back to its previous very hot and dry pattern over a wide area,
we're not going to go back up.
   ``But if the weather goes back to hot and dry, and that persists
for a week or 10 days, we will go back up again,'' he said. ``One
rain does not make a crop.''
   In a 6-to-10-day outlook issued after the close, the National
Weather Service predicted temperatures and rainfall closer to
normal in the Midwest for the first half of next week.
   Cautious trading was expected Tuesday ahead of an Agriculture
Department report on planted-acreage totals and revised
supply-demand projections.
   Wheat settled 16} cents to 19} cents lower with July at $3.68 a
bushel; corn was 13 cents to 21\ cents lower with July at $2.88\ a
bushel; oats were 15 cents to 27 cents lower with July at $2.66 a
bushel; soybeans were 44 cents to 66 cents lower with July at $8.58
a bushel.
   Cattle for near-month delivery surged the 1.50-cents-a pound
limit on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in reaction to lower grain
prices and strong packer demand, said Charlie Richardson, an
analyst in Denver with Lind-Waldock & Co.
   Near-month cattle futures had fallen in recent weeks as grain
prices rose, reflecting widespread producer selling of cattle due
to high feed prices. But Richardson said many traders believe
cattle futures have bottomed out.
   Pork futures were down sharply to limit-down due to concerns
about the nation's large hog herd, he said.
   Live cattle were .30 cent to 1.50 cents higher with August at
66.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .60 cent to 1.50 cents
higher with August at 76.02 cents a pound; hogs were 1.50 cents
lower to .10 cent higher with July at 45.47 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.40 cents lower to .40 cent higher with July at
32.70 cents a pound.
   Sugar futures fell in sympathy with soybeans on New York's
Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange, where the October contract settled
.54 cent lower at 13.39 cents a pound.
   Platinum sank its $25 limit on the New York Mercantile Exchange
in reaction to lower grains, a stronger dollar and an apparent
easing of racial tensions in South Africa, said Bernard Savakl,
metals analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York. The October
contract settled at $552.30 a troy ounce.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $4.50 to $4.60
lower with August at $436.40 a troy ounce; silver was 6.3 cents to
6.7 cents lower with July at $6.937 a troy ounce.
   Near-month crude oil prices tumbled 68 cents a barrel on the
Nymex to the lowest close since late 1986, hurt by a selloff that
traders blamed on too much supply and renewed skepticism about
OPEC's ability to restrain production.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 67 cents to 73 cents
lower with August at $14.78 a barrel; heating oil was 1.97 cents to
2.06 cents lower with August at 41.33 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.04 cents to 1.99 cents lower with August at 52.13
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures gained on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for September delivery of the Standard & Poor's
500 index settled .90 point higher at 272.45.
</TEXT>
