<FILEID>AP-NR-07-11-88 2004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-CPC     07-11 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-CPC,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CPC's Profit Up 45 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD CLIFFS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CPC International Inc. said its
profit jumped 45 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier,
boosted in part by growth in its consumer food and corn refining
operations.
   The food conglomerate said its second-quarter profit rose to $72
million, or 91 cents a share, from $49.8 million, or 61 cents a
share, in the second quarter of 1987.
   The earnings gain occurred despite a decline in second-quarter
revenue, to $1.23 billion from $1.32 billion a year earlier.
   In the first six months of the year, CPC earned $130 million, or
$1.64 a share, up from $92.5 million, or $1.13 a share, in the same
period last year. Revenue for the six-month period fell to $2.31
billion from $2.52 billion in 1987.
   The figures do not reflect a special gain of $126 million from a
restructuring last year that included the sale of European
operations and interests in Asian companies.
   The strength of European currencies against the dollar, a lower
debt burden and lower U.S. tax rate contributed to the
second-quarter earnings performance, said Chairman James R. Eiszner.
   ``For the year 1988 we now expect that CPC's earnings per share
will show an increase of 30 percent or more, excluding the special
gain in 1987,'' Eiszner said.
   The drought gripping the nation's Farm Belt probably will not
have a significant impact on earnings because more than half of
CPC's revenue comes from operations in 47 foreign countries, he
said.
   The company's brands include Hellmann's mayonnaise, Mazola corn
oil and margarine, Skippy peanut butter, Thomas' English muffins,
Arnold breads, Mueller's pasta products, Karo and Golden Griddle
syrups, and Knorr soups and sauces.
</TEXT>
