<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MGMSale 1stLd-Writethru   07-11 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MGM Sale, 1st Ld-Writethru,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MGM Split Off from MGM-UA in $400 Million Corporate Shuffle</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA6</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, The transaction ... to RESTORE first
reference to Barris Industries Inc. Picks up 8th graf pvs, MGM will
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $400 million split of Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer
studios from MGM-UA Communications Inc. may not be financier Kirk
Kerkorian's last shuffle involving the two big Hollywood names,
MGM-UA's president indicated Monday.
   ``We're still considering further transactions,'' said Stephen
Silbert, president and chief operating officer of MGM-UA, which
announced Monday it would spin off its MGM unit.
   Kerkorian, who controls 82 percent of MGM-UA, will end up with
at least 57 percent of the new MGM and 25 percent will go to a
company controlled by investor Burt Sugarman and two movie
producers, the companies said. The rest will be offered for sale to
public holders of MGM-UA stock, with Kerkorian buying anything left
over.
   MGM-UA, maker of the Oscar-winning movie ``Moonstruck'' and
popular TV series ``thirtysomething,'' has had several losing
quarters and Kerkorian acknowledged in April he was considering
selling all or part of the company.
   Silbert declined to say what the next move might be, but said
the MGM sale was ``a separate, free-standing transaction,'' and
wasn't part of some larger deal.
   Analysts suggested the deal's primary value was to raise money
to pay off MGM-UA's debt, and the company's stock closed at $15 a
share Monday, down 75 cents from Friday's close.
   The transaction recreates MGM, known for its roaring lion logo,
as a separate, publicly held producer of movies and television
shows. The company will be run by producers Jon Peters and Peter
Guber, major shareholders in Sugarman's Barris Industries Inc. and
makers of ``The Color Purple'' and ``Witches of Eastwick.''
   MGM will get a 50 percent interest in the present MGM-UA
distribution network. Barris and Kerkorian's investment vehicle,
Tracinda Corp., will each appoint half the MGM board.
   MGM-UA, to be renamed United Artists Corp., will also make
movies and TV shows, and has a library of 1,000 movies including
the ``Rocky'' and ``Pink Panther'' series.
   The transaction, expected to close in the fall, calls for
issuing approximately 50 million shares of new stock in MGM, to be
sold for $8 a share.
   Barris Industries will buy 25 percent of the new stock for $100
million.
   Present holders of MGM-UA will get rights to buy the rest, and
Kerkorian has agreed to exercise all his rights, giving him at
least 57 percent of the new MGM. Kerkorian also will buy any shares
that aren't bought by MGM-UA public shareholders, the companies
said.
   Under the arrangement, MGM-UA will sell 50 million shares of new
stock in MGM for $8 a share.
   Of the proceeds, $100 million would come back to MGM and $300
million will be used in part to pay off its $230 million bank debt,
Silbert said. He added that up to 9 million new shares will be
issued for sale to Barris in employee stock option plans.
   In Kerkorian's last shuffle of the companies in 1986, MGM's
3,000-film library, including such classics as ``Gone with the
Wind'' and ``The Wizard of Oz,'' was sold to Turner Broadcasting
Systems Inc. for $1.3 billion and the MGM studio lot was sold to
Lorimar-Telepictures Corp.
   MGM will own ``Moonstruck'' and other movies produced under the
MGM-UA label since 1986.
   Analysts said the deal allows Kerkorian to pump cash into United
Artists while retaining an interest in the well-known MGM name.
   ``Every company would probably jump at the opportunity to
recapitalize and get rid of their debt,'' said Jeffrey Logsdon of
the Crowell Weedon & Co. investment firm in Los Angeles.
   Guber and Peters joined forces with Sugarman last year by
merging their private production firm with his Barris Industries
Inc., maker of TV's ``The Newlywed Game'' and ``The Dating Game.''
   Guber said the MGM name will add luster to movies he and Peters
have in the works, including ``Batman'' starring Jack Nicholson and
``Rainman,'' with Dustin Hoffman and Tom Cruise.
   ``To have the opportunity to be part of that terrific tradition
and to be able to bring it to another level is a once in a lifetime
opportunity for us,'' Guber said.
</TEXT>
