<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dialog-Knight-Ridder 1stLd-Writethru f0253 07-11 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dialog-Knight-Ridder, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0253,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Acquiring Database Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE with Lockheed comment, other material.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. will buy Dialog Information
Services Inc., the world's biggest electronic information retrieval
company, for $353 million from Lockheed Corp., Knight-Ridder
announced Monday.
   Dialog, which had revenue of $98 million last year, has more
than 91,000 subscribers in 86 countries, and collects information
from more than 320 databases.
   ``The acquisition of Dialog represents a significant increase in
Knight-Ridder's commitment to electronic information services and
doubles the size of our rapidly expanding business information
services division,'' said James K. Batten, president and chief
executive officer of Knight-Ridder.
   David K. Ray, president of the company's business information
services division, said the Dialog acquisition would complement
existing Knight-Ridder databases.
   ``Dialog has been a pioneer in the electronic information
businesses and is an industry leader in terms of number of
customers, revenue, size, breadth and depth of database,'' Ray said.
   The sale was expected to be completed in the third quarter.
   Knight-Ridder is a national information and communications
company with operations that include broadcasting, publishing,
cable television and information services.
   Lockheed has received a number of inquiries about selling Dialog
over the past year and a half, said spokesman Hud Englehart in the
company's Calabasas, Calif., headquarters.
   ``It's a matter of having a very interested buyer making a very
attractive offer,'' Englehart said, noting the sale price was 3{
times Dialog's annual revenue.
   In 1987, Dialog had a pretax profit of $17 million on revenue of
$98.1 million.
</TEXT>
