<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CooperSale     07-11 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cooper Sale,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cooper Says Parties Are Interested in Purchase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cooper Companies Inc., which has
been trying to sell all or part of its operations for more than a
year, said Monday it has received ``indications of interest'' from
parties in buying its principal businesses.
   Cooper, which is involved in optometric, ophthalmic surgical and
diagnostic businesses, said it is working with its investment
banker, Morgan Stanley & Co., to begin discussions and negotiations
with some of the newly interested parties.
   Gene Elsbree, a Cooper spokesman, wouldn't name the companies
interested in buying Cooper's businesses but said they include
American and foreign firms.
   Cooper said it hoped to be able to propose specific deals to its
board within 30 days.
   In trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, Cooper fell 50
cents a share to $11.12{.
   Cooper said it has enough cash flow to finance the company until
the sale of one of its principal businesses, but expects to
complete within the next few weeks the previously announced $40
million of ``bridge financing'' to help until the asset sales are
completed.
   The federal government last October blocked Ciba-Geigy's
proposed $150 million purchase of Cooper's worldwide contact lens
and solutions businesses. Cooper wound up selling Ciba-Geigy only
its international solutions business for $50 million.
   Earlier this year, the government blocked Schering-Plough Corp.,
parent of contact lens maker Wesley-Jessen, from buying Cooper's
worldwide lens business for $150 million. Schering-Plough also
agreed to buy both Cooper's worldwide contact and U.S. solutions
businesses for $195 million, but the government again blocked it on
antitrust grounds.
   On May 5, Cooper announced the Federal Trade Commission's
decision and announced the company would put all its assets up for
sale.
   In its second fiscal quarter ending April 30, Cooper had a net
loss of $12 million on sales of $232 million. For its fiscal year
ending Oct. 31, 1987, Cooper posted income of $52 million on sales
of $627 million.
</TEXT>
