<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0261 07-11 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0261,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Higher, Dollar Lower In Morning Tokyo Activity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning closing, comments. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar declined against the Japanese in
Tuesday morning trading, while share prices edged higher on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar was changing hands at 132.88 yen by late morning,
down from Monday's close of 133.33 yen and from Tuesday's opening
level of 132.90 yen.
   Exchange dealers said market players were reluctant to
participate ahead of the release of Japanese trade figures for the
first half of this year, due out Tuesday afternoon in Tokyo, and
U.S. trade figures for May, to be announced Friday in Washington.
   On the stock exchange, the widely-followed Nikkei Stock Average
of 225 selected issues finished the morning session up 94.03 points
at 28.080.02 in moderate trading.
   Securities brokers attributed the gain to active buying by
institutional investors.
   ``Institutional investors sat back for the whole of last week
while the exchange rates were fluctuating,'' said Seiko Negishi, a
broker at Sanyo Securities. ``But they came back to the market this
week as they saw the yen-dollar rate settling around where it is
now.''
   Negishi also said institutional investors, who tend to be more
sensitive about the market situation abroad than do private
investors, reacted favorably to a decline in long-term interest
rates in Japan and the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
